<1ST_LINE>r a AM-BatteredWoman     08-23 0490</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Battered Woman,0501</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Reinstates Suit Against Police</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BOB EGELKO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   In a ruling that could expand the duty of
police to protect individuals, a federal appeals court Tuesday
reinstated a suit by a woman who said officers derided her
complaints about her husband's violence and failed to help her.
   Although police normally cannot be held liable for injuries to
crime victims, the 9th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals said a
``special relationship'' may be created when a victim gets a
restraining order against another person and repeatedly tells
police of continuing threats.
   Restraining orders, which generally forbid a person to approach,
contact or harass another person, have become common in domestic
violence cases.
   In this case, the restraining order may have been ``an
affirmative state commitment to protect (the woman) from her
husband's harassment,'' said Judge Betty Fletcher in the 2-1
decision.
   Judge Mary Schroder concurred with Fletcher in the decision.
   In dissent, U.S. District Judge Laughlin Waters said the
existence of a restraining order created no legal right to police
protection, at least without proof that the order had been
violated. He also asked whether the court was telling police that a
person with a restraining order was entitled to ``preferred status
in terms of police response.''
   Todd Roberts, a lawyer for police in the San Mateo County
community, declined comment on the ruling.
   The woman, Jena Balistreri, said in her suit that she was
severely beaten by her husband in 1982. She said police removed her
husband from the home in Pacifica, a suburb of San Francisco, but
refused to arrest him, did not offer medical help and were rude and
unsympathetic to her complaint. She quoted one officer as saying he
didn't blame her husband because of the way she was ``carrying on.''
   The court quoted Ms. Balistreri as saying she told police
throughout 1982 about vandalism and hundreds of harassing phone
calls, and named her now-divorced husband as the suspect.
   She got a restraining order in late 1982 prohibiting her
ex-husband from contacting or harassing her. In the following
months, she said, he crashed his car into her garage and a firebomb
was thrown through her window. Police refused to arrest her
ex-husband and suggested after the firebombing that she move or
hire a private investigator, she said.
   She said police responded to her telephone complaints with
ridicule, and refused to investigate a series of harassing phone
calls she got between 1983 and 1985.
   Ms. Balistreri's suit against the Pacifica police and Chief Al
Olsen said the failure of police to protect her violated her rights
to due process and equal protection of the law and contributed to
her physical injuries, bleeding ulcer and emotional distress.
   U.S. District Judge Samuel Conti dismissed the suit, saying
police had not violated her rights even if everything she said was
true. But the appeals court disagreed and reinstated the suit.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
