<1ST_LINE>r i AM-India-Punjab     08-23 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-India-Punjab,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Report Sikh Miltants Kill 15 in Punjab</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW DELHI, India (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Sikh extremists fatally shot 15 people,
including a member of the governing Congress Party, and wounded
three policemen in the northern state of Punjab, news reports said
Tuesday.
   The deaths raised to more than 1,750 the known number of people
killed this year by militant Sikh separatists. More than half of
the victims have been Sikhs and most of the others Hindus.
   Joginder Singh Bhatti, a municipal commissioner of Jandiala town
and a member of Prime Minister Rajiv Gandhi's Congress party, was
slain by gunmen in Jandiala, according to reports from Punjab.
   News reports from the state gave these accounts of the other
attacks:
   A truck rigged with a bomb exploded in Amritsar district,
seriously wounding three policemen.
   Three moderate Sikhs were killed by extremists in the village of
Timowal near Amritsar, the Sikhs' holy city.
   A farmer and his son were slain in Amritsar district,.
   In adjoining Gurdaspur district a woman and three men were
killed.
   A Hindu girl was killed and robbed of her money and jewelry.
   The bodies of four Sikh youths believed to have been killed late
Monday were found by police near the village of Mamanke in Amritsar
district.
   Sikhs make up less than 2 percent of India's population of 800
million but form a majority in Punjab state. Militants, claiming
discrimination by the Hindu majority, have been fighting for a
separate state in the Punjab since 1982.
   Officials say at least 4,500 people have been killed in the
Punjab-related violence during the past six years.
</TEXT>
