<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2356EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-China-Corruption     08-23 0254</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-China-Corruption,0262</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Unable To Pay Bribes Needed To Land Job, Man Commits Suicide</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEIJING (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Chinese army veteran committed suicide because
he was unable to pay the bribes needed to obtain a good job, an
official daily reported today.
   Wang Zhilong, who was looking for civilian work after 20 years
in the army, jumped to his death on July 27 from the fifth floor of
a hospital in central China's Luoyang City, the China Daily said.
   Wang had been hospitalized after trying to kill himself three
days earlier by touching electric wires.
   The report said Wang became depressed after a local Communist
Party official, Li Shiyi, demanded a color TV, a bicycle and
name-brand cigarettes and liquor as preconditions for arranging a
job.
   It said Wang spent his life savings of $810, more than double a
worker's annual salary, on the gifts, but was still unable to
satisfy the corrupt official.
   It said Wang's suicide surprised local party and government
officials and a joint team was formed to investigate the death and
punish those responsible.
   The ruling Communist Party in recent months has issued stern
warnings about official corruption, which has become increasingly
serious as the nation's market-oriented economic reforms loosen
state controls.
   Influence-peddling, always a part of doing business in China,
has been joined by widespread black marketeering, hoarding,
extortion and graft.
   The daily said that in Henan province, where Luoyang is located,
prosecutors handled 589 corruption cases involving 246 government
employees in the first six months of this year.
</TEXT>
