<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0010EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BoxOffice     08-23 0470</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Box Office,0487</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>`Nightmare' No. 1 in Box Office Revenues</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD DE ATLEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOLLYWOOD (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The fourth visit by Freddy of ``Nightmare On
Elm Street'' was worth nearly $13 million, while the average
box-office take by ``The Last Temptation of Christ'' was cut nearly
in half as it doubled its distribution.
   ``Nightmare On Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' earned $12.8
million last weekend for New Line films, the biggest opening this
summer by a movie not distributed by a large studio.
   No. 2 was ``Young Guns'' with $5 million.
   The only other debut movie to make the top 10 last weekend was
``Married To The Mob,'' in seventh place with $3.2 million.
   ``The Last Temptation,'' which was not among the top 10 because
of its limited distribution, doubled its screens to 18 in the
United States and Canada. But its take as the box office softened
with $476,623, or $26,459 per theater. That compared to last week's
$44,579 per screen for a three-day total of $401,211 on nine
screens.
   In third place last week was ``Die Hard,'' with $4.5 million,
followed by ``A Fish Called Wanda'' with $4.4 million; ``Cocktail''
in fifth place with $4 million and ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit'' in
sixth place with $3.6 million.
   ``Married To The Mob,'' starring Michelle Pfeiffer as a woman
widowed after her hit-man husband is done in by his boss, was next.
   At No. 8 was ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream'' with $2.7
million, followed by ``Coming To America'' with $2.5 million and
``Midnight Run'' in the 10th with $2.1 million.
   Here are the top films for the weekend as tallied by Exhibitor
Relations, with distributor, weekend gross, number of theater
screens, average per screen, total gross and number of weeks in
release.
   1. ``Nightmare On Elm Street 4: The Dream Master,'' New Line,
$12.8 million, 1,765 screens, $7,271 per screen, $12.8 million, one
week.
   2. ``Young Guns,'' 20th Century Fox, $5 million, 1,416 screens,
$3,558 per screen, $16.3 million, two weeks.
   3. ``Die Hard,'' 20th Century Fox, $4.5 million, 1,629 screens,
$2,777 per screen, $46 million, six weeks.
   4. ``A Fish Called Wanda,'' MGM-UA, $4.4 million, 1,215 screens,
$3,627 per screen, $24.3 million, six weeks.
   5. ``Cocktail,'' Disney, $4 million, 1,462 screens, $2,739 per
screen, $46.2 million, four weeks.
   6. ``Who Framed Roger Rabbit,'' Disney, $3.6 million, 1,598
screens, $2,293 per screen, $119.3 million, nine weeks.
   7. ``Married To The Mob,'' Orion, $3.2 million, 824 screens,
$3,921 per screen, $3.2 million, one week.
   8. ``Tucker: The Man and His Dream,'' Paramount, $2.7 million,
720 screens, $3,864 per screen, $8.1 million, two weeks.
   9. ``Coming To America,'' Paramount, $2.5 million, 1,273
screens, $1,973 per screen, $111.1 million, eight weeks.
   10. ``Midnight Run,'' Universal, $2.1 million, 1,006 screens,
$2,095 per screen, $29 million, five weeks.
</TEXT>
