<1ST_LINE>r a PM-RoosterFlap     08-23 0299</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Rooster Flap,0310</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Man Convicted Of Anti-Rooster Ordinance</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SANTA ANA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Rudely awakened neighbors crowing about
Jose Sanchez's vocal 15-pound rooster won a court victory when the
owner was convicted of illegally harboring the animal in a
residential area.
   Sanchez may now find himself in jail because of the pet Rhode
Island Red rooster named Travis, who ruffled too many feathers with
his predawn wakeup calls in the tranquil neighborhood 35 miles east
of Los Angeles.
   Sanchez, 26, who fought the city over its anti-rooster law for
two years was convicted Monday on four misdemeanor counts. He could
be ordered to serve six months in jail and pay a $1,000 fine for
each count.
   Sentencing is scheduled Sept. 23.
   Deputy City Attorney Frank Rhemrev said he doubts the maximum
sentence will be assessed.
   ``Can you believe it? I might end up in county jail with
burglars and thieves. And I'll be there because of a chicken,''
Sanchez said before Monday's decision.
   Many people have told Sanchez he shouldn't risk going up the
river for a rooster, but he remained adamant.
   ``You can get warm and cuddly about a rooster just like you can
about a cat or a dog,'' Sanchez said. ``Travis is real friendly...
He's a companion, just like any other pet.
   ``He just happens to be a chicken,'' he said of the 7-year-old
bird.
   Rhemrev said neighbors began complaining about the rooster calls
in 1986.
   Sanchez said he thinks the 1984 law banning roosters, but not
hens, is wrong, and vowed to ``go all the way'' for his bird, even
if it means jail.
   The pet owner said because Travis was 3 years old and living in
his backyard when the law was passed, the rooster should be the
beneficiary of a grandfather clause.
</TEXT>
