<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0049EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r p PM-GOPTicket Bjt   08-23 0934</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-GOP Ticket, Bjt,920</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>WASHINGTON TODAY: Bush's First Big Choice Causing Him Trouble</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP News Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WALTER R. MEARS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Special Correspondent</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   One man, one vote, one vice presidential
candidate, and George Bush has chosen himself a problem _ a
distraction from the themes of his Republican campaign for the
White House.
   It may be unfair. It may be, as Bush supporters contend, a
creation of the news media. But the Dan Quayle issue is undeniably
a campaign detour just when the Republicans wanted to build on the
sendoff of their national convention pageantry.
   That's a problem for Bush and his strategists, and for Sen.
Quayle, who can hardly be enjoying his new line of work very much.
It has brought him denunciations and ridicule. He is in fact an
intelligent man who works diligently, if selectively, on his
legislative issues. He got less than a day to celebrate his sudden
leap from junior senator to vice presidential nominee. Then the
nagging, persistent questions about his military service and now
his educational record emerged to divert the GOP running mates from
their chosen agenda.
   Instead of taking the offense coming out of New Orleans, Bush
and Quayle find themselves snarled in a damage control operation.
The question is whether and when it will end.
   According to a friend of the vice president, one who watched him
make his vice presidential selection, Bush chose Quayle on his own,
with minimal input from his advisers.
   James A. Baker III, who resigned as secretary of the treasury to
run the Bush campaign, was said to have been opposed to the
selection of Quayle before it was announced. He has since been a
loyal supporter, although hardly a cheerleader.
   Quayle, 41, was supposed to be the fresh face, the man who would
symbolize the Republican future, a young conservative with no
political baggage. He was picked to offer a positive comparison to
the Democratic nominee, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, 67, who has
his own political scars, notably the admitted blunder of setting up
a high-priced breakfast club at which lobbyist-donors would dine
with the chairman of the Senate Finance Committee. Bentsen called
that off after his fund-raising plan was disclosed.
   His refunds and apology quashed the issue. By the time Gov.
Michael Dukakis, the Democratic presidential nominee, picked him
for the ticket, it was history.
   Not so with Quayle, who was fresh, new business in New Orleans
when he began by fumbling early questions about the way he got into
the Indiana National Guard in 1969. His student deferment was
expiring and the Guard was a sought-after alternative to the draft
and the likelihood of duty in the Vietnam War. The question still
pending is whether the influence of his newspaper-owning family got
him a Guard slot or whether, as Quayle insists, the unit he joined
was seeking recruits for vacancies.
   Quayle joined the Guard when his student deferment was about to
lapse with his graduation from college.
   Dukakis was draft-deferred as a student during the Korean war.
He volunteered for the draft prior to his graduation in 1955 and
served just under two years in the Army.
   He said the Quayle matter would be an election issue. ``How we
make our decisions, how we make the presidential selections, who we
select . . . whether or not that person should be a heartbeat away
from the presidency, obviously will be an issue,'' he said.
   Bush said the matter should subside. After all, not many people
vote on the basis of vice presidential nominations. The contest is
between two men, the presidential nominees.
   After a weekend of campaigning _ defensively _ with Bush, Quayle
went back to Washington for some basic training on national
politics. Bush said his running mate had to get his staff, schedule
and personal affairs organized. ``This hit him out of a clear, blue
sky,'' Bush said.
   That's part of the problem.
   A system that subjects presidential candidates to almost
inhumane scrutiny doesn't do a thing to check out the vice
presidential nominees. One man, the nominee, gets to pick the vice
presidential half of the ticket, by fiat.
   To compound the problem, presidential candidates act as though
choosing a running mate is a piece of business that has to be left
for the last minute.
   Bush has known since late last winter, when his presidential
nomination was assured, that he would need a running mate. He even
knew the deadline: Aug. 18.
   There was time for a careful, thorough search of the field and
for close scrutiny of the people in that field. That kind of search
might have led Bush to the same conclusion _ Dan Quayle. But he
would have known the man and the record. The time and the resources
were there to avoid unpleasant surprises, for Bush and for Quayle,
who obviously didn't see anything like this in his two campaigns
for the House and two for the Senate.
   Then, too, it's just possible that in the case of the vice
presidency, the choice shouldn't be one vote by one man.
   Despite the often-repeated fact that no incumbent vice president
since Martin Van Buren in 1836 has been elected president, being
No. 2 is a very good way to become No. 1. Thirteen of the 43 men
who have served as vice president eventually have become president.
   Those are better White House odds than you'll get in any other
line of work.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Walter R. Mears, executive editor of The
Associated Press, has covered national politics since 1960.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
