<2ND_LINE>PM-BRF--Gulf Air,0132</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gulf Airline To Resume Flights to Baghdad, Tehran</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANAMA, Bahrain (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gulf Air, which stopped flying to the
capitals of Iran and Iraq when war broke out between the two
nations, plans to resume the lucrative routes, Bahrain's Gulf News
Agency reported.
   The carrier _ owned by Bahrain, Qatar, Oman and the Abu Dhabi
province of the United Arab Emirates _ stopped flights to Baghdad
and Tehran like most other airlines shortly after the war began in
September 1980.
   The Gulf News Agency said in a dispatch Monday that flight
schedules will be fixed once the U.N.-sponsored cease-fire appears
stable.
   The cease-fire took hold Saturday, but both sides have accused
the other of violations. Iran and Iraq are scheduled to start peace
talks Thursday in Geneva.
