<HEAD>Congressional Delegate Who Admits Fraud Submits Resignation</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PAGO PAGO, American Samoa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This U.S. territory's
congressional delegate is resigning after he admitted conspiring to
defraud the government of more than $130,000, the governor said
Monday.
   Gov. A.P. Lutali said he had accepted Delegate Fofo I.F. Sunia's
resignation, which takes effect Sept. 6.
   Sunia, a Democrat, pleaded guilty Aug. 3 in Washington to
charges of operating a payroll-padding scheme. He is scheduled to
be sentenced on Oct. 4.
   The U.S. attorney's office accused Sunia and his chief aide,
Matthew K. Iuli, of using money obtained from the scheme to
entertain constituents, pay election and campaign expenses and make
house and car loan payments.
   Sunia announced his resignation in a one-sentence letter to
Lutali that contained no explanation. The date he chose, however,
is one day before the House Ethics Committee is scheduled to
consider action against him.
   Lutali said a special election to fill Sunia's seat would be too
costly, and instead the winner of the November election will take
office immediately instead of in January.
