<1ST_LINE>r p PM-PresidentialPolls     08-23 0600</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Presidential Polls,590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CBS Poll: Voters Question Quayle, but GOP is Up</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GARY LANGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Many voters harbor doubts about Sen. Dan Quayle
of Indiana as the GOP vice presidential nominee, although the
Republican ticket emerged from its national convention with a
narrow lead, a new poll has found.
   George Bush and Quayle led Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis
and his running mate, Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas, by 46 percent to
40 percent in the CBS News poll of 1,221 registered voters across
the country.
   The survey, released Monday, was the first done entirely after
the Republican convention in New Orleans, which ended Thursday with
a well-received acceptance speech by Bush, and it found improvement
in ratings of his leadership and popularity.
   But half the respondents did not believe the 41-year-old Quayle
has the experience to be a good president, and 28 percent were
unsure. Thirty-nine percent wished Bush had chosen someone else.
   Quayle has faced questions about whether he used his wealthy
family's connections to get into the National Guard and avoid the
draft and combat in the Vietnam War. In the poll, 40 percent said
phone calls made to the Guard on his behalf represented ``an unfair
attempt'' to ease his admission; 40 percent said such calls were
acceptable and 20 percent were unsure.
   Among the seven in 10 who had heard of the issue, 48 percent
said they believed Quayle had joined the Guard to avoid the draft.
Just 29 percent thought that was not his main reason, and 22
percent said they didn't know.
   Also among those who had heard about it, just 50 percent
believed Quayle was telling the truth about the National Guard
issue, while 26 percent said he was not and 24 percent didn't know.
   Quayle also did not do well in comparison to Bentsen: Forty-one
percent said Bentsen would be a better vice president, to 28
percent for Quayle. The rest didn't know.
   Still, support was up for the Republican ticket as a whole.
Dukakis, enjoying his own convention bounce, had led by 17 points
in a CBS News-New York Times poll early this month.
   The 6-point spread in the new poll was just within its margin of
error of plus or minus three percentage points. But other polls
have found Bush gaining, allowing the conclusion that the
Republicans lead slightly. In a Gallup poll this weekend, they led
by 9 percentage points, 51-42.
   Bush was expected to gain in popularity following the publicity
from his convention, just as Dukakis did after the Democratic
convention. Such bounces in the polls generally settle as the
campaign progresses.
   On Bush's personal ratings, 51 percent said they had faith in
his ability to deal wisely with an international crisis, while 37
percent said they would be uneasy. His rating on this question
earlier this month was the opposite.
   Bush was rated favorably by 39 percent and unfavorably by 25
percent in the new survey, much improved from his
favorable-unfavorable rating of 27-33 in the previous poll.
   Dukakis did worse on the confidence measure, with 53 percent
uneasy about him in a crisis, 29 percent confident. And his
favorable-unfavorable rating dropped from 38-19 before the GOP
convention to 32-25 after it.
   Efforts by Republicans at the convention to paint Dukakis as a
liberal had little effect: 34 percent saw him as a liberal,
compared with 35 percent in the earlier poll. But 34 percent said
Dukakis was more likely than Bush to raise taxes, up from 27
percent in early August.
   The poll was conducted Friday through Sunday.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
