<1ST_LINE>r w PM-Obit-Mologne     08-23 0279</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Obit-Mologne,270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Commander of Walter Reed Army Medical Center Dead At 56</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Maj. Gen. Lewis Apsey Mologne, who was twice
awarded the Distinguished Service Medal for his leadership as
commander of Walter Reed Army Medical Center, has died of cancer.
He was 56.
   Mologne, an army physician who in 1983 became commander of
Walter Reed, the military's central hospital in Washington, retired
from the military Aug. 1 and died Monday.
   He took over at a time when Walter Reed and the military medical
establishment had been plagued by revelations about incompetent
physicians, inaccuracies in drug testing, the theft of drugs and
unpaid bills. Three commanders had left within five years.
   Mologne was credited with restoring morale as he instituted new
procurement systems, streamlined paperwork, worked with city police
on the drug theft problem and reorganized the military's urinalysis
laboratory at Fort Meade in Maryland.
   Born in Mount Pleasant, Pa., Mologne was graduated from the U.S.
Military Academy at West Point, N.Y., and was commissioned in the
Army Corps of Engineers. He also was graduated from the Airborne
School at Fort Benning, Ga.
   He was a company commander in Korea before resigning from the
Army to attend medical school at the University of Pittsburgh. He
was commissioned in the Army Medical Corps after graduation and
later worked as a surgeon, administrator and medical professor.
   Mologne's posts included chief surgeon and deputy commander at
Fitzsimons Army Medical Center in Colorado and head of the Army
Medical Command in South Korea. He was chief of medical corps
affairs and professional services director in the U.S. Surgeon
General's office from 1982 until he became commander at Walter Reed.
</TEXT>
