<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0245EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Salvador     08-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Salvador,0368</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Leftist Coalition to Run in 1989 Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DOUGLAS GRANT MINE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SAN SALVADOR, El Salvador (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A coalition of three leftist
parties whose leaders are linked to the Marxist-led guerrilla
movement say they will participate in elections for the first time
since the civil war began in 1979.
   The Democratic Convergence, a coalition of three left-of-center
parties, announced Monday that it will choose its candidates in the
coming weeks for the March presidential elections.
   The coalition includes the National Revolutionary Movement, the
Popular Social Christian Movement and the Social Democratic Party.
   In the past, the Christian Democratic government of President
Jose Napoleon Duarte invited leftist political leaders to
participate in elections, but asked the guerrillas to lay down
their arms.
   Leftist parties have boycotted previous elections, saying their
security could not be guaranteed and elections formed part of a
U.S.-directed counterinsurgency plan.
   Guillermo Ungo, leader of the National Revolutionary Movement,
and Ruben Zamora, chief of the Popular Social Christian Movement,
are the president and vice-president of the Democratic
Revolutionary Front.
   The front forms a civilian-military alliance with the Farabundo
Marti National Liberation Front, the guerrilla army battling the
U.S.-backed government.
   An estimated 65,000 people, mostly civilians, have died in the
civil war.
   Leftist civilian politicians recently said guerrilla leaders
understand their decision to take part in the March elections.
   ``Our objective in the electoral process is the promotion of a
political and negotiated solution to the armed conflict as an
indispensable condition for fulfilling the Salvadoran people's most
pressing demands,'' a communique issued by the coalition said.
   ``We are convinced that our participation will bind and mobilize
people around the objectives of social justice, democracy, national
independence and peace,'' the statement said.
   The election likely will be a close contest between El
Salvador's two dominant parties, the incumbent Christian Democrats
and the conservative Republican Nationalist Alliance.
   The rightist alliance, known as Arena, gained control of the
legislature and two-thirds of the country's municipal governments
in elections held in March.
   Duarte, barred by the constitution from another term as
president , has been diagnosed as having terminal liver cancer.
</TEXT>
