<2ND_LINE>PM-Political Briefs,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Playboy Coy About Parkinson's `New Comments' On Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former lobbyist Paula Parkinson is back in the
limelight and in Playboy magazine, offering new details about a
1980 vacation when she briefly shared a cottage with Republican
vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle and two other congressmen.
   Jonathan Black, managing editor of Playboy, said Monday that
Parkinson's ``new comments'' about events at the Florida cottage
eight years ago would appear in text accompanying a ``Women of
Washington'' pictorial in the November issue of the magazine.
Parkinson will appear nude in the pictorial.
   Black said the article was originally written long before Quayle
was named as Vice President George Bush's running mate, but that
``new material'' from Parkinson was inserted last week.
   Black declined to answer further questions about the article or
its contents. The magazine is scheduled to be on the newsstands
Oct. 1.
   Parkinson first appeared nude in the magazine in 1980, several
months after being identified as the woman who shared a cottage
with Quayle and former Reps. Tom Railsback of Illinois and Thomas
B. Evans of Delaware.
   Quayle never was accused of intimacy with her, and a Justice
Department investigation of Parkinson's relationships with members
of Congress found no impropriety.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Ford Says He Would Have Tried To Help Son Enter Guard</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MADISON, Wis. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former President Gerald Ford says he would
have called on an influential friend to get his son into the
National Guard if confronted with a situation like that Republican
vice presidential nominee Dan Quayle faced in 1969.
   ``Any father who wouldn't, in my judgment, would be neglecting
his parental responsibility,'' Ford said at a press conference
Monday.
   Ford said some reporters have been ``bloodthirsty'' in
questioning the military record of Quayle since GOP presidential
nominee George Bush named the Indiana senator as his running mate.
   ``Well, I think I would have called a friend,'' Ford said.
   Quayle has said he sought service in the Guard so he could
attend law school.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Vet Counselors Ordered to Avoid Interviews on Quayle</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Federal employees who counsel Vietnam War
veterans have been ordered not to give media interviews on
Republican vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle's National Guard
service.
   One angry counselor called the order a violation of his right to
speak out. But the official who issued the directive in seven
western states said he was merely reinforcing a law that bars
government employees from getting involved in politics.
   The order was issued Friday by Farrell Udell, associate regional
manager for the western region of the Veterans Administration
readjustment counseling service.
   ``Because we're a government organization, we do not care to
comment on political issues,'' Udell said in a telephone interview
from his San Francisco office.
   David Culmer, a counselor in the agency's office in the Westwood
neighborhood of Los Angeles, said, ``I don't feel that federal
employees should be censored or muzzled or not allowed to speak
their opinion. I don't think it's appropriate.''
   Quayle, the Indiana senator tabbed by Vice President George Bush
as his running mate, has faced questions about whether he used his
family's influence to get into the National Guard in 1969 and so
avoid being drafted into combat in the Vietnam War.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Poll Shows Dukakis Leading in Kentucky</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democrat Michael Dukakis led Republican
George Bush by 12 percentage points in the most recent poll of
registered voters in Kentucky, although the undecided block
remained large.
   The poll, released Monday by Wilkerson & Associates, showed that
46 percent of the likely voters supported Dukakis, 34 percent
backed Bush and 20 percent were undecided about the presidential
race.
   The telephone poll involved 1,008 registered voters statewide
who said they intended to vote in November and was conducted
between July 26 and Aug. 11, prior to last week's Republican
National Convention in New Orleans and the addition of Sen. Dan
Quayle of Indiana to the GOP ticket.
   The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 3 percentage
points.
</TEXT>
<HEAD>___</HEAD>
<HEAD>Bush Leading Dukakis In Mississippi</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Vice President George Bush, buoyed by the
attention on the Republican National Convention in New Orleans last
week, held a comfortable lead over Democratic contender Mike
Dukakis among state voters according to a recent poll.
   In the poll, commissioned by Jackson radio station WJNT and
conducted by Rick Knox and Associates of Jackson Aug. 19-20, 52
percent indicated they will vote for Bush while 36 percent said
they planned to vote for Democratic nominee Michael Dukakis.
   Another 9 percent were undecided and 3 percent favored other
candidates.
   Pollsters contacted 1,000 registered state voters statewide, 200
at random from each of the state's five congressional districts.
The poll has a margin of error of plus or minus 5 percentage points.
</TEXT>
