<1ST_LINE>r a PM-LeftoverMoney     08-23 0423</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Leftover Money,0436</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Government Closer to Getting $100,000 Left by Woman</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOUISVILLE, Ky. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Uncle Sam will get about $100,000 of the
money left by a widow who wanted her estate used to reduce the
national debt, but the bequest is only enough to offset the
gargantuan debt for 21 seconds.
   The federal government and Kentucky recently reached an
agreement on the distribution of the money after a legal battle of
more than four years over whether the state was entitled to
inheritance taxes.
   Under the agreement, the state will get $30,000, and the U.S.
Bureau of Public Debt will get the $100,000 or so remaining after
bequests to relatives.
   Minnie Vogel, who had no children, died in May 1984 at age 85.
She left $35,000 of her $188,000 estate to seven nieces and nephews.
   ``All the rest ... I bequeath and devise to my beloved country,
the United States of America, to be used to reduce the national
debt,'' Ms. Vogel said in her will. ``The reason for this
distribution ... is because of the deep love I have for America and
I wish to show my appreciation and love in helping my country in
this small way.''
   The national debt is $2.5 trillion, and grows an estimated
$100,000 every 21 seconds.
   The agreement was recently approved by Jefferson Circuit Judge
Edmund P. Karem. The parties are awaiting final approval from
Jefferson District Probate Court, said Assistant U.S. Attorney
Michael F. Spalding.
   Spalding said he is pleased the case seems about to be resolved
but is not sure why it took four years.
   In an effort to resolve the issue, the federal government agreed
to abide by Kentucky law and pay the inheritance tax. But Ms.
Vogel's lawyer sued, saying he did not think it was Ms. Vogel's
intent that part of her money should go to the state.
   ``We felt her intent was to give it all to the federal
government,'' said Sheldon Isaacs, the lawyer who prepared the will
and is administering the estate.
   All parties acknowledged they lacked a clear precedent.
   David Liebschutz, a spokesman for the Bureau of Public Debt,
said he could recall just one donation of similar size: the
$100,000 given annually by a retired Ohio industrialist who also
sends the bureau his monthly Social Security checks.
   Liebschutz said few people will their money to the government.
   The fund to reduce the public debt receives about $500,000 a
year in donations, he said. Most contributions from individuals
come as checks for $10 or $20.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
