<1ST_LINE>r a PM-SourceIdentification     08-23 0328</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Source Identification,0336</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspapers Ask Judge To Throw Out $700,000 Award</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MINNEAPOLIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Lawyers for two newspapers have asked a judge
to throw out a $700,000 jury award to a public relations man who
sued the papers for breaking a promise not to print his name as the
source of a news story.
   The lawyers for the St. Paul Pioneer Press Dispatch and
Minneapolis-based Star Tribune argued Monday that Hennepin County
District Court Judge Franklin Knoll should have instructed the jury
to consider whether the First Amendment gives newspapers a right to
breach a contract.
   Knoll said he will issue a ruling later on the newspapers'
request that he reverse the jury verdict or grant a new trial.
   The jury decided that the newspapers engaged in
misrepresentation when reporters for both papers promised Dan Cohen
that they would not identify him as a source. Editors later
overruled the reporters and published Cohen's name.
   The jury last month found misrepresentation and awarded Cohen
$500,000 in punitive damages and $200,000 in compensatory damages.
   Star Tribune lawyer James Fitzmaurice argued Monday that the
jury had no grounds for its ruling. He said Cohen should have been
required to show the newspapers acted with ``malice'' in breaking
their oral agreements, a standard used in libel cases.
   But the judge questioned whether the First Amendment allows
newspapers to break contracts.
   ``Then I guess the point is that no one should make a contract
with you because they can't be assured your client won't break
it,'' the judge told Fitzmaurice.
   Cohen leaked court documents to reporters during the 1982
gubernatorial campaign that revealed that Marlene Johnson, who was
the successful candidate for lieutenant governor, had a shoplifting
record.
   Cohen, who worked for rival candidate Wheelock Whitney, provided
the information on the condition that he not be identified. Editors
at the newspapers testified that they broke the promise because the
public had a right to know the information came from the Whitney
campaign.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
