<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0406EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Japan-Defense     08-23 0495</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Defense,0508</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Japan Vows To Continue Defense Buildup</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN K. PAULSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Soviet Union has not stopped its military
buildup in the Far East and the U.S. economy is in comparative
decline, so Japan will continue its five-year defense expansion
program, the Defense Agency said today.
   The decision is likely to keep Japan's military spending above 1
percent of its gross national product, a self-imposed ceiling
abandoned last year by the government that had been observed since
1976.
   The budget for defense-related expenses for the current fiscal
year is $28 billion, an estimated 1.013 percent of Japan's GNP.
   In its annual report on defense, the government said ``the
Soviet Union has adopted a military buildup as one of its top
priorities and as a result has increased its strength enough to
confront the U.S. in the spheres of both nuclear and conventional
warfare.''
   The report said that although the United States continues to
play a major role in international politics, ``no one can deny that
its position has recently been declining comparatively in the
economic field.
   ``Under these circumstances, Japan will be increasingly expected
to play a role commensurate with its position as the second-largest
economic power among free world nations next to the United
States,'' it said.
   The report said Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev has
emphasized peaceful intentions, but ``there is no change in the
trend of continuous military buildup of the Soviet Union as seen in
the realities of deployment of SS-24 ICBM (intercontinental
ballistic missiles), commissioning of a fourth Kiev-class aircraft
carrier and deployment of a fourth generation of fighter aircraft.''
   It said that in the Far East, the Soviet Union has begun to
build up its forces rapidly, deploying ``enormous forces'' along
the Soviet-China border.
   Japan has already begun development of a surface-to-ship missile
which will be used by its Ground Self-Defense Forces beginning this
year. It also is developing a new anti-submarine deck helicopter to
engage in anti-submarine and anti-ship warfare.
   Japan has about 180,000 authorized defense personnel. The
figures are not broken down by services.
   According to the report, the United States had 50,400 men
stationed in Japan as of Dec. 31, 1987, of whom about 2,100 were in
the Army, 7,400 in the Navy, 23,600 in the Marine Corps and 17,300
in the Air Force.
   The report said Japan should steadily improve its defense
capabilities as planned in the National Defense Program Outline, a
five-year program to beef up Japan's defenses.
   The Japanese government passed the controversial five-year
defense buildup plan in September 1985 to meet U.S. requests that
Japan shoulder more of the burden for its own defense.
   The plan calls for an annual increase of 7.9 percent in defense
spending, compared to about 6 percent in previous years.
   Defense spending is a sensitive issue in Japan, where
anti-military sentiment has been strong since the militarism of
World War II. The constitution renounces war as a sovereign right.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
