<2ND_LINE>AM-Japan-Markets,0219</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall; Dollar Posts Narrow Gain</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Stock prices fell for the second day in a row on
the Tokyo Stock Exchange Tuesday, while the dollar held its ground
against the yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues, a 130.24-point
loser the previous day, lost another 159.23 points, or 0.57
percent, to finish at 27,919.95 points. The main barometer in Tokyo
trading closed below the 28,000-point level for the first time
since Aug. 16.
   On the foreign exchange market, the dollar closed at 133.93 yen,
up only 0.05 yen from Monday's closing, after moving in a narrow
range of 133.75-134.00 yen.
   ``The decline in New York overnight led lower share prices and
thin trading here today (Tuesday). In addition, investors are
afraid of the higher interest rates worldwide and are buying
less,'' a stock analyst with a major securities firm in Tokyo said.
   In foreign exchange, the dollar opened trading at 133.75 yen,
down from Monday's close of 133.80 yen, and traded mainly between
133.75 and 133.93 yen throughout the morning. The dollar was
changing hands at 133.89 yen at midmorning.
   Foreign exchange dealers said the dollar-yen rate was expected
to remain steady, with investors seen as selling the U.S. currency
when it reaches the 134-yen level.
</TEXT>
