<2ND_LINE>PM-Israel, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0450,0618</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fierce Rioting in Gaza Strip Refugee Camps, 17 Wounded</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 14 grafs to UPDATE with leaflet issued, firebomb
threats, details; pickup 12th pvs, `No deaths ...'</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By DAN IZENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Underground leaders of the 8-month-old
Palestinian uprising today urged more attacks on Israelis and
called on Arabs to set up independent institutions in the occupied
territories.
   The calls came in a leaflet that also designated today a day of
firebomb attacks to protest Israel's deportation of 33 Arabs since
the revolt against 21 years of Israeli occupation began in the West
Bank and Gaza Strip.
   The leaflet was distributed a day after Israeli troops shot and
wounded 17 Palestinians in bloody clashes throughout Gaza. Ninety
other Arabs were injured by beatings or overcome by tear gas,
Western relief officials said.
   ``There is no going back on the achievements realized on the
path to the establishment of an independent Palestinian state on
our national soil ... The Zionists (will) be driven out of our land
so we may built on it our independent state with its capital in
Jerusalem,'' the four-page statement said.
   There is ``no sign of weariness on the part of the masses,'' the
leaflet added. ``We invite you to extend the struggle against the
occupation.''
   The leaflet, the 24th issued since the uprising began Dec. 8,
called for setting up underground classrooms, planting crops for
storage and boycotting Israeli farm products.
   It also called on Palestinians to stage four days of general
strikes over the next seven days in solidarity with deportees and
with five Palestinians killed in a fire in Tel Aviv and by Israeli
troops in a prison riot last week.
   Palestinians also were urged to defy Israel's ban on autonomous
grassroots committees, calling for ``redoubled efforts'' to build
more of them.
   It also applauded neighboring Jordan's severing earlier this
month of legal and adminstrative ties with the West Bank as ``one
of the main achievements of the uprising.''
   An army spokesman said, meanwhile, that soldiers maintained
curfews today on four refugee camps and neighborhoods where the
violence occurred in the Gaza Strip, confining about 118,000
Palestinians to their homes.
   The West Bank's largest city of Nablus and three neighboring
refugee camps, whose combined populations are about 140,000, also
were under curfew for a second straight day.
   The clashes followed a general strike, which was called to
protest the Israeli policy of confiscating propety of Arabs
refusing to pay taxes.
   The fighting became intense when the Israeli army imposed
curfews in the Jabaliya, Shati and Bureij refugee camps and parts
of Gaza City.
   Palestinians using loudspeakers at Moslem mosques called on
residents of the camps to defy the orders, and hundreds responded,
blocking roads, burning tires and stoning Israeli patrols.
   No deaths were reported in Monday's violence. At least 252 Arabs
and four Israelis have been killed in the clashes since the
uprising began in the lands Israel seized in the 1967 Middle East
war.
   In another development, Michel Sabah, the first Arab to be
appointed Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem, rejected an
invitation to meet Defense Minister Yitzhak Rabin at the Parliament
in Jerusalem, a church official said Monday.
   He told The Associated Press the refusal was in line with the
church's policy not to meet with Israeli authorities in Jerusalem.
   The Vatican does not recognize Israeli control over Jerusalem,
which was given international status under a 1947 partition plan by
the United Nations. Israel captured the Arab section of Jerusalem
in the 1967 war and later declared all of the city as the Israeli
capital.
</TEXT>
