<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Taiwan-China     08-23 0201</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Taiwan-China,0206</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Domestic Airliner Wants To Fly To China</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TAIPEI, Taiwan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Taiwanese airline has applied for
government permission to begin the first direct passenger flights
between Taiwan and China, officials reported today.
   But Yuan Sung-hsi, a Communications Ministry spokesman, told
reporters the application would be denied because the Nationalists
on Taiwan are technically still at war with the Chinese Communists,
who won a civil war on the China mainland in 1949.
   The application from Formosa Airlines, a domestic carrier,
requested permission to fly between Taiwan and the Chinese cities
of Beijing, Shanghai, Guangzhou, Shantou, Xiamen and Fuzhou,
officials said.
   An airline official, who spoke on condition of anonymity, said
the company planned to operate the service with a U.S. airline. He
declined to identify the U.S. company or provide additional details.
   The Nationalist government continues to claim it is China's
legitimate government and is opposed to any official contacts
between the rival governments. But it adopted a more lenient policy
toward China last year and Taiwanese now may visit the Chinese
mainland for reunions.
   Officials of the government's Entry and Exit Bureau say more
than 150,000 Taiwanese have already visited China via other
countries for the reunions.
</TEXT>
