<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0619EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-PeopleValerie'sSuit     08-23 0513</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People Valerie's Suit,0533</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Valerie Harper Denies She Tried to Control `Valerie' Show</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By LINDA DEUTSCH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Valerie Harper denied she tried to gain
control over the TV series ``Valerie'' before its producers fired
her for allegedly violating her contract, testifying, ``I wasn't
trying to be Genghis Khan.''
   ``I wanted to have participation, early knowledge of stories so
I would be in a partnership on the show,'' she testified Monday,
her 48th birthday.
   Ms. Harper, who was to continue testifying in Los Angeles County
Superior Court this afternoon, was called to the stand by Lorimar,
which is suing her for alleged breach of contract. She is
countersuing, contending that Lorimar wrongfully fired her a year
ago.
   Lorimar replaced Ms. Harper with Sandy Duncan and renamed the
NBC-TV show ``The Hogan Family.''
   Lorimar attorney Donald Engel on Monday sought to show that Ms.
Harper was aware of all aspects of her 1985 contract, and tried to
renegotiate it because she craved more money and total control over
``Valerie.''
   Ms. Harper denied this, saying she left business matters in the
hands of her husband, Tony Cacciotti, and left the contract to her
agent and lawyer, whose advice she later came to doubt.
   ``I'm not good with contracts,'' she said, holding the Lorimar
document. ``I read these and start to get cross-eyed.''
   Ms. Harper acknowledged that even before the pilot for
``Valerie,'' was sold, her relations with other members of the
production staff began to erode.
   The first problem, she said, arose when Cacciotti's name was
left off the credits for the pilot even though he was supervising
producer.
   ``I was disappointed and hurt,'' she said. ``It felt like a
betrayal.''
   As ``Valerie'' began production, Ms. Harper said, she came to
feel that her agent, Jim Berkus, was working more in the interest
of his firm, Leading Artists, than hers.
   ``I had my doubts about how well we were being represented,''
she said.
   ``Do you think Mr. Berkus did a good job in negotiating this
agreement?'' asked Engel.
   ``No,'' replied Ms. Harper.
   Engel then listed the financial terms of the contract, which
brought Ms. Harper $1.5 million for the first one-and-a-half
seasons and provided profit shares and escalating salaries for her
and her husband in subsequent years. In the sixth season, she would
have received $90,000 per episode.
   ``Didn't you realize that you had a very favorable deal?'' asked
Engel.
   ``I felt financially it was a start,'' Ms. Harper replied.
   Ms. Harper said she sought to renegotiate her contract later to
increase her salary and put in writing her participation in
creating story ideas for each episode.
   By then, she conceded, she felt she was losing the right to
influence story lines.
   ``The consultation I had enjoyed had eroded and the relationship
with (the producers) had started to turn,'' she said.
   ``What you thought you had was total control,'' said Engel.
   ``I would disagree,'' said Ms. Harper. ``I wanted participation,
not control. ... I wasn't trying to be Genghis Khan. I wanted
participation with people I loved and respected.''
</TEXT>
