<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0725EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-ContraSupplies     08-23 0615</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Contra Supplies,0634</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Contra Aid Defendants Say They Helped U.S. Interests</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RICHARD COLE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of the six Cuban-Americans indicted on charges
they trained and supplied mercenaries to the Contras through a
Florida guerrilla camp say their fight in Nicaragua supported U.S.
interests.
   The Miami-area men were the second group charged by a Fort
Lauderdale federal grand jury with violating the Neutrality Act,
which bars people on U.S. soil from launching operations against a
government at peace with the United States. The latest indictment
was unsealed Monday.
   One of the six, Rene Corvo, also is accused of shipping a 20mm
cannon, a mortar and other weapons from Fort Lauderdale to Contra
bases in Costa Rica under the guise of humanitarian aid.
   After a brief appearance before U.S. Magistrate Lurana Snow in
Fort Lauderdale, some of the defendants echoed sentiments of the
group whose indictment was unsealed a month ago.
   ``We support the Contras,'' Sergio Becerra, accused of training
the mercenaries in the camp near Naples, Fla., yelled as he emerged
from the federal courthouse.
   ``These men were simply following the orders of their commander
in chief,'' said Corvo's lawyer, A.P. Walter. ``They feel it is the
duty of every American citizen to oppose communism.''
   Kirk Munroe, attorney for one of the men who allegedly financed
the operation, Eulalio Francisco ``Frank'' Castro, said his client
was ``disappointed in the indictment.''
   Castro would again aid the Contras if asked, Munroe said.
   ``I think it will become clear that these men were acting in the
interests of the United States and the interests of freedom-loving
people everywhere,'' Munroe said.
   Also financing the mercenary camp along with Castro was Joseph
Marcos, according to the indictment.
   ``Right now we really don't understand the charges,'' Marcos
said, calling them ``very unfair.''
   Corvo agreed, calling the Neutrality Act case ``very
ridiculous.''
   All four were released without bond. The two remaining
defendants, Rafael Torres Jimenez and Francisco Hernandez, were out
of the country, and federal authorities were attempting to contact
them, Assistant U.S. Attorney Mark Schnapp said.
   Corvo faces up to 38 years in prison if convicted on the weapons
charges and counts of violating the Neutrality Act and conspiring
to violate it. The remaining five men face up to eight years in
prison on the latter two charges.
   According to the indictment, the six men financed and trained
Cuban-American and Nicaraguan mercenaries, most from the Miami
area, at a camp that could handle up to 60 soldiers at a time. Some
of the men saw combat inside Nicaragua after crossing the border
from Costa Rica, Schnapp said.
   The men allegedly worked with Eden Pastora, the maverick Contra
commander who has since quit the movement, and ran the camp from
June 1983 to September 1986. The camp was a poorly kept secret and
was filmed in 1985 by a Naples-area television station, Schnapp
said.
   Members of an earlier group of Contra supporters indicted by the
same grand jury on Neutrality Act charges included Mario Calero _
the brother of Contra leader Adolfo Calero _ and Tom Posey, head of
the Alabama-based Civilian Materiel Assistance.
   One defendant, Joe Adams, a former Adolfo Calero associate,
pleaded guilty to the charges but was given a one-day probation
sentence by U.S. District Judge Norman Roettger.
   The other defendants said they were supported by the Reagan
administration and that the United States was in a de facto state
of war with Nicaragua at the time they aided the rebels.
   Schnapp said the new indictment did not include any evidence
that the men were acting on behalf of the Reagan administration.
``The indictment would indicate that they were not sanctioned,''
said Schnapp.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
