<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Quayle-Parkinson 1stLd-Writethru a0485 08-23 0757</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Quayle-Parkinson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0485,750</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Newspaper: Lawyers Say Ms. Parkinson Told FBI Of Alleged Quayle
Pass</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Adds last 6 grafs, Meanwhile Jonathan, to include further
background reported on Ms. Parkinson. This also incorporates and
serves as a lead to the first item in PM-Political Briefs, a0464.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two former attorneys for one-time lobbyist
Paula Parkinson say she told the FBI in 1981 that GOP vice
presidential nominee Dan Quayle propositioned her during a Florida
trip, but she refused, according to a published report.
   In a copyright story in today's editions of the Daily News of
Los Angeles, the attorneys said Ms. Parkinson told the FBI the
request was made when she, Quayle _ then a congressman _ and two
other legislators shared a cottage during the 1980 golfing trip,
the lawyers said.
   Quayle, an Indiana senator who has been married since 1972, has
said he did not have an affair with Ms. Parkinson, and a campaign
spokesman declined comment Monday evening about the lawyers'
allegations.
   Efforts to find Ms. Parkinson on Monday were unsuccessful, the
newspaper said.
   The two lawyers represented Ms. Parkinson when she was
questioned on March 28, 1981, by the FBI during an investigation of
whether sexual favors were traded for votes against legislation.
The lawyers reviewed their notes of the FBI interview for the Daily
News during separate telephone interviews Monday.
   Ms. Parkinson has said that at the time of the trip, she was
with Rep. Tom Evans, R-Del., who lost his re-election bid in 1982.
   ``Paula reported to the FBI during the investigation of the
lobbying scandal that Quayle was interested in her, flirted with
her and asked her to go to bed with him,'' said Washington attorney
Glenn Lewis, referring to his notes from the FBI interview of Ms.
Parkinson.
   ``She indicated at that time that she couldn't (respond to his
overture) because she was with Congressman Evans,'' Lewis told the
newspaper.
   Washington attorney Roy Kinsey, who also was present during the
interview, said his paraphrased notes show that she told the FBI,
``Quayle made a pass, and said he would like to sleep with'' her.
   According to Kinsey's notes, Ms. Parkinson told the FBI that she
rejected Quayle's suggestion, saying, ``No, I'm with Tom (Evans).''
   Mark Goodin, deputy press secretary for the Bush-Quayle
campaign, was told of the lawyers' comments Monday evening.
   ``I think you've got a huge rumor mill out there churning this
stuff out, and until I have something laid before me that is
substantially more than a rumor, I can't comment,'' Goodin said.
   The lobbying investigation centered on Ms. Parkinson, a lobbyist
for an insurance industry group that opposed legislation to set up
a national farm crop insurance program. The bill passed the House
in September 1980, with Quayle, Evans and the third member of the
Florida trip _ Rep. Tom Railsback, R-Ill. _ voting against it.
   The three Republican congressmen shared a house with Ms.
Parkinson during the January 1980 golfing trip to Atlantis, Fla.
   FBI spokesman Greg Jones refused comment Monday on the
7-year-old interview.
   Kinsey said his 20 pages of notes of the interview paraphrase
Ms. Parkinson stating that she and Evans shared one room, and that
Quayle was in another.
   The Justice Department, which conducted the investigation of Ms.
Parkinson's relationships with the members of Congress, dropped its
case in August 1981 without filing any charges.
   Lewis and Kinsey said they have not talked to Ms. Parkinson for
several years.
   Meanwhile, Jonathan Black, managing editor of Playboy magazine,
said Monday that Parkinson would have ``new comments'' about events
at the Florida cottage in text accompanying a ``Women of
Washington'' pictorial in the November issue of the magazine. Ms.
Parkinson will appear nude in the pictorial.
   Black said the article was originally written long before Quayle
was named as Vice President George Bush's running mate, but that
``new material'' from Parkinson was inserted last week. The
magazine is scheduled to be on the newsstands Oct. 1.
   The Dallas Morning News reported that Ms. Parkinson, who is
divorced, uses her maiden name, Paula Laham, and lives in an
apartment in the Dallas suburb of Mesquite.
   ``She doesn't want to talk to anyone today,'' a woman at the
apartment told the newspaper Monday.
   The former lobbyist was arrested twice in 1985 for public
intoxication, the News reported. One case was dismissed, but she
received 90 days probation on the other.
   She was placed on two years probation last December after
pleading guilty to a charge of driving while under the influence.
</TEXT>
