<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0930EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i PM-Burundi     08-23 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Burundi,0646</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugees Say Military Participated In Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The military in Burundi took part in
massacres that have left at least 5,000 people dead and caused
38,000 to flee to neighboring Rwanda, a U.N. official quoted
refugees as saying today.
   ``What they told me was that they were fleeing persecution from
the military and we saw many people who had been injured by bullets
and bayonets,'' said Code Cisse, a U.N. representative in Rwanda's
capital, Kigali.
   Burundi's military is dominated by the minority Tutsi tribe,
which has been fighting the majority Hutu tribe. The Hutu People
Liberation Party, an exiled opposition group, has charged that
Burundi's military massacred thousands of Hutus.
   Burundi's government has denied the accusations. It claims the
slaughter last week was instigated by exiled Hutus who infiltrated
the tiny central African country to inflame anti-Tutsi sentiments.
   ``What the government did was restore peace,'' said an official
communique issued Monday by Burundi's foreign minister, Cyprien
Mbonimpa.
   The Hutu and the Tutsi are longtime enemies. Following an
abortive coup attempt in 1972 in Burundi, a former colony of
Belgium, the Tutsi massacred more than 100,000 Hutu including most
of the tribe's intelligentsia, according to human rights groups.
   Western diplomats in Burundi's capital, Bujumbura, said there
were ethnic disturbances earlier this month in the northern region
where the slaughter occurred, but the government felt it had
succeeded in calming the situation.
   ``The killing seems to have caught everybody by surprise,'' said
one diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``It could lend
credence to the government's claim there had been infiltrators
trying to stir things up.''
   Most of the killings occurred around the remote farming communes
of Ntega and Marangara in northern Burundi, a hilly, marshy area
that has been sealed off by the military.
   ``News has been very, very difficult to come by,'' the diplomat
said. ``But from all that we have been able to gather, the army
moved in after the initial mass killing had occurred and was
instructed to fire only upon those carrying arms or threatening
other people.''
   Although Burundi claims it has restored peace to the area, the
U.N. official said peasants still were fleeing across the border
with Rwanda at an average of 5,000 per day, and the refugees had
numbered 38,000 by Monday.
   He said the majority of refugees were Hutu.
   Cisse, who represents the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees,
said urgent international assistance was needed to help Rwanda cope
with the influx. He said the immediate requirements were blankets,
medicines and tents to accomodate the refugees, many of whom were
sleeping in the open.
   ``The conditions are very bad,'' he said. ``They are located in
a region where there is a high risk of malaria and are being housed
in schools and health clinics. We can't meet the need.''
   Rwanda and Burundi are among the world's most densely populated
countries.
   Nearly 5 million people live in Burundi, which covers an area
about the size of Maryland. Eighty-four percent of its people are
Hutu, while 15 percent are Tutsi. The same percentages apply to the
approximately 6 million people in Rwanda, which covers a slightly
smaller area.
   In an official communique Monday, the government of Burundi
promised to work with refugees who fled to Rwanda to try to return
them to their homes as soon as possible.
   The government has restricted travel between towns, enforced a 7
p.m.-to-5 a.m. curfew throughout the country and banned meetings of
more than five people.
   The massacre, in which the government has said 5,000 have died,
was the first outbreak of violence since Maj. Pierre Buyoya seized
power in a bloodless coup Sept. 3, 1987 while former President
Jean-Baptiste Bagaza was in Canada.
</TEXT>
