<DOCNO> AP880823-0071 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1002EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Nicaragua-Ortega 1stLd-Writethru a0484 08-23 0393</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Nicaragua-Ortega, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0484,0401</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ortega: U.S. Political Parties ``Imperialist''</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 2nd graf to say Ortega spoke Monday.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By FILADELFO ALEMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MANAGUA, Nicaragua (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Daniel Ortega says the U.S.
Democratic and Republican parties are ``imperialist'' because each
had an assistance plan for Nicaraguan rebels fighting to overthrow
his government.
   Ortega said Monday he doubted the inauguration of a new American
administration next year would improve U.S.-Nicaraguan relations
but held out hope a Democratic administration under Michael Dukakis
would seek negotiations.
   ``What we have said is that a future U.S. government _ Democrat
or Republican, both have shown themselves to be imperialist _ be
responsible and wise enough to have learned the lesson (President)
Reagan would leave them,'' he said.
   Both parties ``have their own plan for aid to the Contras'' and
``aren't satisfied that there exists a sovereign, free and
independent government in Nicaragua,'' Ortega said.
   The United States has supported the rebels, known as Contras,
since 1981.
   U.S. military aid for the rebels expired in February. On Aug.
10, the Senate voted largely along party lines for a Democratic
proposal to provide the Contras with $27 million in non-lethal
humanitarian aid after Oct. 1 and a possible second vote on $16.3
million in stockpiled military aid later this year.
   A cease-fire has been in effect since March 21, but talks on a
permanent truce to the civil war broke down in June. Each side has
accused the other of violating the truce.
   Ortega said if Dukakis is elected president and ``is capable of
executing (plans) to enter negotiated solutions, he would be giving
the United States the opportunity to vindicate itself before the
people of Latin America.''
   Ortega made his remarks during a ceremony marking the 10th
anniversary of the seizure of the National Palace by Sandinista
guerrillas fighting the government of the late President Anastasio
Somoza.
   In the Salvadoran capital of San Salvador, six Nicaraguan exiles
staged a peaceful protest inside their country's embassy to demand
greater democratization in Nicaragua.
   The six men, representing a group called the United Front of
Mestizos of the Nicaraguan Atlantic Coast, said they were
protesting what they called the Sandinista government's failure to
fulfill a year-old regional peace accord.
   Among other measures, the treaty commits Central American
governments to make democratic reforms and negotiate peaceful
solutions to insurgencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
