<DOCNO> AP880823-0072 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1004EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Mexico-Politics     08-23 0428</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Mexico-Politics,0448</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cardenas Files Charges Against Election Officials</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JAMES ANDERSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MEXICO CITY (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Cuauhtemoc Cardenas filed
criminal charges against two top election officials, accusing them
of failing to release results of the July 6 elections from nearly
half of Mexico's voting stations.
   In his petition, presented Monday night, Cardenas said Manuel
Bartlett Diaz, president of the Federal Election Commission and
interior minister, and Fernando Elias Calles, the commission
secretary, violated the electoral code by not releasing results
from at least 24,000 polling stations.
   More than 18 million Mexicans cast ballots at about 55,000
stations, according to the Election Commission.
   ``We asked that the (vote) information be made known and that
the authorities fulfill their responsibility,'' said Cardenas,
presidential candidate of the National Democratic Front coalition.
   Elias Calles rejected Cardenas' claims and presented a
multi-party election committee with a computer printout of the
national vote for the Chamber of Deputies.
   President-elect Carlos Salinas de Gortari won 50.36 percent of
the vote in official returns to 31.12 percent for Cardenas and
17.07 for Manuel Clouthier of the conservative National Action
Party.
   ``In this commission we have never hidden (vote) information,''
Elias Calles said.
   In an incident Sunday, soldiers carrying automatic rifles
stopped about 150 opposition representatives from entering a room
at the Legislative Palace where millions of ballots are kept. The
army is required to guard the ballots until the election is
certified.
   The deputies-elect said the ballots would prove opposition
charges that the PRI rigged the election.
   Earlier Monday, the governing Institutional Revolutionary Party,
or PRI, assured the nation a new Chamber of Deputies will be
certified by Sept. 1.
   The outgoing president customarily introduces his successor to
the nation on Sept. 1 during his final state-of-the-union address.
The new president is sworn in Dec. 1.
   Mexican presidents serve single, six-year terms beginning Dec.
1. The PRI has won every presidential election since it was created
in 1929.
   On Monday, Cardenas' National Front suffered two defections to
the governing party.
   Lucia Santes, a Front leader in southeastern Tabasco state, said
in announcing her defection she had been the object of ``low blows,
envy and rancor'' and that the PRI ``represents the real option for
change.''
   Amalio Salinas Munoz, a 36-year PRI veteran before resigning to
become a Front senate candidate in central Morelos state, asked to
be welcomed back to the governing party ranks, the PRI said.
   A party statement quoted Salinas Munoz as saying he had been
``threatened with death by those who claim to be (Front) leaders in
Morelos.''
</TEXT>
