<DOCNO> AP880823-0076 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1047EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Soviet-Baltics     08-23 0512</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Soviet-Baltics,0528</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Estonians Call For Economic Independence</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARK J. PORUBCANSKY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MOSCOW (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Two Estonian scholars today called for greater
economic independence from Moscow for their republic on the 49th
anniversary of an agreement that led to the Soviet takeover of
Estonia and two other republics.
   Activists said thousands of demonstrators from Latvia, Lithuania
and Estonia were planning to commemorate the signing on Aug. 23,
1939, of a secret non-aggression pact between the Soviet Union and
Nazi Germany.
   The pact divided Eastern Europe into spheres of Soviet and
German influence and led to the Soviet takeover of the three
independent Baltic republics a year later. Soviet officials say the
pact bought their country a crucial two years to prepare for war
with Germany.
   Activists in Latvia and Lithuania told The Associated Press that
authorities have granted them permission for outdoor meetings for
the purpose of recalling the victims of dictator Josef Stalin's
purges. But they said demonstrators undoubtedly would use the
gatherings to mark the signing of the non-aggression pact.
   Mikhail Bombin, correspondent for the dissident journal
Express-Chronicle, said 10,000-25,000 people were expected at a
rally in the Latvian port of Riga.
   Valdas Analauskas, the journal's correspondent in Lithuania,
said a large crowd gathered Monday night in the central square in
the capital of Vilnius and surrounded about 40 people on a hunger
strike in support of Lithuanian political prisoners. He said there
had been no action by authorities to break up the protest.
   Authorities have granted permission for a gathering in a central
Vilnius park tonight, Analauskas said.
   Philosopher Edgar Savisaar and economist I. Raig, writing in
today's edition of the newspaper Sovietskaya Kultura, called for
Estonia and other republics to be given full responsibility for
managing their economies. Estonia is politically and economically
controlled by the Kremlin.
   ``The government is strong when all of its parts are strong; the
parts are strong when they receive the right to be strong. Only
then will both, the parts and the whole, win,'' they said.
   Savisaar was one of the founders this year of a group called the
Peoples Front, a citizens' organizations that says it supports
Soviet leader Mikhail S. Gorbachev's reforms but demands more
autonomy for the Baltic republics.
   The article followed similar calls at a Communist Party
conference in Moscow at the end of June.
   Savisaar and Raig said the central government should count on
each of the 15 Soviet republics for production of goods and
services, but leave it to the republic to decide how best to
fulfill the task. They said the republics now have little power
over factories run by powerful Moscow ministries.
   Many Estonians are chafing under what they view as the drag on
their economies by other, less developed parts of the Soviet Union,
and some radicals are seeking a complete break.
   The Molotov-Ribbentrop pact of 1939, named for Soviet Foreign
Minister Vyacheslav Molotov and German Foreign Minister Joachim Von
Ribbentrop, was published for the first time in the Soviet Union
less than two weeks ago by an Estonian newspaper.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
