<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Iran-Iraq     08-23 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Iran-Iraq,0332</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Iran Reports Iraqi Troop Movements</HEAD>
<TEXT>
   NICOSIA, Cyprus AP) _ Iran claimed today that Iraq was massing
troops and moving armor to the warfront in preparation for new
military thrusts across the central and southern sectors of the
disputed border.
   The official Islamic Republic News Agency said Foreign Minister
Ali Akbar Velayati of Iran sent an urgent message to U.N.
Secretary-General Javier Perez de Cuellar notifying him of the
Iraqi movements and warning of ``the Iraqi regime's intentions to
launch military operations against Iran.''
   Iran and Iraq have accused each other of violating a cease-fire
that began Saturday.
   Velayati told Perez de Cuellar the Iraqis have massed troops
facing Fakkeh on the central sector of the border, IRNA reported.
The dispatch was monitored in Nicosia.
   The agency quoted Brig Gen. Asghar Jamali, deputy commander of
Iran's ground forces, as saying that U.N. observers watched an
Iraqi armored brigade roll up to the western bank of the Nahr Anbar
river at 11:07 a.m.
   He said the Iraqis dug in and were now facing the Iranians on
the other bank of the river in the southern sector of the warfront.
   IRNA quoted Jamali as saying that at the request of the command
of the U.N. Iran-Iraq Military Observer Group, which is monitoring
the cease-fire, he ordered his troops not to fire or react in any
way to the Iraqi movements.
   There was no immediate comment from Baghdad on the Iranian
charges.
   Iraq claimed on Monday that the Iranians have redeployed in the
central sector of the border, and warned its troops may use force
to push them back.
   At the United Nations in New York, officials refused to discuss
the alleged cease-fire violations but said U.N. truce observers
were defusing tensions successfully on the front line.
   The two countries are scheduled to meet face-to-face in Geneva
Thursday for talks aimed at achieving a comprehensive peace in
their 8-year-old war.
</TEXT>
