<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1102EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i PM-PalauPresident     08-23 0648</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Palau President,0667</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Investigation Into Palau President's Death Awaits Autopsy Results</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HOWARD GRAVES</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KOROR, Palau (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The investigation of the shooting death of
President Lazarus Salii was stalled today pending the outcome of an
autopsy and an FBI examination of the weapon and other evidence.
   ``The government is still not ruling out anything,'' spokesman
Bonifacio Basilius said when asked if the autopsy had indicated the
shot was self-inflicted. ``Nothing has changed except an autopsy
took place.''
   Salii, 51, father of four children, was found alone Saturday in
a living room chair at his home with a single shot in the head from
a .357-caliber Magnum revolver.
   He was the second of Palau's three presidents in seven years to
die by gunfire. The first president of the tiny western Pacific
archipelago, Haruo I. Remeliik, was assassinated in June 1985.
   At a special election two months later, Salii was elected to
serve the remaining portion of Remeliik's four-year term. That term
would have ended this year; Salii had planned to announce his
candidacy for president Sunday.
   Basilius said the autopsy by Dr. Hee Yong Park, a pathologist
and chief medical examiner for Guam, and Dr. Victor Yano was
restricted to the head area.
   Basilius said the autopsy report is expected by Wednesday or
Thursday. He said it will be discussed with the Salii family and
``at that time a joint decision will be made as to when the content
is made public.''
   Basilius and Attorney General Philip Isaac said investigators
had thoroughly questioned Salii family members and neighbors. None
of them said they had seen anyone leave the Salii residence after a
noise was heard.
   Isaac said the revolver and spent bullet were found beside
Salii's chair. An FBI agent from Honolulu, who happened to be in
Palau on other business, left for Washington today with the
revolver, the spent bullet and hair samples for examination by the
agency's crime laboratory.
   Haruo Willter, Palau's liaison representative in Washington,
said today he had spent about two hours with Salii on Saturday,
reviewing his activities in Washington.
   ``We just talked about the things he already knew from our
nearly daily telephone conversations,'' said Willter, who arrived
Friday.
   He said Salii was in a ``very, very good mood and he invited me
to his rally on Sunday.''
   Salii's body was found by his wife, Tina, after she had finished
lunch with a maid and a driver.
   Vice President Thomas O. Remengasau, who also was Palau's
minister of justice, was sworn in late Saturday as the new
president.
   Two congressmen with ties to Palau expressed their sympathies to
the Salii family and Remengasau on Monday. Rep. Morris K. Udall,
D-Ariz., and Ron de Lugo, the non-voting representative in Congress
of the U.S. Virgin Islands, told Remengasau in a telegram: ``We
stand ready to help you and Palau's other leaders.''
   In April, Udall and de Lugo charged that Salii and two other
Palau officials were paid $475,000 in 1983 and 1984 out of a $32
million loan made by British banks to Palau for construction of a
power plant.
   Salii acknowledged receiving $100,000 from an official of the
company that built the plant, but said it went to a travel agency
he owned.
   Udall and de Lugo also have charged without elaboration that
several senior Palauan government officials have been connected to
shipments of Asian heroin through Palau.
   Udall is chairman of the House Committee on Interior and Insular
Affairs. De Lugo is chairman of the Subcommittee on Insular and
International Affairs, which is considering legislation to make the
island chain of 15,000 residents self-governing.
   A state funeral will be held Friday at the National Congress
Building in Koror, Palau's capital and business center, followed by
a funeral mass at Sacred Heart Catholic Church.
   Janet McCoy, principal Interior Department deputy secretary,
will head a U.S. delegation to the funeral.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
