<1ST_LINE>r i PM-Irish 2ndLd-Writethru   08-23 0543</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Irish, 2nd Ld-Writethru,a0501,0560</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IRA Kills Royal Navy Recruiting Officer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 10 grafs to UPDATE with government changing plates
on cars of British military personnel in West Germany. Pick up 7th
pvs, Crispin Rodwell.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The IRA killed a Royal Navy
officer with a bomb planted in his car that exploded near a Roman
Catholic section of Belfast. One newspaper said some residents
jeered as the car burned.
   The government said today it was changing the license plates on
British army cars in West Germany to disguise them against a
stepped-up IRA campaign.
   The killing Monday night came three days after eight British
soldiers were slain by another IRA bomb.
   Lt. Alan Shields, 45, a Royal Navy recruiting officer, was
driving into East Belfast when a bomb attached to his car blew up,
police said. They said Shields was the only casualty.
   The British newspaper The Guardian said some residents jeered as
the car burned.
   The outlawed Irish Republican Army claimed responsibility in a
telephoned message to a radio station, saying it had killed a
British soldier.
   Shields was believed to be the first member of the Royal Navy
killed by the IRA in Northern Ireland.
   The Defense Ministry, responding to a wave of attacks on British
military personnel in Western Europe this summer, said today the
distinctive military plates on the 95,000 cars driven by military
personnel and their families in West Germany would be replaced by
ordinary British plates.
   The change will make the plates indistinguishable from those on
cars of British tourists, Armed Forces Minister Archie Hamilton
said.
   Four soldiers have died in IRA attacks on British army personnel
in Western Europe this summer. It is suspected the IRA identified
them through plates on their cars.
   Crispin Rodwell, a news photographer who was driving about 50
yards behind the car, said: ``It just exploded and was immediately
engulfed in flames. Several people ran forward with fire
extinguishers but the flames were very intense.''
   ``They sprayed it but couldn't get close enough to have any
effect and the driver was still inside,'' Rodwell said.
   The attack followed an IRA bombing 50 miles west of Belfast on
Saturday that killed eight British soldiers in a military bus and
injured 27 others.
   In London, staff at Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office
said she was ``saddened and angered by yet another senseless
killing.''
   Mrs. Thatcher ordered a major security review following the bomb
attack Saturday, the deadliest IRA attack on the military since
1982.
   The mainly Catholic IRA is fighting to end British rule in
Protestant-dominated Northern Ireland and unite it with the
overwhelmingly Catholic Irish Republic under socialist rule.
   Mrs. Thatcher said Monday that detention without trial of people
suspected of guerrilla activity had not been ruled out.
   Ken Maginnis, a Protestant member of Parliament from Northern
Ireland who urged Mrs. Thatcher to reinstate the policy, said he
gave her the names of three IRA men he claimed were involved in the
Saturday bombing.
   He claimed internment of 50-70 ``top flight'' IRA organizers
would ``drastically reduce'' violence in Northern Ireland.
   Internment was introduced in Northern Ireland in 1971 and about
2,000 people were held without trial before it was abandoned in
December 1975 amid world criticism.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0080 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1116EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u p PM-Dukakis 1stLd-Writethru a0443 08-23 0843</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dukakis, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0443,820</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Precede BROOKLINE, Mass.</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Top 10 grafs new with Dukakis today; pick up 6th graf pvs
bgng ``Dukakis during...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By JOHN KING</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ANDOVER, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Michael Dukakis today said George Bush
``has no business'' in the White House if he supports mandatory
recitation of the Pledge of Allegiance in schools.
   Dukakis also called his Republican opponent's plan to erase the
federal deficit ``son of voodoo economics.''
   Dukakis, beginning the second day of a gubernatorial trip to
northeastern Massachusetts, urged students to say the Pledge of
Allegiance at the start of the school day but said it would be
unconstitutional to make it mandatory.
   ``I say the Pledge of Allegiance. That's not the issue,''
Dukakis said.
   Bush and other Republicans have criticized Dukakis for vetoing a
state measure that would have penalized teachers if they did not
lead their students in the Pledge of Allegiance. Dukakis did so
after the state Supreme Court, citing U.S. Supreme Court precedent,
said the legislation was unconstitutional.
   ``You have no alternative but to veto it if you're true to your
oath,'' Dukakis told area newspapers editors. ``You're under a
constitutional oath to veto it. ... Is the vice president
suggesting something else? If he does, he has no business running
for the office.''
   The Democratic nominee also lambasted Bush's call for a flexible
freeze on federal spending as a means of balancing the budget.
   ``There is no Republican plan,'' Dukakis said after detailing
his plan to freeze military spending, reduce some domestic programs
and collect unpaid taxes. ``The vice president is talking about a
flexible freeze. That's like a melting ice cube. ... That's the son
of voodoo economics.''
   On Monday night, CIA Director William Webster briefed Dukakis
and running mate Lloyd Bentsen on national security and foreign
affairs.
   Participants refused to comment on the session, one of a series
of briefings Dukakis and Bentsen, already a member of the Senate
Intelligence Committee, are entitled to as the Democratic
presidential and vice presidential nominees.
   Dukakis, during a visit to Lowell on Monday, said his campaign
has been trying to complete arrangements for three debates with
Bush hosted by a bipartisan commission established under a joint
agreement between Republicans and Democrats.
   Dukakis said the Bush campaign has not responded to inquiries
about debates, but that he hoped the first encounter, scheduled by
the commission for Sept. 14, could be devoted to national security
and foreign policy.
   Bush frequently criticizes Dukakis as inexperienced on those
fronts, and did so again Monday in the context of U.S. involvement
in the Persian Gulf.
   Dukakis was quick to fire back.
   ``How anyone who sat there and did nothing while we sold arms to
the ayatollah can seriously talk about leadership in the Persian
Gulf is beyond me,'' Dukakis told a news conference.
   He also continued to question Bush's judgment in selecting Sen.
Dan Quayle of Indiana as his running mate and said voters should
compare the vice presidential nominees closely as they weigh their
vote for president.
   ``How we make decisions, how we make the presidential
selections, who we select ... whether or not that person should be
a heartbeat away from the presidency, obviously will be an issue in
this campaign,'' Dukakis said.
   Quayle has been embroiled in controversy since it was revealed
last week that an employee of his wealthy family's newspaper chain
who had ties to the Indiana National Guard recommended Quayle to
Guard officials at the height of the Vietnam War. By serving in the
Guard, Quayle, a staunch conservative, avoided combat duty.
Quayle's father also has been quoted as saying his son ``talked his
way'' into law school because his grades were not good enough.
   Dukakis said he considered the military records of candidates
for the presidency and vice presidency relevant as a campaign issue
but refused to answer directly when asked if he considered Quayle
qualified to be vice president.
   ``This is a judgment the American people will have to make,''
Dukakis said. ``They've had an opportunity now to watch Michael
Dukakis make his selection and George Bush make his decision. And
they will judge us on this and other issues.''
   Dukakis defended his military record from an attack by New York
Republican Rep. Gerald Solomon, who criticized Dukakis for
deferring his military service while attending Swarthmore College
during the Korean War.
   Dukakis said he could have applied for further deferments and
entered law school upon graduating Swarthmore in 1955 but instead
asked to be drafted immediately and entered the Army less than two
months after graduation.
   The truce ending the war had been signed by then, but Dukakis
served 16 months in Korea near the demilitarized zone.
   ``I'm very proud of that service and very proud of the
opportunity it gave me to serve my country,'' said Dukakis, who
suggested Solomon was trying to deflect attention from the Quayle
controversy.
   ``I don't think it's a coincidence that a Republican congressman
raised it,'' Dukakis said. ``It will be up to the Republican Party
to explain all this.''
</TEXT>
