<1ST_LINE>r a PM-People-GraceJones 1stLd-Writethru a0512 08-23 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-People-Grace Jones, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0512,0515</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Singer Removed From Plane With Boyfriend and Children</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: UPDATES with airline denial and comments throughout. Note
language in grafs 5 and 13.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By PAUL GEITNER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Singer-actress Grace Jones says Jamaican police
dragged her and two children from an American Airlines plane this
morning after her boyfriend demanded the pilot apologize for flight
delays. The airline denied the allegation.
   ``I went through hell and back,'' Ms. Jones said in a telephone
interview from Jamaica today.
   The argument escalated and police were called when the pilot,
who is white, allegedly used a racial slur to describe Ms. Jones'
boyfriend, who is black, said an officer at the Norman Manley
International Airport police station in Kingston, Jamaica.
   The officer, who refused to give his name, said the boyfriend,
Chris Stanley, 35, had demanded that pilot George Caughran
apologize for delays on the flight to New York.
   ``The captain didn't apologize for the late departure,'' he
said. Then, according to Stanley, ``the pilot called him a
nigger,'' the officer said. ``He didn't apologize for that either.''
   An American Airlines spokesman, Steve McGregor in Fort Worth,
Texas, said that was not true. ``Absolutely not. The pilot did not
use racial epithets. (Stanley) used racial epithets himself.''
   McGregor said when Ms. Jones' companion learned the flight was
delayed, he ``leaped over the ticket counter and threatened an
employee. He abused the flight attendants (verbally) and abused the
captain verbally.''
   Police were called, the Jamaican officer said, to remove Stanley
when he refused to get off the plane. Ms. Jones, her 8-year-old son
and Stanley's 8-year-old daughter also got off the plane and
accompanied Stanley to the police station, where he was charged
with disorderly behavior and resisting arrest, the officer said.
   Ms. Jones was not charged with anything, the officer said. ``She
said she couldn't go (on with the flight) alone,'' he said.
   But Ms. Jones, who was in Jamaica to record her next album, said
she and the children were forced off the plane.
   ``They physically pulled us off,'' she said.
   Ms. Jones said the plane was at least two hours late, but the
crew did not offer any apology.
   ``No one was making any disturbance whatsoever,'' she said, but
when Stanley asked the captain for an apology, he replied: ```We're
not going to apologize to niggers,' or something like that, with
the two children sitting behind us.''
   She said about 15 officers were called and they ``literally
pulled us, dragged us off the plane and pushed both of the
children.''
   ``Those children were totally molested. There's a plane full of
witnesses,'' Ms. Jones said.
   McGregor said American personnel at the scene described Ms.
Jones' demeanor as ``fairly calm throughout the whole incident.''
He said Ms. Jones never was removed from the flight. ``We asked her
if she wanted to continue on the flight,'' he said.
   Stanley was released on $200 bail, police said. He was to appear
before a resident magistrate today.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
