<1ST_LINE>u a PM-WeatherpageWeather 1stLd-Writethru a0506 08-23 0585</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Weatherpage Weather, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0506,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>For Second Time in Week, Part of Nation Beats the Heat</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts one graf after 3rd graf, `The thunderstorms ...,' to
update with rain amount; inserts one graf after the 7th graf pvs,
`The first ...,' to update with record lows.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   A cold front pulled much cooler air into the northern Plains
today, giving a part of America a break from summer's record heat
for the second time in less than a week.
   Showers and thunderstorms continued ahead of the front, with the
heaviest storms widespread from the middle Mississippi Valley to
the southern Plains.
   The thunderstorms brought heavy rain and gusty winds to the
region. Winds gusted to near 45 mph Monday night in parts of St.
Louis and to near 50 mph in Greene County, Ill., north of St.
Louis, causing power outages.
   Springfield, Mo., got 3.35 inches of rain this morning.
   Thunderstorms trailing the front across the Texas Panhandle and
central New Mexico also brought brief, heavy rain. A half inch fell
at Amarillo, Texas, in 30 minutes this morning.
   Thunderstorms moved from eastern North Dakota to central and
eastern Minnesota Monday night and today.
   Showers and thunderstorms also continued today from northern
Alabama to southeast Georgia and northeast Florida.
   The first cold front brought more seasonable temperatures to the
Northeast, the Ohio Valley and the Middle Atlantic States before
the weekend.
   That cool air remained in place in the Northeast, where
temperatures dipped to record lows today, including 44 at Albany,
N.Y.; 43 at Burlington, Vt.; and 42 at Hartford, Conn., while
Syracuse, N.Y., tied its record of 45. In the distant Northwest,
Pocatello, Idaho, tied its record low of 36.
   The fronts are easing the swelter of a summer in which more than
2,000 records have fallen.
   Today's forecast called for scattered showers and thunderstorms
from the Great Lakes region to the Ohio and middle Mississippi
valleys, and from Oklahoma and the southern Rockies to the Arizona
mountains, with storms most numerour from southeast Michigan to the
lower Ohio Valley, southern Missouri and the Arizona mountains; and
from the Tennessee and lower Mississippi valleys to the Gulf Coast
states, Georgia and Florida.
   High temperatures were predicted in the 80s and 90s across much
of the nation; the 60s and 70s from the north Atlantic Coast to the
Great Lakes, North Dakota and the California coast; 100 to 105
degrees in the Rio Grande Valley and the central part of Texas,
inland western Oregon, the central valleys of California and the
desert Southwest.
   Temperatures around the nation at 3 a.m. EDT ranged from 37
degrees at Houlton, Maine, to 89 at Nellis Air Force Base near Las
Vegas, Nev.
   Other reports:
   _East: Atlanta 75 foggy; Boston 56 fair; Buffalo 57 fair;
Charleston, S.C. 74 cloudy; Cincinnati 68 cloudy; Cleveland 61
partly cloudy; Detroit 66 cloudy; Miami 81 fair; New York 60 fair;
Philadelphia 60 fair; Pittsburgh 64 partly cloudy; Portland, Maine
48 fair; Washington 68 partly cloudy.
   _Central: Bismarck 62 fair; Chicago 67 showers; Dallas-Fort
Worth 88 fair; Denver 66 fair; Des Moines 67 fair; Indianapolis 72
cloudy; Kansas City 70 fair; Minneapolis-St. Paul 63 partly cloudy;
New Orleans 77 fair; St. Louis 73 thunderstorms.
   _West: Albuquerque 71 cloudy; Anchorage 52 cloudy; Las Vegas 89
fair; Los Angeles 65 fair; Phoenix 89 fair; Salt Lake City 65 fair;
San Diego 69 fair; San Francisco 61 fair; Seattle 67 fair.
   _Canada: Montreal 54 fair; Toronto 59 partly cloudy.
</TEXT>
