<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DietLabFire     08-23 0248</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Diet Lab Fire,0253</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Diet Center's Pharmaceutical Lab Burns; Residents Evacuated
Overnight</HEAD>
<DATELINE>REXBURG, Idaho (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   People living near a pharmaceutical
laboratory that burned down were allowed to return to their homes
today as officials continued investigating whether smoke from the
fire was toxic.
   Clouds of smoke hovering over Rexburg and nearby Sugar City from
Monday's fire were dispersing and drifting away from populated
areas, said Gordon Harrop of the Rexburg-Madison County Fire
Department.
   An explosion Monday afternoon apparently started the fire in the
Ferguson Pharmaceuticals laboratory, a research and development
facility where diet supplements were developed for the company's
2,300 Diet Center franchises in the United States and Canada.
   The plant's 120 employees were on a break; no one was injured in
the explosion or fire. But people were evacuated overnight from a
four-block area around the plant, a Madison County sheriff's office
said.
   Four people were treated for respiratory complaints at Madison
Memorial Hospital and released.
   Ross Mayfield, operations director for the state Bureau of
Disaster Services, said residents' breathing problems may have been
caused by chlorine and polyvinyl chloride fumes from burning
plastic containers.
   The bureau asked the Idaho National Engineering Laboratory near
Arco to help monitor the cloud for hazardous chemicals.
   Harrop said the fire was allowed to burn itself out when it was
clear that the building and its contents could not be saved. Crews
monitored the gutted, smoldering building today, and a state fire
investigator was on the scene, he said.
</TEXT>
