<1ST_LINE>r a PM-BankerKidnapped     08-23 0358</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Banker Kidnapped,0367</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Boxer Arrested in Kidnapping of Alabama Banker</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Billie Jean is cq for third man in 6th graf</NOTE>
<DATELINE>EVERGREEN, Ala. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A former U.S. Olympic boxer was among
three men arrested in the kidnapping of a banker who escaped by
untying himself from a tree, authorities said today.
   Clint Jackson, who lost in the preliminaries of the 1976
Olympics in Montreal, was charged with first-degree kidnapping in
the abduction of Thomas Salo, vice president of the First Alabama
Bank of Evergreen, said Conecuh County Sheriff Edwin L. Booker.
   Jackson was arrested in the Atlanta area Monday night, said
Booker. Sheriff's Lt. David Wood of Clayton County, Ga., said
Jackson was charged as a fugitive under state law.
   Jackson, 34, formerly lived in Evergreen in south Alabama and
knows Salo, said Booker. He worked for several years as a jailer
with the Davidson County Sheriff's Department in Nashville, Tenn.,
and compiled a 25-5 record while fighting professionally from 1979
through October 1985.
   A secretary said Jackson left the sheriff's department on Jan.
15, 1981, and has not been heard from since.
   David Reginald Smith, 24, of Atlanta and Billie Jean Jackson,
27, of Evergreen also were charged with kidnapping and were held in
the Conecuh County Jail, said Booker. It wasn't clear if the two
Jackson men were related. The sheriff said federal charges might be
filed.
   Conecuh County authorities planned to travel to Atlanta to
question Clint Jackson, said the sheriff.
   Salo was confronted at gunpoint by two masked men on his way to
work Monday. The men told Salo to write a check for $9,000 and to
call the bank to tell workers to cash it, said Booker.
   After getting the check, the two took Salo to a wooded area,
where a car driven by a third man was waiting, said the sheriff.
The men tied Salo to a tree and left him, unharmed.
   Salo managed to free himself and telephone the sheriff's office.
Booker said he was waiting at the bank when Smith came inside to
cash the check using a bogus identification card.
   Billie Jean Jackson was arrested shortly afterward.
</TEXT>
