<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1254EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a PM-DrugKillings     08-23 0184</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Drug Killings,0187</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drug Killings Cited in Soaring Houston Homicide Rate</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The number of homicides in Houston this year is
up by more than 40 percent, with more drug-related killings
reported during the first eight months of 1988 than in all of 1987,
police records show.
   As of Sunday, 300 homicides had occurred in Houston, compared
with 209 through Aug. 21, 1987. Sixty-nine slayings this year are
believed to have been drug-related, 19 more than in 1987, records
show.
   Police speculated that drug killings are increasing because of
the popularity of crack cocaine and an influx of Colombian and
Jamaican drug dealers, who are believed to be more violent than the
typical local street dealer.
   ``Evidently the competition is getting stiffer,'' said Sgt. John
Burmester. ``There's big money involved and people will kill each
other for little money.''
   The FBI's uniform crime report for 1987 said Houston had a rate
of 13.8 homicides per 100,000 inhabitants, below New York's 20.4,
Detroit's 20.2, Miami's 20.1, Los Angeles' 16.6 and New Orleans'
18.1, but above Dallas' 2.9, Pittsburgh's 3.1 and Boston's 4.0.
</TEXT>
