<DOCNO> AP880823-0096 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1257EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a BC-Theater     08-23 0602</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Theater,0613</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Shakespeare's `King John,' Starring Kevin Conway, Opens in Central
Park</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL KUCHWARA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Drama Critic</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``King John'' is one of Shakespeare's least
performed historical plays, and the situation won't change after
the revival of the drama in Central Park by the New York
Shakespeare Festival.
   The play is a pageantry about greed, but not much of its
celebration of self-interest, or anything else for that matter,
comes across in the Public Theater's sprawling and haphazard
production.
   That's because director Stuart Vaughan lets his actors do what
they want, resulting in a clash of acting styles that leaves more
blood on the stage than any of fight co-ordinator B.H. Barry's
awkwardly choreographed battles.
   John is not the most forceful of Shakespeare's monarchs. In this
production, Kevin Conway plays him as a petulant, difficult child,
but it's still a performance with little personality. Despite a few
minor tantrums, Conway practically disappears into the dour, gray
scenery by Lindsay W. Davis. His death at the end of the play seems
little more than an aside to all the fight scenes that have gone
before.
   Jay O. Sanders is more forceful as Philip, supposedly the
illegitimate son of Richard the Lion-Hearted. Philip is the one
fictional character in the play and dominates the evening. He's a
kind of master of ceremonies, a not-disinterested everyman who
comments on and participates in the action. Sanders plays him a
little too comically, and an ill-fitting wig that makes him look
like a red-haired Prince Valiant doesn't help his performance.
   The production's best acting comes from Devon Michaels as the
young Arthur, John's nephew and the rightful heir to the throne.
He's direct and straightforward in his interpretation of the little
prince and even manages to get some of the poetry Shakespeare put
in the play.
   Mariette Hartley, late of the early morning television wars,
struggles with the role of Constance, Arthur's vengeful mother. She
has about as much success as she did on CBS, trying to wrestle
audiences away from ``Today'' and ``Good Morning, America.''
   ``King John'' is the fifth production in the New York
Shakespeare Festival's marathon of all the Bard's plays. So far,
the festival has had better luck with its exuberant renditions of
two comedies _ ``A Midsummer Night's Dream'' and ``Much Ado About
Nothing.'' The tragedies and historical dramas like ``King John''
have defeated the festival's efforts.
   In other reviews, Clive Barnes in the New York Post said, ``It
has clarity and purpose, a handful of performances worth
cherishing, a few lively sword-fights, and an interestingly
uncluttered view of Shakespeare's England through his slanted
perspective of English history.''
   Howard Kissel wrote in the Daily News: ``The production,
visually dull, is not likely to win new friends for `King John,'
but it presents the play with clarity and occasionally force.''
   Frank Rich, in The New York Times, wrote, ``Though `King John'
is far better acted than the deadly all-star `Julius Caesar' that
Mr. Vaughan fielded in the spring, it is staged in the same way:
colorless standard-issue sets and costumes, attenuated and cliched
battle sequences, a stiff front-and-center procession of scene
after scene. The play is dispensed like medicine.''
   Linda Winer wrote in Newsday that the production ``is ultimately
a provocative staging of one of Shakespeare's least familiar
history plays. Since this `John' has been directed by Stuart
Vaughan, who recently bashed `Julius Caesar' stupid with Martin
Sheen and Al Pacino, and since it costars Mariette Hartley, most
renowned from Polaroid commercials and the last failed CBS `Morning
SHow,' this accomplishment is even more of a pleasant surprise.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
