<1ST_LINE>u a PM-Death-Commutation 1stLd-Writethru a0453 08-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Death-Commutation, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0453,0552</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Board Recommends Clemency For Condemned Killer</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with 7 grafs to UPDATE with Roemer saying he will
probably delay execution. Picks up in 5th graf, `Monroe,
maintaining ...' Also incorporates correction sent as a0508.</NOTE>
<HEAD>Precede ANGOLA</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Gov. Buddy Roemer said today he will
probably delay the execution this week of a convicted killer who
has maintained his innocence for more than a decade.
   The state Pardon Board recommended Monday night that Ronald
Monroe's sentence for the 1977 stabbing death of Lenora Collins be
reduced to life imprisonment.
   Roemer said during a news conference today that Monroe's case
``has been giving me personal concern for some time.''
   Monroe, 33, is scheduled to die in the electric chair early
Thursday.
   Although Roemer said he was leaning against a commutation, he
said he probably would stay the execution for up to 100 days to
allow courts to review the case. Roemer said he would issue a
decision later in the day.
   Louisiana's three governors since the U.S. Supreme Court
reinstated the death penalty in 1976 have refused to intervene in
pending executions.
   In a brief statement, Pardon Board chairman Yvonne Campbell said
the panel found that Monroe had been deprived of due process of
law. She would not elaborate or disclose how board members voted.
   Monroe, maintaining that he had not killed Lenora Collins,
pleaded for clemency during a hearing at the Louisiana State
Penitentiary here Monday.
   ``I am innocent and will be innocent until the day I die,'' he
said.
   Prosecutors contend Collins was killed after she told Monroe he
was being evicted from an apartment in the family's duplex.
   Defense attorney Douglas Morris said a confession to Collins'
slaying by another man raised enough questions to justify a life
sentence.
   ``I think that anyone who studies the facts of this case will
realize there is a grave doubt about who committed this crime,''
Morris said.
   He said Monroe has an IQ of 77, and reads no better than a
third-grader.
   Courts have rejected the defense contention that George Stinson,
convicted in the 1980 stabbing death of his common-law wife in
Pontiac, Mich., told a cellmate, Francis Lee McWilliams, that he
killed Collins.
   McWilliams told police that Stinson said only that Collins had
been killed in the same way as his wife, according to testimony.
   Family members, including Monroe's wife, Jo Ann, and his
daughter, told the board that Monroe was quiet and introverted and
had no previous record of violence.
   The chief witnesses against Monroe in his 1980 trial were
Collins' two children, who were 11 and 12 years old when she was
slain in 1977. The daughter, Theodise, was stabbed in the back when
she tried to help her mother.
   On Monday, Theodise Collins again identified Monroe as the
killer.
   Monroe said he was sleeping in his apartment at the time of the
killing.
   The case has been through the courts several times. The U.S.
Supreme Court has rejected appeals twice. A third request to block
the execution was filed last week.
   Eighteen people have died in Louisiana's electric chair since
1976, three of them this year.
</TEXT>
