<1ST_LINE>u a AM-HandcuffRapist Bjt   08-23 0681</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Handcuff Rapist, Bjt,0696</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Persistence of Victim's Parents Lead to Arrest</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DALE LEACH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>COLUMBUS, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The parents of a rape victim staked out
the location of the attack for more than a year, with the wife as
decoy and her armed husband waiting in the dark. Their persistence
paid off with the arrest of a man police say is responsible for as
many as 60 rapes.
   ``Obviously, they had really carefully thought out what they
were going to do,'' Debra Seltzer, rape prevention coordinator of
the local chapter of Women Against Rape, said Tuesday. ``It really
shows the frustration that a lot of people feel.''
   Police on Monday announced the arrest of Robert Biddings, 34, of
Columbus, who authorities say is a suspect in a four-year string of
attacks attributed to the so-called ``handcuff rapist.'' The
nickname resulted from the use of handcuffs in early attacks later
attributed to the same man.
   Biddings was being held on one count of rape and two counts of
kidnapping in lieu of bonds totaling $750,000. But police said they
would seek to have him charged with as many as five dozen rapes.
   ``We're talking about 60 rapes and over 100 felony charges
altogether,'' said Capt. Antone Lanata.
   In announcing the arrest, police said only that they were led to
Biddings by the victim of an attempted rape who was able to give
police a license number of a car driven by her alleged assailant.
Police said they traced the car to Biddings and arrested him
Thursday.
   However, a court document shows the victim cited was a woman
whose daughter had been raped in the same spot in June 1987. The
woman was acting as a decoy to apprehend her daughter's attacker,
according to a search warrant affidavit police filed with the
Franklin County Municipal Court.
   The affidavit said the older woman was standing at a bus stop on
the city's near east side about 10:30 p.m. Aug. 5 when she was
approached by a man, grabbed from behind, carried to a nearby yard
and thrown to the ground.
   ``The suspect then produced a small, black revolver, pointed the
firearm at (the woman) and stated, `I blow your head off,''' the
affidavit says.
   The woman's husband, who had been watching from a car, then ran
up behind the man and said ``Freeze! Police!'' according to the
affidavit. The attacker fled, but the husband obtained the license
number of the man's vehicle, according to the court document.
   Police said the couple identified Biddings' photo from a group
of 11 photos. Later, their 23-year-old daughter picked Biddings'
photo from a similar group.
   The Columbus Dispatch reported in a copyright story Tuesday that
the parents had spent several nights a week for the last year in
search of their daughter's attacker, despite warnings from police
that they were placing their lives in danger and probably wasting
their time.
   The father said he knew police were understaffed and could not
spend as much time on the case as he and his wife wanted. The
Dispatch interviewed the father Monday, but efforts to reach him
Tuesday were unsuccessful. There is no listing for the couple in
the Columbus telephone directory, and the affidavit did not
identify the couple's hometown.
   Lanata refused to confirm the newspaper's account.
   ``I didn't give it to them, and I don't intend to comment on
their story,'' he said.
   Deborah Emm, author of a doctoral dissertation on survivors of
sexual assaults, said the parents' eagerness to see their
daughter's attacker brought to justice was not unusual. But their
persistence was.
   ``I certainly couldn't endorse it,'' said Ms. Emm, who is
director of Survivors of Crime, a local hospital-affiliated
organization that helps victims and their families deal with
assaults. But, she said, ``It's certainly understandable why people
would do this.''
   ``Usually, people try to do that shortly after the assault
occurs, and they're usually not successful,'' she said. ``People
who are close to a victim feel victimized themselves. Sometimes
they feel more a victim than the one who was assaulted.''
</TEXT>
