<1ST_LINE>r w AM-US-Israel     08-23 0327</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Israel,320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Criticizes Israel's Expulsion Of Palestinians</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department has questioned Israel's
expulsion of Palestinians from the troubled West Bank, but an
Israeli spokesman on Tuesday defended the policy as ``a measure of
last resort'' in dealing with agitation.
   The disagreement underscores a split between the U.S. and
Israeli governments over Palestinian unrest that has claimed more
than 200 lives in the last eight months.
   The latest U.S. complaint was registered unannounced Monday,
when Deputy Secretary of State John C. Whitehead summoned Oded
Eran, the deputy Israeli ambassador, to his office.
   On several occasions, the State Department has also taken the
public offensive against Israel on the issue by authorizing
spokesmen to criticize the expulsion of Palestinians as unjustified.
   The U.S. position is that if individuals are accused of illegal
acts they should be charged and prosecuted, not summarily banned
from the territory that Israel has held since 1967.
   State Department spokeswoman Phyllis Oakley declined Tuesday to
provide any details about Whitehead's meeting with Eran, who is in
charge of the Israeli embassy while Ambassador Moshe Arad is on
home leave.
   It was learned, however, that Whitehead, who is filling in for
the vacationing Secretary of State George P. Shultz, told Erad the
U.S. government was unhappy with the expulsions.
   Yossi Gal, the Israeli embassy spokesman, declined to describe
the session. However, he said that in trying to cope with violence
on the West Bank and in Gaza, the Israeli government uses
expulsions ``only as a last resort.''
   Gal said the expulsions are carried out ``in conformity with the
law of the land and subject to review of the Israeli high court.''
   ``It is done as a measure of last resort in order to try to
ensure public safety and is used only when we are convinced it is
the best way to handle the instigators and the inciters in the
territories,'' the spokesman added.
</TEXT>
