<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FerryRefloating     08-23 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Ferry Refloating,0323</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Historic Ferry Faces Setback</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KILEY ARMSTRONG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The sunken ferry Ellis Island, which carried 12
million immigrants to Manhattan and New Jersey, was outfitted with
pontoons Tuesday but sprang a leak before workers could refloat it.
   A Navy crew started pumping water out of the vessel at 10 a.m.
and attached pontoons to it an hour later, said Manny Strumpf, a
spokesman for the National Park Service.
   At around noon, the pressure caused an 8-foot by 12-foot plywood
patch to collapse over the engine room, and water rushed back into
the boat, said Strumpf. The pumping was halted until Wednesday.
   Strumpf said it normally would take several hours for the ferry,
aided by the rising tide, to float to the surface.
   Work began in April to refloat the vessel, which sank in 1968 in
a slip between the northern and southern portions of the 27.5-acre
island.
   The double-decked ferry began service in 1904 for what was then
the Bureau of Immigration. It made its last run Nov. 29, 1954, and
was docked at Ellis Island until it sank.
   The 160-foot-long vessel could carry 1,000 immigrants in its
hold and about 25 officials and visitors on the top. It also was
outfitted with a 12-bed sick bay and a padded cell for violent
mental patients.
   Now, all that remains of the ferry is its 160-foot by 45-foot
cast-iron hull.
   Five Naval Reserve units have removed 500 tons of mud and
patched holes in the deck. Divers brought up benches, linoleum
tile, map fixtures, pulley systems, a captain's chair and other
items.
   The Park Service decided the sunken ferry had become a
navigational hazard. The channel is being dredged for newer ferries.
   ``Its raising is the first step in resolving the problem while
respecting the ship's historical significance,'' the Park Service
said in a statement.
 
</TEXT>
</DOC>
