<DOCNO> AP880823-0110 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1403EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r w AM-DurableGoods     08-23 0627</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Durable Goods,670</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>With AM-Economy Bjt</HEAD>
<HEAD>Indicator of Demand For Manufactured Goods Down Sharply</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MARTIN CRUTSINGER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Orders for ``big ticket'' durable goods, hurt
by a drop in demand in the volatile transportation sector, fell a
sharp 7 percent in July, the biggest setback in four years, the
government reported Tuesday.
   The Commerce Department said orders for durable goods, items
expected to last at least three years, fell $8.8 billion to a
seasonally adjusted $116.6 billion last month as demand dropped off
for ships and tanks, autos and aircraft.
   The July decline was the largest since a 7.2 percent drop in
April 1984. But it followed on the heels of an 8.7 percent June
increase, which had been the largest one-month advance in more than
six years.
   Economists said they were not concerned by the turn-about,
contending that it primarily reflected the fact that orders for
expensive capital goods were notoriously volatile from month to
month. They said the July report did nothing to shake their belief
that manufacturing will remain strong in the months ahead.
   ``The July drop is not indicating any real weakness in the
industrial sector of the economy,'' said Bruce Steinberg, senior
economist at Merrill Lynch. ``The backlog of unfilled orders is
sufficiently fat that we should have very solid production gains
for the rest of the year.''
   The manufacturing sector has been one of the economy's standouts
in 1988 as American producers have benefited from a weaker dollar,
which has made their products more competitive on overseas markets.
   Analysts said that even though the dollar has been gaining in
value since June they saw little danger that American goods would
be priced out of overseas markets.
   ``July should not be seen as anything but a one-month pause in
what has been a very strong area of economic activity,'' said Allen
Sinai, chief economist of the Boston Co.
   Michael Evans, head of his own Washington-based economic
forecasting firm, said the orders report should calm inflation
fears that have been building in the financial markets because of
concerns that factory operating rates were at such high levels.
   ``The orders numbers are back to normal. Everybody knew that the
June number was a fluke,'' he said. ``This is entirely consistent
with the fact that we're going to have slower growth in the second
half.''
   The big surge in June and the hefty drop in July reflected wide
swings in orders for transportation goods, which had soared by 33.3
percent in June only to plunge 21.2 percent in July to a monthly
total of $29.7 billion.
   About half of the July drop in transportation was attributed to
a decline in defense orders for ships and tanks with the rest of
the weakness coming from declines in orders for autos and aircraft.
   Without the big swings in transportation, orders would have
fallen 0.9 percent in July after rising 0.7 percent in June.
   Military orders fell by 43.9 percent in July to $7.8 billion
following a 68.8 percent surge in this volatile category in the
previous month.
   Orders in the category of non-defense capital goods were
basically unchanged in July at $35.4 billion following a big 12.4
percent increase in June. This sector, which reflects industry
plans to expand and modernize production facilities, has been
strong all year as manufacturers have boosted spending to meet
rising export demand.
   Orders for primary metals such as steel dropped 0.3 percent in
July to $12.2 billion, the second consecutive small monthly decline.
   Orders for the machinery category which includes computers fell
5.6 percent to $20.7 billion while a second machinery category rose
3.8 percent to $19.2 billion.
   Shipments of durable goods dropped 2.6 percent to $113.4 billion
following a 1.5 percent increase in June.
</TEXT>
