<1ST_LINE>u a PM-HueyNewton     08-23 0389</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Huey Newton,0398</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former Black Panther Refuses Prison Release</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther Huey Newton told
officials today that he won't leave the prison where he's been
serving time for a parole violation unless a fellow inmate and
former Panther is also released.
   The other inmate _ convicted killer Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt _
two weeks ago lost his eighth bid for parole after a state panel
called him a ``danger to the public.''
   Pratt, a former deputy defense minister of the Black Panther
Party, is serving a life term for murdering a Santa Monica woman
during a $30 robbery. He was convicted in 1972 of killing
27-year-old Caroline Olsen.
   Pratt's supporters contend that he is a political prisoner and
the victim of police efforts to jail Panther leaders and dismantle
the Oakland-based radical movement of the late 1960s and early 70s.
   San Quentin spokeswoman Jeanne Ballatore said that prison
officers filed a disciplinary action against Newton for refusing to
obey a direct order by guards to prepare for his release today. He
was serving a 60-day sentence.
   A state parole board panel at the prison will hold an informal
hearing today to review the case and decide whether the offense
merits additional time in custody, she said.
   Newton has the option of accepting their recommendation and
remaining in prison if that is their finding, Ballatore said.
   Whatever the board rules, Newton may refuse the recommendation
and remain in custody pending a complete hearing, she said.
   Newton was charged with the 1967 killing of an Oakland policeman
and convicted of manslaughter, but that conviction was overturned
on appeal after he served two years in prison. The charge was
dropped after two retrials ended in hung juries.
   He was convicted in 1974, because of an assault conviction in
1964, of possessing a firearm allegedly used in the pistol-whipping
of his tailor. He then fled the country and lived for three years
in Cuba. He was acquitted of a charge of assault in connection with
the incident.
   Newton is scheduled to finish parole on Feb. 8, 1989.
   He was jailed at San Quentin for parole violations that included
failure to submit to drug testing and failure to advise his parole
officer that he had been arrested for investigation of driving
under the influence of alcohol or drugs.
</TEXT>
