<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Women-Satisfaction     08-23 0223</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Women-Satisfaction,0229</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Poll: Married Women More Likely to be Very Satisfied</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Married women aged 18-44 are nearly twice as
likely as unmarried women to say they are very satisfied with life,
according to a Gallup poll released Tuesday.
   Overall, 44 percent in the national survey of 1,000 women said
they were very satisfied with their lives and another 44 percent
said they were mostly satisfied, as opposed to the third choice,
not satisfied.
   Money, marriage and part-time employment were the most common
factors. Fifty-seven percent of women with family incomes of
$35,000 or more said they were very satisfied, compared to 29
percent of women with incomes less than $15,000.
   Similarly, 53 percent of married women said they were very
satisfied, compared to 23 percent of unmarried women. And 52
percent of women who work part time said they were very satisfied,
compared to 41 percent of full-time workers.
   Of those with children, 46 percent said they were very satisfied
with their lives. Of those with no children, only slightly fewer,
39 percent, took that choice.
   The poll's margin of error for the entire sample was plus or
minus three points, but as in all polls it was greater for
subgroups. The poll, conducted by telephone June 17-21, was
commissioned by Ortho Pharmaceutical Corp., which makes
birth-control products.
</TEXT>
