<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PurseReturned     08-23 0233</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Purse Returned,0240</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Purse Returned After 35 Years</HEAD>
<DATELINE>DANA POINT, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The money was gone but the memories
remained locked in a purse stolen 35 years ago.
   Mary Ellen Thomas remembers the night of Aug. 15, 1953, whe she
had just cashed her $120.25 paycheck for two weeks' work as a
cashier at the Cal-Neva Lodge in Crystal Bay, Nev., on the north
shore of Lake Tahoe.
   She was 22-year-old Mary Ellen Hall then, and a New York steak
cost $2.75.
   She remembers that it was her first summer away from home and
she had a get-together with friends to celebrate payday.
   At evening's end she rode back to the hotel with a co-worker who
made some unsuccesful advances. He was so mad, she remembers he
snatched her handbag.
   But last week the owner of the Cal-Neva Lodge, Charles Bluth,
presented Ms. Thomas with the handbag, uncovered last summer during
remodeling. The purse was stashed inside a wall.
   The 57-year-old retired teacher from Dana Point was tracked down
through her Social Security number.
   ``I'd like to think I've changed. I'm not so naive,'' Ms. Thomas
said. ``But in many ways, I'm very much the same.''
   Ms. Thomas will keep her purse for a while to show off to
friends. But she's promised to return it to the Cal-Neva Lodge
where it will become a part of the lodge's history display.
</TEXT>
