<1ST_LINE>r p PM-Reagan-Fundraiser 2ndLd-Writethru a0608 08-23 0474</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reagan-Fundraiser, 2nd Ld-Writethru, a0608,480</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>For Release 4:25 p.m. EDT</NOTE>
<HEAD>Bush, Quayle Are `Winners;' Dukakis, Bentsen Just `3rd Stringers'
_ Reagan</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Subs graf 3, he made no, to describe controversy over Quayle.
Inserts graf6, Earlier in the, with quote on Quayle. Removes last 3
grafs pvs as outdated.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By W. DALE NELSON</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>IRVINE, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan predicted today that he
will be succeeded by George Bush and Dan Quayle because ``America
is not going to trade away our winning team for third-stringers.''
   In remarks prepared for delivery at a $500-a-person fund-raising
luncheon for Sen. Pete Wilson, R-Calif., Reagan described the
Republican Party as ``strong, unified and ready to work for
victory.''
   He made no reference in his prepared remarks to the controversy
surrounding Bush's choice of Quayle, a second-term GOP senator from
Indiana, as his running mate. Quayle has been the subject of
controversy for joining the Indiana National Guard during the
Vietnam war, making himself immune from the draft.
   ``America is not going to trade away our winning team for
third-stringers with a weak defense, a foreign policy of errors,
curve-ball campaign promises, a set of policies to be named later,
and billions of dollars in higher taxes,'' the president said.
   Democratic presidential nominee Michael Dukakis told a news
conference in Beverly, Mass., ``I think it will be the American
people who decide who belongs in the major leagues and who belongs
in the bush leagues. I think it's Dukakis and (Democratic vice
presidential candidate Lloyd) Bentsen who belong in the major
leagues.''
   Earlier in the day, Reagan was asked by reporters after a
signing ceremony for trade legislation if Bush should drop Quayle
from the Republican ticket. ``No. He's a fine man and
well-qualified,'' Reagan responded.
   Urging the re-election of Wilson, who faces a challenge from
Democratic Lt. Gov. Leo McCarthy, Reagan said he sees ``a real
chance that Pete may be part of a Republican majority in the
Senate.''
   ``And wouldn't that be a nice gift for President George Bush and
Vice President Dan Quayle?'' he asked.
   Reagan said that, in 1984, ``our opponents, wrongheaded as their
policies may have been, at least ran in the clear light of day,''
he said. ``They ran as the liberals they were.''
   ``But that has changed,'' he said. ``The first sign of this
deceptive strategy came in 1986, when many of their liberal Senate
candidates ran stealth campaigns, avoiding the tough issues and
using the language of conservatism to conceal their true beliefs.''
   ``In 1988, we are seeing this kind of covert liberalism at the
national level and to an extraordinary degree,'' the president said.
   Reagan will meet privately with Bush on Wednesday before they
appear together at a rally in Los Angeles. It will be their first
meeting since controversy erupted over Bush's selection of Quayle.
</TEXT>
