<1ST_LINE>u w AM-Economy 1stLd-Writethru a0587 08-23 0814</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Economy, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0587,800</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drought Effect Shows Up at Supermarket</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Inserts 2 grafs after 13th graf, ``This should,'' with
earnings report</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By MATT YANCEY</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Labor Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grocery prices jumped 1.4 percent in July, the
biggest monthly increase since early 1984, as the drought's effects
reached supermarket checkout counters, the government said Tuesday.
   But there was little evidence of accelerating retail price
inflation elsewhere in the U.S. economy. Excluding food, overall
retail prices rose just 0.3 percent for the month, slower than the
pace of the first half of 1987, the Labor Department said.
   Including the drought-related price spikes for food _ which
accounts for about one-sixth of people's spending _ consumer prices
rose 0.4 percent in July, an annual rate of 5.2 percent.
   ``Despite all the talk about inflationary pressures, it's very
difficult to find much in the way of evidence of it, even with this
huge increase for food,'' said Sandra Shaber, an economist for the
Futures Group, a Washington consulting firm.
   Energy costs were up 0.3 percent, largely because of 0.7 percent
rise in gasoline prices, but both home heating oil and electric
rates declined. Even with the July increase, gasoline prices are
still lower than they were last December and 28.1 percent below
their peak in March 1981.
   Housing expenses _ which account for 42 percent of what people
spend _ rose at the same 0.3 percent monthly pace they have
maintained since February, with slightly lower repair costs
offsetting slightly higher rents and mortgage payments.
   Retail auto prices were unchanged and clothing prices dropped
0.6 percent, the second consecutive monthly decline, despite
increases in both on the wholesale level in July, the Labor
Department said.
   Economists said it is becoming increasingly apparent that retail
outlets are finding it harder to pass along wholesale price
increases.
   ``The real question is whether some of it will start seeping
through; there certainly hasn't been the surge that people worried
about,'' said Larry Chimerine of the WEFA Group, a Bala Cynwyd,
Pa., economic forecasting firm.
   ``We're seeing a lot more consumer resistence than we used to,
and that is going to keep inflation down,'' said Michael Evans, a
Washington economic consultant. ``Part of it is the availability of
imports, but consumers also have become so use to rebates and sales
that they won't buy without them.''
   Meanwhile, the Commerce Department reported that orders for
``big ticket'' durable goods plunged 7 percent in July, the biggest
drop in four years, primarly because of huge declines in orders for
cars and decreased military purchases.
   The decline had been anticipated after durable-goods orders
skyrocketed 8.7 percent in June, the biggest monthly increase in
more than six years.
   ``This should not be taken as anything more than a one-month
pause in what has been a very strong area of economic activiity,''
said Allen Sinai of the Boston Co., a New York financial consultant.
   In a third report, the Labor Department said Americans' average
weekly earnings, after adjusting for inflation, climbed 0.6 percent
in July, the best showing since a 1.2 percent increase in April.
   Workers benefited from a rise in hourly earnings plus an
increase in the number of hours worked, which was only partially
offset by the boost in consumer prices in July. The advance left
Americans' inflation-adjusted earnings 0.2 percent higher than they
were a year ago.
   The higher food prices from the four months of dry weather in
the Farm Belt had been anticipated and, if anything, analysts were
surprised that they were not bigger.
   ``The food prices increases are not that big or that
unexpected,'' said Chimerine. ``We'll have a second round of
drought-related increases later on, but it's not going to be a
phenomenal increase.''
   The 1.4 percent gain in grocery store prices was led by a 9.6
percent jump in egg costs, a 7.4 percent boost for poultry and a
4.7 percent gain for fresh fruits and vegetables.
   ``These increases reflect rising input prices, at least
partially due to the adverse summer weather,'' the Labor Department
said.
   Cereal and bakery product prices gained 1.1 percent, while
cooking oil posted a 1.0 percent price increase.
   Despite widespread increases for most foods, meat costs overall
declined slightly as drought-stricken farmers trimmed their herds.
Pork prices dropped 2.2 percent and beef and veal prices rose just
0.1 percent.
   The second major food price spike resulting from the drought is
not expected until the end of this year or early 1989 as meat
shortages from the early slaughters start showing up.
   Food costs overall rose 1.0 percent in July; slower advances of
0.5 percent and 0.4 percent, respectively, were posted for
restaurant meals and alcoholic beverages.
   For the first seven months of 1988, inflation on the retail
level is running at an annual rate of 4.5 percent, just a tick
above the 4.4 percent rate for all of 1987.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
