<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FoliagePredictions     08-23 0343</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Foliage Predictions,0350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Foliage Experts See Colorful Season Ahead</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JILL ARABAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>MONTPELIER, Vt. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   This year's hot, dry weather should not
keep Vermont's trees from displaying their famous array of fall
colors, but the dry spell could prompt the trees to turn color
early, experts said Tuesday.
   ``Here and there on the hillsides you've got an occasional tree
that's starting to turn, although it's nothing to get alarmed
about,'' said Arlo Sterner of Wolcott, who's been monitoring
foliage for the state for 40 years.
   ``I don't want to sound like the perennial hyper-salesperson,
but I really think we can look forward to some gorgeous foliage
this fall,'' said George Buzzell, a forester from Newport who also
surveys foliage for the Vermont Travel Division. ``If you plan to
come to Vermont, be prepared to pick up a lot of film and use it.''
   Vermont's precipitation is 5 inches below normal so far this
year, the National Weather Service said. The state also experienced
an infestation from an insect called the pear thrips, which
defoliated nearly 500,000 acres, mostly in southern Vermont, but
foresters say those trees grew a second set of leaves.
   Predicting the start of the season is always difficult, but it
usually begins the second week of September in the northern part of
the state and lasts through most of October.
   The season's length and brilliance are affected by rainfall,
sun, temperature and other weather factors. Too much sun, rain or
heat retard the foliage.
   Sterner and Joe Luisi of the weather service said a dry year
usually means an earlier season. Luisi said a spell of chilly
weather next month also could prompt the leaves to turn.
   The uncertainty doesn't seem to have discouraged prospective
visitors. Inns and lodges are booking their usual throng of autumn
customers, and the state Travel Division is swamped with telephone
calls.
   Division spokesman John Cashman said the peak weekend of Oct.
8-10 should be especially busy because Oct. 10 is not only Columbus
Day, but Thanksgiving Day in Canada.
</TEXT>
