<1ST_LINE>u w AM-US-Poland     08-23 0372</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Poland,360</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>US Urges Poland To Reconcile, Not Intimidate Strikers</HEAD>
<HEAD>With AM-Poland Bjt</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By BARRY SCHWEID</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Diplomatic Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The State Department on Tuesday urged the
Polish government to employ reconciliation, not force, in dealing
with spreading labor unrest.
   ``Free labor unions can help the Polish economic reform effort,
not hinder it,'' said a statement read by spokeswoman Phyllis
Oakley.
   ``Indeed, it is hard to see how economic reform can succeed
without the participation of free trade unions. Economic reform is
a truly national undertaking. It must include all the people.''
   The mildly worded statement contained no direct criticism of the
Polish government. U.S.-Polish relations have improved since
martial law was lifted in 1983, but the ban on the Solidarity labor
movement remained and the statement concentrated on that issue.
   ``As tension mounts in Poland, the United States continues to
encourage dialogue and national reconciliation,'' it said, ``not
confrontation and intimidation by force as the means to resolve
Poland's difficulties.''
   The Polish government has imposed special security measures and
scheduled a session of Parliament next Wednesday to try to cope
with the worst strikes since 1981.
   In Warsaw, Interior Minister Czeslaw Kiszczak said at least 20
illegal strikes had threatened anarchy in the country. Polish
authorities have denounced the organizers as outside agitators and
even terrorists.
   Mrs. Oakley said, however, the strikes were ``a clear indication
of the wishes of the Polish people and their support for
Solidarity.''
   She said Poland needed economic reform and that trade unions
should play an important role.
   ``The United States is watching developments in Poland
closely,'' the statement said.
   In a separate statement, the State Department accused the
government of Czechoslovakia of using force against peaceful
demonstrators and urged the release of dozens who were detained.
   The demonstration in Prague on Sunday marked the 20th
anniversary of the use of Soviet troops to crush a reform movement
in the Warsaw Pact country.
   ``The demonstration points once more to the pressing need for
the Czechoslovak government to re-evaluate the tragic events of
1968 and address the legacy of political repression and economic
stagnation,'' the department said.
   It called the demonstration ``an apparently spontaneous
outpouring of frustration and hope by the people of
Czechoslovakia.''
</TEXT>
