<HEAD>Mother Ordered to Trial for Allegedly Stashing Cocaine in Girl's
Backpack</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The mother of a 7-year-old girl, who found a
golf ball-sized chunk of cocaine in her backpack and shared it with
school chums, was ordered to stand trial on charges of drug
possession and child endangerment.
   Maria Christina Torres, 39, of Topanga, accused of stashing the
cocaine in daughter Angelina's backpack in June, was told Monday to
return Sept. 6 for arraignment on two felony counts. She remains
free on $25,000 bail.
   Angelina, subpoenaed as a prosecution witness, testified she
found the cocaine while looking through her backpack at school. She
later tasted it and shared it with schoolmates.
   If convicted, Torres faces up to seven years in prison, said
Deputy District Attorney Larry Diamond.
   Defense attorney Richard A. Walton argued there was no proof his
client intended to sell the cocaine and that there was insufficient
evidence to support a child endangering charge.
