<DOCNO> AP880823-0128 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1540EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Panama-Analysis Bjt   08-23 0715</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Panama-Analysis, Bjt,0735</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Noriega Opposition in Limbo</HEAD>
<HEAD>An AP Analysis</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By REID G. MILLER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>PANAMA CITY, Panama (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Neither public protest nor U.S.
pressure has budged Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega, and the Panamanian
movement to oust the nation's de facto ruler appears mired in
uncertainty and despair.
   Noriega's political foes did not even draw much enthusiasm from
a huge anti-government demonstration that accompanied the funeral
Aug. 15 of a revered former president whom the military threw out
of office three times.
   Tens of thousands of people marched 40 and 50 abreast in the
funeral procession for Arnulfo Arias Madrid, but Roberto Aleman, a
leader of the opposition alliance, discounted its significance.
   ``In the short and medium term, I doubt that it will mean
much,'' he said. ``In the longer term, we may see some life put
back into the movement or we may see it fractionalized. The thing
is, Arnulfo is gone but Noriega's still here.''
   Behind Aleman's assessment was his concern, shared by other
opposition leaders, that the death could split the Authentic
Panamanian Party, which Arias founded and built into the country's
largest opposition force.
   ``There's no one of Arias Madrid's stature in the wings, but if
his followers can unite around someone it would certainly
strengthen the entire opposition movement,'' a Western diplomat
said privately. ``If they don't, the party is likely to be split
into a number of competing factions and that would just muddy
things up.''
   Noriega has weathered a 14-month-old opposition campaign to
force him out as commander of the 15,000-member Panama Defense
Forces, which include the armed forces and police.
   U.S. economic sanctions against Panama and federal indictments
on charges of drug trafficking and money laundering have had little
visible impact on Noriega's standing.
   Eric Arturo Delvalle, the president Noriega put into office,
rebelled and tried to fire the general a few days after the U.S.
indictments were handed up in February. Noriega arranged for the
National Assembly, which he controls, to dismiss Delvalle instead.
   In speeches, interviews and billboard advertisements, Noriega
says the government will hold a presidential election as planned in
May 1989.
   The main questions are whether Noriega will seek the presidency
and whether the opposition can unite long enough to defeat either
the general or the candidate he chooses. Some opposition leaders
speak of boycotting the election, but most do not see that as an
option.
   Another diplomat said: ``The U.S. sanctions haven't driven
Noriega out, it is doubtful they (Washington) will try a military
solution and there's no one in Panama who can singlehandedly carry
the opposition banner. The people are being driven to despair.
   ``There are a lot of people out there who are against Noriega _
very easily the majority, I'd say _ but they feel abandoned by the
United States and there's not one single opposition leader with
whom they feel comfortable.''
   Morton Abramowitz, U.S. assistant secretary of state for
inter-American affairs, visited Panama two weeks ago. Opposition
leaders who met him said he offered nothing new.
   One said, on condition his name not be used: ``I got the
impression that nothing will happen until after the (U.S.)
election, and then who knows what?'' Some observers had expected
Noriega to announce his presidential candidacy Aug. 12, his fifth
anniversary as commander of the Defense Forces.
   Noriega dropped no hints at the celebration, however. Instead,
he delivered another diatribe against the United States, accusing
it of creating a crisis in Panama to negate the 1977 treaties that
turn the Panama Canal over to Panama on Dec. 31, 1999.
   ``Many Panamanians wrongly thought that with the new treaties of
1977, Panama and the United States were beginning a permanent
honeymoon, forgetting that for the United States a treaty is no
more ... than a useful but ephemeral act,'' Noriega declared.
   On Sunday, the Panama Defense Forces rejected charges that its
troops are harassing U.S. military personnel and called the
accusations part of an effort to undermine the government.
   Its statement injected a note of sarcasm by saying U.S.
officials who make such accusations ``must have the IQ of a
3-year-old Cro-Magnon.''
</TEXT>
<NOTE>EDITOR'S NOTE </NOTE>
<TEXT>
   Reid G. Miller, a roving correspondent based in
San Jose, Costa Rica, has covered Central America for The
Associated Press since 1984.
</TEXT>
