<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1635EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ConsultantTheft     08-23 0520</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Consultant Theft,0535</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Army Charges Pratt Consultant Stole Report By Rival</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HARTFORD, Conn. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Pratt & Whitney quickly dismissed a
consultant who the Army said stole a sensitive report by a rival in
a helicopter-engine competition, but the Army said it lacked the
evidence to press charges.
   An internal report obtained by The Hartford Courant said
consultant William Henry Maloney, 50, stole a 358-page progress
report on the LHTEC T-800 turbine helicopter-engine program from an
office of the Army Materiel Command's Aviation Branch on Dec. 8,
1986.
   Maloney, who was chief of the Aviation Branch until his
retirement as a colonel in 1984, returned the report two hours
later after an Army engineer noticed it missing and asked about it.
Maloney also lied about the incident, the Army said.
   Maloney said Monday that he is innocent of any criminal conduct.
``I did something stupid, but I didn't do anything wrong,'' he said.
   Maloney told the Courant he didn't take the report.
   The Army said the case is unrelated to the Justice Department
investigation into allegations of bribery and bid-rigging in
Pentagon procurement. Under scrutiny in that probe are consultants
for Pratt and Norden Systems, both divisions of Hartford-based
United Technologies Corp.
   LHTEC is a partnership of two major engine builders, the Allison
Gas Turbine Division of General Motors and the Garrett Engine
Division of Allied Signal Aerospace Co.
   LHTEC is competing against the team of Pratt and Textron
Lycoming of Stratford, Conn., to develop the T-800.
   At stake are $3.5 billion in T-800 production contracts and
domination of a class of turbine engines that can power smaller
airplanes, including business jets, as well as helicopters.
   William C. Campbell, director of communications for Allison,
said the report was a detailed account of LHTEC's progress in
developing the T-800, including technical information of keen
interest to competitors. But he said he wasn't sure the data would
give a rival an edge in competition for the T-800 contract.
   The Courant obtained the internal report of the Army's
investigation into the incident under the Freedom of Information
Act and reported on it in Tuesday's editions.
   Eugene J. Tallia, chief of Pratt's Washington office, said the
company suspended Maloney, who was under a one-year contract, eight
days after the incident. Maloney never offered to give Pratt the
LHTEC data, Tallia said.
   Army lawyers concluded there was probable cause to believe
Maloney committed ``criminal conversion,'' a theft in which a
perpetrator doesn't intend to permanently keep a stolen item, and
gave a false sworn statement to investigators.
   But Col. Anthony Wagner, deputy command counsel for the Army
Materiel Command, said no charges have been filed against Maloney
because Pratt denied ever having received or used information from
the report, leaving no way to prove criminal intent.
   He said the Army Materiel Command has barred Maloney from its
offices and Army investigators are holding Maloney's Pentagon pass.
   Maloney now works as senior Washington, D.C., representative for
the Northrop Corp. of Los Angeles, a major aircraft manufacturer.
   John Thorne, a spokesman for Northrop, said he couldn't comment
on the Army report because he hadn't read it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
