<1ST_LINE>d a AM-BRF--PlaneSeizure     08-23 0189</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-BRF--Plane Seizure,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bolivian Passenger Jet Seized For Cocaine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MIAMI (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   U.S. Customs seized a Bolivian passenger jet
Tuesday after inspectors found 46 pounds of cocaine in a box not
listed on the manifest, officials said.
   Lloyd Aereo Bolivian Flight 900 from Santa Cruz, Bolivia, landed
at Miami International Airport just before 7 a.m. Tuesday after a
stop in Panama.
   Customs agents saw a cardboard box that was not on the manifest
unloaded from the belly of the Boeing 727, said spokesman Cliff
Stallings.
   ``Inside was 46 pounds of cocaine wrapped in black plastic,
coated in heavy grease, and placed inside a plexiglass box inside
the cardboard box,'' Stallings said.
   The cocaine discovery was the ninth aboard an LAB plane since
March 5, 1986, for a total of 412 pounds, Stallings said.
   But the seizure of the aircraft was the Bolivian carrier's
first. He noted that Bolivia has signed the international treaty
requiring tough drug inspections and security, and which allows the
seizures.
   To reclaim the plane, LAB could have to pay a fine of up to
$1,000 per ounce of cocaine, or about $736,000, Stallings said.
</TEXT>
