<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Harris     08-23 0352</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Harris,0363</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Scarsdale Diet Doctor Killer Now Eligible For Clemency</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BEDFORD HILLS, N.Y. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jean Harris became eligible for
executive clemency Tuesday, 7{ years after she went to prison for
the murder of the developer of the Scarsdale Diet, Dr. Herman
Tarnower.
   Mrs. Harris, 65, who recently wrote a book on her experiences at
the Bedford Hills Correctional Facility, will ask Gov. Mario Cuomo
to grant clemency because of her age, poor health including two
heart attacks in prison, and good prison record, according to her
attorney, Michael Kennedy.
   State law requires an inmate to serve half the minimum prison
term before becoming eligible for executive clemency, an act that
commutes a sentence and allows an inmate to become eligible for
parole.
   Final release must be granted by the State Parole Board.
   Mrs. Harris, a former girls school headmistress, was sentenced
to 15 years to life.
   She was convicted of second-degree murder for the shooting of
Tarnower in the cardiologist's home in Purchase on March 10, 1980.
While she has always contended that Tarnower died as a result of
her own suicide attempt, prosecutors contended Mrs. Harris shot her
lover of 14 years during a jealous rage over a romance with a
younger woman.
   Anne Lennox, who heads a group fighting for Mrs. Harris'
freedom, has said the group is seeking to give the governor
petitions bearing 10,000 signatures to show support for clemency.
   Two years ago, Mrs. Harris sought a waiver of the minimum time
requirement to seek clemency. The governor's Executive Clemency
Board denied the request.
   Anne Crowley, a spokeswoman for Cuomo, said Mrs. Harris'
application would be reviewed as are all requests.
   Authorities will seek comment from the sentencing judge and the
Westchester County district attorney's office, as well as the head
of Bedford Hills.
   Russell Leggett, who presided over the trial and has since
retired to private practice, has gone on record favoring clemency.
The district attorney's office has not commented.
   Ms. Crowley said it was possible the review of Mrs. Harris'
petition may not be completed by the Christmas season, when Cuomo
usually grants clemencies.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
