<1ST_LINE>r w AM-ConservationPlans     08-23 0174</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Conservation Plans,170</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farm Conservation Planning More Than One-Third Complete</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers have developed conservation plans for
protecting 54 million acres of highly erodible cropland, about 38
percent of the 143 million acres targeted for planning by the 1985
farm law, the Agriculture Department said Tuesday.
   Wilson Scaling, chief of the Soil Conservation Service, said
plans have actually been put into effect on 17 million acres, or
about 12 percent of the affected land.
   Under the 1985 law, farmers who raise crops on highly erodible
land must have a conservation plan approved by Dec. 31, 1989, and
implement it fully by Dec. 31, 1994, to remain eligible for USDA
program benefits.
   ``We are on target for meeting the 1989 deadline,'' Scaling
said. ``We hope to have 65 percent of the plans completed by the
end of 1988 and the remaining 35 percent completed by end of 1989.''
   However, Scaling cautioned farmers not to wait until the last
minute to request technical assistance from SCS because they might
have a long wait.
</TEXT>
