<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1844EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MigrantShortage     08-23 0319</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Migrant Shortage,0327</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Farmers Report Shortage Of Migrant Workers</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SHARPSVILLE, Ind. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Some of Indiana's produce that survived
the drought may rot in the fields because of a shortage of migrant
workers, a state official said Tuesday.
   Eldon Smith and his son, Scott, said the drought has delayed the
crops at their Sharp-View Farms Inc. by a few weeks, but their 300
acres of tomatoes and 80 acres of cucumbers have had a strong
finish.
   ``It's as good as any year we've ever had. We just don't have
the labor,'' said Scott Smith.
   In a normal year, the two crops are staggered so the harvest is
spread over several weeks. This year's dry conditions, however,
forced the Smiths to plant the tomatoes later than usual, so the
crops have come in at the same time.
   Michelle Moscato, who heads the migrant services division of the
state Department of Human Services, said the same problem is
generating demand for more labor throughout the state at a time
when migrant workers are relatively scarce.
   Ms. Moscato said the number of migrant workers who came to
Indiana this summer is up 10 percent to 15 percent to 3,800 to
4,000.
   ``But people are not staying because the work is not good,'' she
said.
   This week, the Smiths employed 40 migrant workers, compared with
the 80 usually hired at this time. The farm could use 120 workers
this year, so the 40 who are there must work sunrise to sunset,
seven days a week, the elder Smith said.
   ``People are working long hours and are making $30 to $40 a
week. The tomatoes are very small and it's taking two or three
times as long to fill a basket,'' Ms. Moscato said.
   While cucumber harvesters usually are paid an hourly rate,
tomato pickers are paid 28 cents to 35 cents a bushel basket,
compared with at least 35 cents last year.
</TEXT>
