<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Contract-DefenseProbe     08-23 0340</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Contract-Defense Probe,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Congressmen Urge New Rules On Defense Contracts</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By TIM AHERN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Seven senior members of the House Armed
Services Committee said Tuesday the Pentagon should add a clause to
future defense contracts to ensure that any illegally gained
profits can be recovered by the government.
   ``There is an urgent need to protect both the national security
and the interests of the U.S. taxpayer in defense procurement,''
they said in a statement.
   ``A clause in all future contracts allowing the Defense
Department to recover the profit from illegally obtained contracts
would go a long way toward doing that,'' it said.
   The statement arises from the current Pentagon bribery
investigation, which involves allegations that private consultants
illegally bought information about future contracts from Defense
Department employees. No charges have been filed in the case, which
became public June 14.
   Defense Secretary Frank C. Carlucci and other top Pentagon
officials have said that if any of the contracts involved in the
investigation turned out to have been won on the basis of illegal
information, the Pentagon can use existing laws to recover the
profits.
   Carlucci last month ordered that a new clause be inserted into
some contracts with firms involved in the investigation.
   The clause should be put into all contracts, the statement said.
   ``Without such protection, the government is not in a position
to feel comfortable entering into future contracts'' with any of
the defense firms mentioned in the investigation, the statement
said.
   The clause could replace some of the legions of auditors who now
check contracts, said Rep. William Dickinson, R-Ala., ranking
Republican on the panel.
   ``We've got so many regulations now it takes two men to buy an
aspirin tablet, one to fill out the papers and one to audit them,''
he said. ``By the time they're finished, they've both got a new
headache.''
   The letter was signed by Dickinson and Reps. Larry Hopkins,
D-Ky.; John Kasich, R-Ohio; Jim Courter, R-N.J.; Bill Nichols,
D-Ala.; Nicholas Mavroules, D-Mass.; and Les Aspin, D-Wis.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
