<1ST_LINE>r a AM-ManholeFire     08-23 0380</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Manhole Fire,0392</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Manhole Fire Forces Back Bay Blackout</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Connoly is cq in last graf.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BOSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Offices were emptied, businesses closed and
commuters were stalled Tuesday when officials cut power to part of
downtown Boston for two hours following an electrical fire
triggered by a crew searching for an underground gas leak.
   A Boston Edison Co. spokesman said 12,500 residential and
business customers lost electricity after the Fire Department
ordered power cut around 9:20 a.m. to battle a fire that spewed
flames and thick black smoke from a manhole in the Back Bay section
of Boston.
   The outage affected parts of the city's central shopping area
and several major hotels.
   Firefighter Bill Murphy said a crew contracted by Boston Gas Co.
accidently cut Edison's cables with a backhoe, causing a short
circuit that sparked the fire.
   The fire burned for 35 minutes and caused $50,000 of damage to
Edison's cables before firefighters extinguished the flames with
two foam-spraying trucks and more than 1,000 pounds of dry powder,
Murphy said.
   ``It cut us off before we opened. We just worked in the dark and
shelved books,'' said Beth Wong, an employee at B. Dalton
Bookseller.
   Several people were trapped briefly in elevators at the 52-story
Prudential office tower. Offices in the building were closed and
workers were told to evacuate.
   At the Top of the Hub restaurant, on the building's top floor, a
normally busy pre-lunch time was very quiet, but some employees
decided to stay. ``All I know is I'm not walking down 52 stories,''
said Leslie Dempsey.
   About 300 delegates to a Ford Motor Co. convention were
evacuated from the Massachusetts Convention Center, said Ernest
Lucci, director of marketing.
   A back-up generator and a skylight kept the Neiman Marcus store
in the posh Copley Place shopping mall bright, but cash registers
remained still.
   The Massachusetts Bay Transportation Authority evacuated and
closed five darkened subway stations, but trains continued.
   Police stationed extra motorcycle policemen in the area to
direct traffic after signal lights went dark, spokeswoman Jill
Reilly said.
   Power was restored after about two hours to all but 23 buildings
near the fire. Edison spokesman Bill Connoly said officials did not
know when the remaining customers would receive electricity.
</TEXT>
