<1ST_LINE>r a AM-PayolaLawsuit     08-23 0305</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Payola Lawsuit,0313</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>$25 Million Antitrust Suit Dropped</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LOS ANGELES (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has dismissed a $25 million
antitrust lawsuit against MCA Records and the Warner Communications
labels brought by a record promoter under scrutiny in a nationwide
payola investigation.
   During a five-minute hearing Monday, U.S. District Judge
Consuelo B. Marshall decided to dismiss the suit, reversing a
decision she made in June.
   Marshall said that after reviewing MCA's and Warner's motion for
dismissal, she decided her previous ruling was incorrect.
   The 2-year-old action was filed by independent record promoter
Joseph Isgro, who accused MCA, Warner and 10 other record companies
of conspiring to boycott his services.
   All the other record companies settled out of court.
   Attorneys Steven Cannata and Lawrence Papale, representing
Isgro, were very surprised by the judge's decision.
   ``It was the same motion, word for word, that she already
denied,'' Cannata said. Papale said the ruling would probably be
appealed.
   ``MCA continues to deny there was conspiracy in the first
place,'' said Brad Phillips, a lawyer with the firm representing
MCA. He contended that Isgro could not have proven that there was
an antitrust violation.
   MCA is still suing Isgro, claiming civil racketeering against
the promoter. The judge, on Monday, dismissed a similar complaint
filed by Warner, saying Warner's complaint against Isgro was not
specific enough. Warner, however, has 30 days to amend its
complaint.
   Isgro drew attention in the payola scandal in 1986 when NBC News
portrayed him as being associated with organized crime. After the
telecast, all major record companies announced they would suspend
use of independent promoters.
   Isgro has denied any connection with payola practices, but he is
the focus of a federal grand jury probe. His former business
associates, Ralph Tashjian and Bill Craig, were indicted in January
of several payola and tax evasion charges.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
