<1ST_LINE>r w AM-Meat-Poultry     08-23 0375</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Meat-Poultry,350</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Cattle Fattened For Slaughter Bringing Higher Prices</HEAD>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Cattle fattened for the slaughter market are
bringing higher prices this month, reflecting fewer animals and a
strong consumer demand for beef, the Agriculture Department said
Tuesday.
   In all, cattle slaughter in August may rise only 8 percent from
July, the department's Economic Research Service said in an updated
review of the livestock and poultry situation.
   Officials gave the 8 percent forecast even though August has two
more working days at plants than July, which raised speculation
that cattle slaughter might rise by as much as 10 percent this
month.
   ``Cow slaughter has begun picking up,'' the report said.
``However, this appears to be a seasonal movement of beef cows off
grass (pasture) rather than a forced drought movement.''
   There had been an increase in cow slaughter earlier this summer
as some producers in the drought-stricken Northern Plains and in
the Lakes states were forced to send beef and dairy cows to market
because of feed shortages.
   In many cases, however, breeding animals have been purchased by
producers in other areas where feed is available, thus forestalling
massive sell-offs of herds.
   According to federal inspection reports, the slaughter of beef
cows this year through the first week in August totaled about 1.89
million head, down 9 percent from the same period in 1987. Dairy
cow slaughter, at 1.66 million head, dropped 3 percent.
   Prices of fed cattle in the southern Great Plains are selling
for more than $70 per 100 pounds of live weight in late August, up
from $66 in July, the report said.
   Beef from cows goes mainly into hamburger and processing, while
grain-fed steers and heifers provide the higher-grade cuts found in
supermarkets.
   Looking at pork, the report said weekly slaughter is expected to
increase sharply in September, pushing prices down.
   Meanwhile, hot weather has disrupted marketings and slowed
weight gains of hogs. That has lent some support to ``an otherwise
weak market'' this summer, the report said.
   Wholesale prices of dressed broiler chickens in early August
remained around 70 cents a pound, well above the 53 cents of a year
earlier. Prices should average around 61 to 65 cents a pound during
the third quarter, the report said.
</TEXT>
