<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Britain-IRA     08-23 0501</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Britain-IRA,0518</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Navy Officer Killed By Bomb; British Military Adopts New License
Plates</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BELFAST, Northern Ireland (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   IRA guerrillas killed another
British military officer and London announced Tuesday it is
changing license plates for the cars of Britiah servicemen in West
Germany.
   Lt. Alan Shields, 45, a navy recruiting officer, was driving
into East Belfast Monday night when a bomb attached to his car blew
up, police reported.
   His death came three days after an IRA bomb killed eight
soldiers in a bus in Northern Ireland. Shields was the 26th British
serviceman killed this year in IRA attacks, compared with three in
1987.
   The Defense Department announced in London that the distinctive
military plates used on the 95,000 vehicles of British military
personnel and their families in West Germany would be replaced by
standard British license plates.
   Four British military personnel were killed in Western Europe
this summer by bombs and automatic rifle fire. The IRA claimed
responsibility for the attacks that involved cars carrying military
license plates.
   Armed Forces Minister Archie Hamilton said the license-late
change will make the cars of military personnel indistinguishable
from those of British tourists.
   Shields, whose wife and son live in Scotland, was believed to be
the first Royal Navy man killed by the IRA in Northern Ireland.
   Crispin Rodwell, a news photographer who was driving behind
Shields' car, said, ``It just exploded and was immediately engulfed
in flames. Several people ran forward with fire extinguishers ...
but couldn't get close enough to have any effect and the driver was
still inside.''
   The blast occurred near the Roman Catholic Short Strand area, a
stronghold of Irish Republican Army. The Guardian newspaper in
London said some Short Strand residents jeered as the car burned.
   The outlawed IRA claimed responsibility for the bombing in a
telephoned message to a local radio station, saying it had killed a
British soldier.
   But a press officer at police headquarters in Belfast said
Shields was a Royal Navy recruiting officer who worked at the
recruiting office in Belfast.
   The IRA circulated a statement Tuesday saying Shields ``was
engaged in recruiting personnel to carry on Britain's war in
Ireland.''
   It added: ``Our volunteers had been observing their target and a
number of others based at the same location for some time.
Yesterday when the opportunity presented itself a 3-pound charge of
high explosives was placed on the vehicle.''
   Prime Minister Margaret Thatcher's office in London said she was
``saddened and angered by yet another senseless killing.''
   Mrs. Thatcher ordered a security review following the IRA bomb
attack Saturday that killed eight soldiers and injured 27.
   The soldiers were in an unmarked military bus returning to their
barracks at Omagh, 50 miles west of Belfast, following leave on the
British mainland when a bomb in a car parked on the roadside
exploded as the bus passed.
   The mainly Roman Catholic IRA is fighting to unite Northern
Ireland, a British province where Protestants outnumber Catholics
3-2, with the predominantly Catholic Irish Republic.
</TEXT>
