<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Lebanon     08-23 0404</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Lebanon,0418</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Syrian-Backed Factions Vow to Block Elections</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By RIMA SALAMEH</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BEIRUT, Lebanon (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Syrian-backed leftist and Moslem factions
on Tuesday vowed to block presidential elections until Christians
agree to constitutional reforms that would give Lebanon's feuding
communities an equal share of power.
   ``Nationalist and progressive forces will undertake all poitical
and active measures to prevent elections until achieving national
entente,'' said a joint statement issued by 12 factions.
   The factions included the prominent Shiite Moslem Amal militia
of Justice Minister Nabih Berri and the Progressive Socialist Party
of Druse warlord Walid Jumblatt.
   The six-year term of President Amin Gemayel, a Maronite
Catholic, expires Sept. 23, and under the constitution, parliament
must elect a new president by mid-September.
   Planned elections in the 99-seat parliament were blocked last
Thursday when most Christian deputies boycotted the session to
protest the candidiacy of former President Suleiman Franjieh.
   Franjieh, 78, a staunch ally of Syria, was president when the
civil war broke out in April 1975. Before his term ended in 1976,
he requested Syrian military intervention to end the fighting.
   There are only 76 active members of parliament. The house was
elected in 1972 for a four-year term, but but its mandate was
renewed several times because civil strife prevented elections.
   The Lebanese Forces militia, the Christians' main military arm,
is pro-Israeli and violently opposed to Syria, which maintians
40,000 troops in east and north Lebanon and Moslem west Beirut.
   Israel maintians a self-proclaimed ``security zone'' six to 10
miles into southern Lebanon.
   Under an unwritten national covenant made after Lebanon's
independence from France in 1943, Christians have maintained the
top executive, legislative, judicial and military posts.
   The president is traditionally elected from the Maronite
Catholic community.
   In the absence of elections, the outgoing president could form a
caretaker Cabinet under a Maronite prime minister.
   But the statement on Tuesday vowed to fight with ``political and
material'' means any such attempt by Gemayel. It did not elaborate
or say outrightly if that meant the 12 groups plan to rekindle
civil war fighting.
   The statement also called for a nationwide ``warning strike'' on
Friday to protest the ``American-Israeli intervention that
prevented the parliament from practicing its role of electing a new
president.''
   The pro-Syrian militias urged their followers to ``be on maximum
alert to confront the critical situation and to continue the
struggle in order to liberate the country and regain its
sovereignty.''
</TEXT>
