<HEAD>Israeli Diplomat Returns From Moscow</HEAD>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An Israeli diplomat returned Tuesday from
Moscow amid speculation that his country and the Soviet Union will
open political talks, the Foreign Ministry said.
   Yaakov Kedmi traveled to the Soviet Union last month as a member
of a delegation whose purpose was to issue visas for Soviet Jews
and inspect the Israeli Embassy building.
   It was the first visit by Israeli diplomats to the Soviet Union
since ties were severed between the two countries 21 years ago over
the 1967 Middle East war. A Soviet delegation has been in Israel
for more than a year.
   Israel radio reported earlier this week that the Israeli team
and their Soviet counterparts in Israel would meet again for
political talks.
   Foreign Ministry officials denied that any political discussions
were planned either in Jerusalem or Moscow.
   The Soviet-born Kedmi, 43, was among the first Soviet Jewish
activists who came here in the late 1960s. Since then, about
200,000 Soviet Jews have come to Israel.
