<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Mandela     08-23 0397</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mandela,0406</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Mandela's Health Excellent, Doctor Says</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By HANNS NEUERBOURG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A lung specialist who visited Nelson Mandela last
weekend in a Cape Town hospital said Tuesday the black African
nationalist leader is in ``excellent'' health after a bout with
non-infectious tuberculosis.
   ``He is in excellent shape and he is in the best possible
hands,'' said Professor Heinrich Herzog. ``He told me, `I was sick
and now I am perfectly well'. He also said all symptoms (of the
disease) had gone.''
   Herzog, a former president of the European Society of
Pneumology, returned Monday night after a three-day stay. He said
he was invited by Mandela's attending physician, Attie de Kock of
Stellenbosch University.
   De Kock, who is treating Mandela in Cape Town's Tygerberg
Hospital, wanted to have a second, ``neutral'' specialist confirm
his diagnosis after unspecified quarters voiced doubt about it, he
said.
   Herzog said an examination of medical records and X-rays left
him ``absolutely without doubt'' that the diagnosis was correct and
that the 70-year-old Mandela had suffered from ``closed or
non-bacillar tuberculosis.'' He said antibiotic therapy worked
``very fast and with perfect results.''
   ``He is really in the best possible hands,'' Herzog said. He
said he knew De Kock as a colleague and a fellow member of the
American College of Chest Physicians and that they both repeatedly
met at international medical congresses.
   He laughed when told some people may suspect his trip was
arranged by the white government for propaganda purposes. ``They
should know that I am an outspoken opponent of apartheid. But I
went there (to see Mandela) because he is a patient. I did not go
there for political reasons,'' Herzog said.
   His observations contrasted with a report by Mandela's lawyer,
Ismail Ayob, who said last week that Mandela had lost much weight,
was short of breath, had a persistent cough and impaired speech.
   ``Mr. Mandela is normally slender,'' Herzog said. ``He did not
cough once when I visited him. Because of the rumors (about his
health) he was extremely grateful for my visit because it provided
him with the final evidence. He could say `Stop now (with the
rumors). You cannot doubt two authorities.'''
   Herzog said Mandela was still in Tygerberg Hospital when he left
South Africa. ``He could leave there soon,'' he said. ``The
question is where to.'' Mandela has been imprisoned since 1962.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
