<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Pakistan 1stLd-Writethru a0651 08-23 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Pakistan, 1st Ld - Writethru, a0651,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ms. Bhutto Says She Got Death Threats; Sectarian Strife Leaves 10
Dead</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 17th graf, ``Since the ...'' with 1 graf to ADD that Zia
was Sunni Muslim.</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By SYDNEY RUBIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>KARACHI, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Opposition leader Benazir Bhutto said
Tuesday that Pakistan's intelligence services received information
her life was in danger following the plane crash that killed
President Mohammad Zia ul-Haq.
   Ms. Bhutto said she was under police protection.
   Meanwhile, a newspaper reported sectarian strife in northwestern
Pakistan in the wake of Zia's death last week had left at least 10
people dead.
   Ms. Bhutto, leader of the country's largest opposition party,
the Pakistan People's Party, said she was informed Tuesday that the
government had posted armed guards outside her home.
   ``They informed me that they had received some threats so they
wanted to post some guards,'' she said in an interview with The
Associated Press at her home. ``They told my secretary, `We used to
follow her for intelligence purposes but now we'll follow her to
guard her.'''
   Ms. Bhutto said she had no other details.
   A civilian intelligence source in his southern port city,
speaking on condition of anonymity, said the police guards had been
watching her since Sunday, four days after Zia's C-130 plane
exploded and crashed in eastern Pakistan on Aug. 17.
   Government officials suspect the plane was sabotaged and a team
of U.S. and Pakistani officials are at the crash site investigating.
   Across the street from her walled home near Clifton Beach was
parked an unmarked blue truck, white jeep and motorcycle, all
bearing special government plates. They were manned by members of
an elite unit from the Sind provincial police called the ``Eagle
Squad,'' the intelligence source said.
   Ms. Bhutto in the interview said political leaders must
``conduct themselves in the finest democratic tradition'' and ``act
so as to give the military no pretext for intervention.''
   She said she was seeking to form alliances with other opposition
groups and reach agreements to prevent them competing for the same
national assembly seats.
   Ms. Bhutto strongly criticized the current cabinet, calling the
ministers ``dangerous'' holdovers from Zia's regime. Thirteen of
the 16 ministers were appointed by Zia.
   ``These are people who know they will lose their power, their
privilege, their patronage Nov. 16 and it is they who will do
whatever they can to prevent the holding of fair, free and
impartial elections,'' she said.
   She called on new President Ishaq Khan to dismiss the cabinet
and appoint a caretaker government until elections of ``people who
don't have a vested interest in the elections and will conduct
themselves in a neutral way,'' she said.
   She expressed confidence that if elections were conducted fairly
she would win. She said her government would seek to attract
outside investment, maintain close relations with the United States
and honor commitments to the Afghan Mujahedeen guerrillas.
   Pakistan under Zia was the United States' chief ally in the
region, chanelling U.S. arms and other support to the guerrillas
fighting Soviet and Afghan forces in neighboring Afghanistan.
   Since the assassination three weeks ago of a Shiite Moslem
religious leader in northwestern Pakistan, tension between Shiite
and Sunni Moslems has increased and authorities feared the
observance could lead to violent confrontations. Zia himself was a
Sunni Moslem.
   Troops were in high profile Tuesday, patrolling Karachi and
other Pakistani cities but there were no immediate reports of
violence.
   The English-language newspaper The Muslim reported Tuesday at
least 10 people died and 10 others were injured the last few days
in sectarian violence between minority Shiites and Sunni Moslems
near Kohat, about 100 miles west of Islamabad, the capital.
   At least six of the dead were Shiites from Lodhikhel who were
attacked by Sunni tribesmen, the newspaper reported.
   The violence is the worst reported in Pakistan since Zia's death.
</TEXT>
