<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Hungary-Romania     08-23 0405</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hungary-Romania,0421</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugees Begin Protest Against Destruction Of Villages</HEAD>
<DATELINE>BUDAPEST, Hungary (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Romanian refugees and Hungarian
activist groups have begun a two-week protest against the razing of
thousands of villages in Romania, it was reported Tuesday.
   The protesters are demanding that the Romanian government stop
its plan to demolish about 7,000 of Romania's 13,000 villages and
to resettle the population in big ``agro-industrial centers'' by
the year 2000.
   Hungarian radio said the peaceful protest began Monday night
outside the Romanian Embassy in Budapest and was led by the Free
Romania group, which is made up of ethnic Romanians who fled to
Hungary.
   Members of the group went on a 24-hour hunger strike on Tuesday,
the Romanian National Day, the report said.
   The demonstrators were planning to take turns standing in front
of the embassy in shifts of three to six hours, and their numbers
are expected to vary from a few dozen to several hundred people.
   Outlawed Hungarian activist groups also represented in the
protest included the Hungarian Democratic Forum, the Fidesz
independent youth group and the Forras Koer (Fountain Circle), the
radio reported.
   The resettlement scheme would affect hundreds of ethnic
Hungarian villages.
   Hungarian Politburo member Imre Pozsgay denounced the project as
a ``crime against mankind.''
   In an editorial, the government newspaper Magyar Hirlap said the
largest ethnic Hungarian group outside Hungary lives in Romania and
that ``it could play the role of bridge between the two countries'
citizens.''
   Critics in Hungary have said the Romanian government is pursuing
a policy of discrimination against the 1.7 million Hungarians in
Romania by destroying village culture as well as the tradition of
Romania's minorities.
   Romania has repeatedly rejected the charges, claiming the
project will raise living standards and win arable land for
agriculture.
   In a related development Tuesday, a Hungarian bishop in charge
of helping Romanian refugees called on the West to bring the
Romanian village-razing plan before the United Nations.
   Bishop Endre Gyula of Szeged, about 10 miles from the Romanian
border, called for economic sanctions against Romania, according to
the Austrian Catholic news agency Kathpress.
   According to Gyula, 12,000 Romanians have fled to Hungary since
Budapest took the unprecedented step last year of accepting
refugees.
   Gyula said refugees have reported that a number of villages
around Bucharest and in Transylvania already have been destroyed,
Kathpress said.
   The bishop described the situation for refugees on the border as
``dramatic,'' saying people were beaten.
</TEXT>
