<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Bentsen 1stLd-Writethru a0628 08-23 0671</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Bentsen, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0628,630</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bentsen Chides Reagan for Delay in Signing Trade Bill</HEAD>
<HEAD>Precede ST. LOUIS</HEAD>
<HEAD>Top 6 grafs new, picking up at pvs 5th graf, ``I fought''</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By STEVEN KOMAROW</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TAYLOR, Mich. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Democratic vice presidential nominee Lloyd
Bentsen told union audiences Tuesday that President Reagan fought
the trade bill until he signed it and tried to take credit for it.
   ``We had no help on that from the administration,'' Bentsen told
a cheering, flag-waving crowd of about 500 United Auto Workers
members overflowing a meeting hall in this Detroit suburb. ``He
could have signed that bill months ago, but he vetoed it over the
plant-closing provision.''
   The president vetoed the trade bill earlier this year largely
because of the provision calling for 60 days' notice to workers
before a plant can be closed. He has since let that provision
become law in separate legislation, and he signed the companion
trade bill Tuesday in California.
   The campaign schedule for Bentsen, chairman of the Senate
Finance Committee and a prime sponsor of the trade bill, was
tailored to help him dramatize his point that Reagan had done a
180-degree turn on the legislation because the issue was hurting
Republican presidential nominee George Bush.
   ``I want you to know who the point man was in fighting that
plant-closing provision,'' Bentsen told clothing workers earlier at
the Biltwell Co. in St. Louis.
   ``It was a senator _ Dan Quayle _ who fought against it. But he
lost and the administration lost and we were able to put it into
law,'' he said, referring to the Republican vice presidential
nominee.
   ``I fought for two or three years to put that trade bill in
effect,'' while the president ``put many a roadblock in front,''
Bentsen said.
   The president now ``has waited until the very last day to sign
it, and he's gone to the latest time zone,'' Bentsen said.
   ``He's been carried kicking and screaming to the altar but it
looks like we finally have a marriage and we're finally going to
get a real trade bill for America,'' Bentsen said, receiving hearty
applause from the 100 workers crowded in the plant snack bar to
listen.
   Bush, when Reagan tapped him earlier in the administration to
talk with the Japanese about unfair trade, was ``heaping effusive
praise'' instead of bargaining tough, Bentsen said.
   Bentsen said a Dukakis-Bentsen administration would fight to
open foreign markets. He promised that one of the first pieces of
business before the Senate next month would be a textile trade bill
aimed specifically at the clothing industry, which he said had been
particularly hard hit.
   When Bentsen toured the plant, the workers, mostly women, showed
him how to use various pieces of equipment. He worked a machine
pressing men's suit coats, and his wife B.A. joked that he didn't
do that at home.
   The company gave Bentsen a blue hopsack blazer, size 42 long,
and he was presented with a ``Buy American'' tee shirt and a union
hat.
   Earlier, talking to reporters on the campaign jet, Bentsen
remarked on Reagan's delay in signing the bill and said the
president ``really is a hard loser.''
   Bentsen denied that Reagan's signature on the measure would take
the issue away from the Democrats. ``Not so long as we remember
it's the Bentsen-Danforth bill,'' he said. Sen. John Danforth,
R-Mo., co-sponsored the legislation.
   Bentsen avoided criticizing Quayle over the Republican's entry
in to the National Guard during the Vietnam war. One of Bentsen's
sons also joined the Guard during that time frame.
   ``I think you'll see less intensity on the issue as time goes
on,'' he said. ``I'm not going to trash him on the issue.''
   Bentsen did chide Quayle for his late conversion, which came
Monday night before the Veterans of Foreign Wars convention in
Chicago, to supporting a bill making the Veterans Administration a
cabinet-level agency. ``That was only a month ago'' that Quayle was
one of few in the Senate to oppose the measure, Bentsen said.
</TEXT>
