<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1827EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u i AM-Burundi-Massacre     08-23 0641</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Burundi-Massacre,0660</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Refugees Say Army Took Part In Burundi Massacre</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DIDRIKKE SCHANCHE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NAIROBI, Kenya (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Refugees fleeing tribal violence in
Burundi claim that the army took part in the slaughter of thousands
of people in that small, central African nation, a U.N. official
said Tuesday.
   At least 5,000 people have been reported killed in massacres
during fightng between two rival tribes.
   Code Cisse, the U.N. High Commissioner for Refugees'
representative in Rwanda, said about 38,000 refugees have fled
Burundi into neighboring Rwanda since the killing broke out Aug.
14. He said about 5,000 peasants continue to cross the border each
day.
   Most of those fleeing are members of the Hutu tribe, said Cisse,
who spoke in a telephone interview after visiting border areas over
the weekend.
   Although the Hutu make up nearly 85 percent of Burundi's 5
million people, they are subservient to the Tutsi, who comprise the
remaining 15 percent and dominate the government and army.
   ``We saw many people who had been injured by bullets and
bayonets,'' Cisse said ``They said they were fleeing because they
didn't want to get shot by the military.''
   The Hutu People Liberation Party, an exiled opposition group,
also has charged that Burundi's military massacred thousands of the
majority Hutus.
   Burundi's government denied the accusations and said 5,000
people were killed in a slaughter instigated by exiled Hutus who
infiltrated Burundi to inflame anti-Tutsi sentiments.
   ``What the government did was restore peace,'' said a communique
issued Monday by Burundi's foreign minister, Cyprien Mbonimpa.
   The Hutu and the Tutsi are longtime enemies. After an abortive
1972 coup attempt in the former Belgium colony the Tutsi massacred
more than 100,000 Hutu, including most of the tribe's educated
class, according to human rights groups.
   Western diplomats in Burundi's capital, Bujumbura, say tribal
disturbances took place earlier this month in the northern region,
where last week's slaughter occurred, but that the government
believes it has restored order.
   ``The killing seems to have caught everybody by surprise,'' said
one Western diplomat, who spoke on condition of anonymity. He said
the suddenness of the violence ``could lend credence to the
government's claim there had been infiltrators trying to stir
things up.''
   Most killings occurred around the remote farming communes of
Ntega and Marangara in northern Burundi, a hilly, marshy area that
has since been sealed off by the military.
   ``News has been very, very difficult to come by,'' the diplomat
said. ``But from all that we have been able to gather, the army
moved in after the initial mass killing had occurred and was
instructed to fire only upon those carrying arms or threatening
other people.''
   Cisse said Rwanda urgently needed help to cope with the refugee
influx. Immediate requirements were blankets, medicines and tents,
he said, adding that many refugees were sleeping in the open.
   ``The conditions are very bad,'' he said. ``They are located in
a region where there is a high risk of malaria and are being housed
in schools and health clinics. We can't meet the need.''
   Rwanda and Burundi are among the world's most densely populated
countries.
   Nearly 5 million people are crammed into Burundi, which covers
an area about the size of Maryland. About 6 million people live in
slightly smaller Rwanda. There, the Hutu-Tutsi percentages are
roughly the same, although the Hutu dominate the government.
   Burundi promised in its communique Monday to work with those who
fled to Rwanda and to make possible a speedy return home.
   The massacre was the first outbreak of violence since Maj.
Pierre Buyoya seized power in a bloodless coup on Sept. 3, 1987
while former President Jean-Baptiste Bagaza was attending a
Francophone summit in Canada.
   The government has restricted travel between towns, enforced a 7
p.m. to 5 a.m. curfew throughout the country and banned meetings of
more than five people.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0160 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1957EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-AIDSTesting     08-23 0447</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-AIDS Testing,0458</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>CDC Organizes Nationwide Random AIDS Testing Of Newborns</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOSEPH B. FRAZIER</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ATLANTA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The federal Centers for Disease Control is
sponsoring a program to randomly test the blood of up to one-third
of the babies born in the United States next year for antibodies to
the AIDS virus.
   The tests will determine only whether the mother is infected. A
positive result does not necessarily mean the child has or will get
AIDS, said Dr. Timothy Dondero, head of the sero-epidemiology
branch of the CDC's AIDS program.
   Although the conclusions of several studies differ, they
indicate that from 30 percent to 50 percent of the newborns testing
positive could eventually get acquired immune deficiency syndrome,
he said in an interview Tuesday.
   Dondero said plans for the infant tests are in place so far in
about 23 states plus Puerto Rico and the District of Columbia, and
actual testing is under way in about half of those.
   He said he expects participation of about 30 states by the end
of the year and more in 1989. The study is part of a $40 million
package of programs to track the spread of the AIDS virus.
   The virus attacks the body's immune system, leaving victims
susceptible to infections and cancer. The disease has claimed the
lives of nearly 40,000 Americans.
   AIDS is most commonly transmitted by sexual contact or by
sharing contaminated drug needles. It is also spread, less often,
from an infected mother to her child before or at birth.
   It is likely that about 1.3 million infants will be tested next
year, using a method first tried by Massachusetts health officials,
Dondero said. No names will be attatched to the blood samples, he
said.
   ``There is no way of testing specimens linked to individuals
unless you have the consent of the individual,'' he said, adding
that getting consent would hobble the random aspect of the sample.
   ``Most groups involved in testing _ military recruits, sexually
transmitted disease clinics, blood donors _ are to some extent
self-selected,'' he said. ``People do not agree to take part who
have some reason for not wanting to take part.''
   The new program is intended to test a true representative sample
of the population, Dondero said. He said the aim is to determine
where AIDS infection among women is concentrated and to determine
where to target prevention programs.
   ``So far it is concentrated in big cities. It is important to
assess if it is prevalent in some rural areas as well,'' he said.
   ``Over time we will be able to monitor trends of infection in
the female half of the general population,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0161 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2007EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Chile     08-23 0481</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Chile,0494</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Pinochet Says Military Will Not Withdraw From Politics</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FEDERICO QUILODRAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>SANTIAGO, Chile (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Augusto Pinochet, celebrating
15 years as chief of Chile's army, declared Tuesday that the armed
forces will not withdraw from politics or abandon control of
internal security.
   In addition, the army's vice-commander, Gen. Santiago Sinclair,
said troops were ``in a state of readiness'' for an October
referendum in which the right-wing president is expected to seek
eight more years of rule.
   The 72-year-old Pinochet's impassioned defense of military
involvement in politics appeared intended to counter suggestions
that he should give up his army command in return for the
presidential nomination.
   Pinochet told army officers at a luncheon at the army academy in
east suburban Santiago that Chile faced a constant threat of
Marxist subversion.
   ``It is thus impossible to conceive that the military would be
called upon to intervene only when the cannon roars in an external
conflict,'' he said. ``Each day we are more certain that the
permanent enemies of Western humanity are active within a country's
own borders.''
   Pinochet complained that past governments ``kept the armed
forces apart from national development and public affairs,
relegating them to darkest passivity.''
   He said Chile's new institutional structure ``requires an armed
forces conscious of their political responsibilities.''
   The luncheon was private, but copies of Pinochet's address were
given to reporters by his press secretary.
   Pinochet was named commander of the army, by far the most
powerful military branch, on Aug. 23, 1973, by elected President
Salvador Allende, a self-declared Marxist. Nineteen days later,
Pinochet led the coup that toppled Allende's government. He has
been the country's authoritarian ruler ever since.
   Sinclair told Pinochet in a speech that the military branch was
in ``a state of readiness over future events on which the destiny
of the country depends.''
   Military leaders meet Aug. 30 to select a single presidential
candidate, expected to be Pinochet. Voters then will be asked to
vote yes or no on the candidate during a referendum.
   Sinclair pledged army support for the nominee, saying ``it is
essential that we move forward and continue the work'' of
Pinochet's administration.
   No exact date for the referendum has been announced, but
Pinochet has said it will be in early October. If he wins a
majority in the referendum, the candidate will begin an eight-year
presidential term in March. If he is rejected by most voters, open
elections are supposed to be held in 1990.
   Opposition supporters have begun an intensive campaign for a
``no'' vote.
   Other commanders participating in the selection of a nominee,
navy Adm. Jose Merino, air force Gen. Fernando Matthei and national
police Gen. Rodolfo Stange, have said the candidate should give up
any military position. However, Pinochet's central source of power
has been his leadership of the army, and he is seen as reluctant to
relinquish it.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
