<1ST_LINE>r p AM-GallupPoll     08-23 0355</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Gallup Poll,330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Gallup Poll: 48 Bush, 44 Dukakis</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A Gallup Poll released Tuesday found 48 percent
support for George Bush and 44 percent for Michael Dukakis in the
presidential race, with about half the respondents approving of
Sen. Dan Quayle as Bush's running mate.
   Fifty-two percent of the 1,001 registered voters surveyed in the
national poll said they approved of Bush's choice of Quayle, an
Indiana senator, while 27 percent said they disapproved and 21
percent were not sure.
   The survey was conducted from Friday through Sunday.
   An earlier Gallup poll found similar reaction to Dukakis' choice
of Sen. Lloyd Bentsen of Texas as the Democratic running mate: 57
percent approved, 22 percent disapproved and 21 percent were unsure.
   Quayle has been embroiled in a controversy over whether he used
family influence to join the National Guard during the Vietnam War
and avoid the military draft. When asked in the new Gallup poll
whom they would choose if they could vote separately for the vice
president, 41 percent picked Bentsen and 36 percent Quayle.
   The four-point spread between Bush and Dukakis was within the
poll's margin of sampling error of plus or minus three percentage
points, meaning it found the race to be statistically a dead heat,
radio station WEEI in Boston reported.
   A CBS News poll conducted over the same period last week found a
six-point spread, 46-40, between the candidates, with Bush
numerically ahead. Another Gallup Poll, done for Newsweek on
Thursday and Friday, found Bush ahead 51-42, while other polls done
just before or during the GOP convention last week found a dead
heat in the race.
   Dukakis had led by as many as 18 points in polls after the
Democratic convention in mid-July, a margin that pollsters
attributed to the rush of positive television publicity generated
by the convention.
   Dukakis' convention bounce was expected to fade, as it did, and
Bush was expected to gain his own boost after the Republican
convention, as the most recent polls indicate he has. The last
Gallup Poll before the GOP convention had the race at 49-42 for
Dukakis.
</TEXT>
