<1ST_LINE>r a AM-FirebombingConviction     08-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Firebombing Conviction,0596</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Two Guilty in Drug Firebombing</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A jury Tuesday convicted two men of arson for
firebombing the home of a man who had complained about drug dealers
in his neighborhood, where a policeman assigned to guard the man's
home was later shot to death.
   Claude Johnson, 28, and Robert Webster, 17, also were convicted
of criminal mischief and intimidating a witness in the trial-level
state Supreme Court.
   First-degree arson carries a maximum penalty of 25 years to life
in prison. Sentencing was scheduled for Sept. 20.
   The Molotov cocktail attacks occurred in the early morning hours
of Nov. 10, two weeks after the victim, Arjune, a Guyanese
immigrant who goes by one name, had moved to the Queens
neighborhood of South Jamaica. He had repeatedly called police
about alleged drug-dealing outside his home in those two weeks,
most recently the night before the attacks.
   ``I saw these guys collecting money from people _ cars and so
forth,'' testified Arjune, who is now in the federal witness
protection program with his wife, son and daughter.
   About 4:25 a.m. on Nov. 10, he said on the stand last week, he
heard his family's dogs barking, looked through a window and saw
the defendants approaching his home, each carrying a burning glass
jar.
   ``I shouted at ... everybody to wake up,'' he said. ``I ran to
the window, where this gentleman, Webster, was trying to open my
window. ... I looked at his face, he looked at me. He was
determined to burn my house.''
   Arjune said the second firebombing occurred about two hours
after the first. In the first attack, four bottles were thrown, all
of which bounced off the house and landed outside. In the second,
three bottles were thrown, one of which went through a window and
set fire to the carpet and draperies while scorching the wall, he
said.
   Webster was involved in both; Johnson was arrested after the
first, he testifid.
   Arjune said he was burned on the arms and chest while hurling
the incendiary device back outside the house.
   ``I had no choice. I couldn't ...,'' he said before breaking
down in tears. ``I couldn't leave the fire to burn my house.''
   The firebombings caused police to post a round-the-clock guard
at the house. Last February, one of the guards, Officer Edward
Byrne, was shot to death in what police called an execution ordered
by high-level drug traffickers to retaliate for their own
prosecutions and imprisonment.
   The Byrne killing was not mentioned in the trial, because it was
ruled legally irrelevant to the firebombings.
   In their summations, defense attorneys pointed out
inconsistencies in Arjune's account of the firebombing and
questioned his identification of the defendants.
   Arjune is scheduled to testify at two other trials of people
accused of having threatened him.
   One defendant is Webster's father, also named Robert, who is
charged with witness intimidation. The other is Thomas Godbolt,
charged with coercion and menacing. Both have pleaded innocent.
   Godbolt is said by authorities to be associated with Lorenzo
``Fat Cat'' Nichols, who is serving a 25-year-to-life prison term
for major drug trafficking in Queens.
   Police Commissioner Benjamin Ward and other officials have said
they believe Nichols _ whose alleged drug organization was the
target of 30 arrests on Aug. 11 _ may have ordered the murder of
Byrne. However, Nichols is not one of the four men charged with
Byrne's killing, and his lawyers have denied he was involved.
</TEXT>
