<1ST_LINE>r a AM-MspiKidnapping     08-23 0503</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Mspi Kidnapping,0516</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Multimillionaire Receives Handwritten Note from Abducted Wife</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KATHY EYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JACKSON, Miss. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A multimillionaire businessman has
received a note from his kidnapped wife, the first indication that
the woman missing nearly a month may be still alive, the FBI
announced Tuesday.
   Robert Hearin received the note from his wife, Annie Laurie
Hearin, last week, officials said. Mrs. Hearin, 72, suffers from an
intestinal disorder that could be fatal if she doesn't get
medication.
   Wayne Taylor, special agent in charge of the FBI's Mississippi
operations, also announced that Hearin had paid a total of $1
million to 12 people named in the original ransom note discovered
the day Mrs. Hearin disappeared. None of the 12, who had lost
lawsuits to a company owned by Hearin, have been charged in
connection with the case.
   Taylor said investigators have no leads in their search for Mrs.
Hearin.
   ``We're optimistic and will continue to be optimistic and hope
for her safe return and nothing more,'' he said.
   Taylor said the news conference was called Tuesday to assure
Mrs. Hearin's abductors that her husband ``has done everything
conceivably possible to meet their demands, considering the
vagueness of them.''
   FBI analysis of the handwriting has confirmed Mrs. Hearin wrote
the letter, which was dated Aug. 10, postmarked Aug. 12 and
received at the Hearins' Jackson home Aug. 15, Taylor said.
   Taylor wouldn't disclose the city from which the letter was
mailed, nor would he discuss its contents other than to say ``it
urged him (Hearin) to comply with the demands of the kidnappers.''
   Hearin, who did not attend the news conference, is president of
Mississippi Valley Gas Co., and has holdings estimated at $100
million in various companies.
   The only word received from the kidnappers was a note left at
the Hearins' home the day of the kidnapping, Taylor said. The vague
note demanded Hearin right alleged wrongs to 12 people, later
determined by investigators as defendants in lawsuits filed by
School Pictures of Mississippi Inc., one of Hearin's companies.
   The $1 million was roughly equal to what the 12 had been ordered
to pay in damages in those lawsuits. The personal checks to the 12
were mailed Aug. 16, Taylor said.
   Hearin did not attend the news conference, but a statement from
him was read. ``I have done everything possible to comply with the
vague demands given me,'' it said. ``My children and I pray for the
prompt release and safe return of my wife and their mother.''
   The couple have two grown children.
   Taylor declined to reveal whether investigators had contacted
the 12 since the checks were mailed to determine if the kidnappers
had contacted any of them. He also said he wouldn't reveal whether
any of the 12 volunteered to return the money, considering the
circumstances under which it was given.
   He said Hearin had conferred with the FBI and other law
enforcement agencies before deciding to pay the money. Taylor said
it was ``a group decision.''
</TEXT>
