<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Honduras-Contras     08-23 0309</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Honduras-Contras,0320</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Honduras To Restrict Contras To Border Region</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By FREDDY CUEVAS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>TEGUCIGALPA, Honduras (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Nicaraguan rebels who have entered
Honduras will be restricted to Honduran border areas to limit their
impact on the country, the foreign minister said Tuesday.
   Rebel leaders have said more than 9,000 rebel combatants, known
as Contras, are at base camps inside Honduras.
   Foreign Minister Carlos Lopez Contreras said many Contras
recently crossed into Honduras seeking refuge and humanitarian aid
distributed by the United States.
   Lopez Contreras said Honduras was allowing the U.S. aid to reach
the Contras as part of the peace plan signed last year by the
presidents of five Central American countries, including Daniel
Ortega of Nicaragua.
   He said the Contras cross the frontier frequently because under
the plan they were to be assigned to a zone in Nicaragua that
borders Honduras.
   Lopez Contreras said some Contras were ``entering Honduras as
refugees, then later returning to their country to fight.''
   The foreign minister said that anti-communist rebels from
Nicaragua and leftist guerrillas from El Salvador have caused
Honduras serious problems.
   Both groups have been using frontier territory for their war
bases and Honduras' social stability has been damaged, Lopez
Contreras said.
   He said to try to alleviate the problem Honduras will restrict
the Contras to border areas while they await supplies from the
United States.
   Honduras faces ``peculiar'' problems because of the superpowers,
Lopez Contreras said, with the United States supporting the Contras
and the Soviet bloc helping Nicaragua's Sandinista government and
the Salvadoran rebels.
   Honduran critics have denounced the government, saying it is
helping the United States support the Contras. They also have
criticized the frequent joint military exercises by U.S. and
Honduran forces.
   There have been several anti-American demonstrations this year
in Honduras, which is considered one of Washington's strongest
allies in the region.
</TEXT>
