<1ST_LINE>r i AM-US-SovietArms     08-23 0318</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-US-Soviet Arms,0325</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>U.S. Hopes for ``Successful'' ABM Treaty Review</HEAD>
<DATELINE>GENEVA (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The United States said it hoped for a
``constructive and successful session Wednesday to begin the third
U.S.-Soviet review of compliance with the 1972 ABM treaty limiting
missile defenses.
   The review is expekcted to last up to two weeks. The
anti-ballistic missile treaty requires such a meeting every five
years.
   A statement Tuesday from the U.S. diplomatic mission in Geneva
reiterated the U.S. position that a Soviet radar under construction
in Krasnoyarsk, Siberia, violates the treaty and that it should be
dismantled.
   Officials in Washington have said the main U.S. objective at the
review conference will be to have Moscow agree to dismantle the
station.
   Otherwise, the White House has threatened to declare the
facility a ``material breach'' of the treaty. This could clear the
way for the United States to overstep treaty limits in its
space-based missile defense program, formally known as the
Strategic Defense Initiative and commonly called ``Star Wars.''
   U.S. officials in Washington said after the Moscow summit in
June that, until the radar is dismantled, conclusion of a separate
treaty limiting long-range nuclear forces would be impossible. That
appeaered to be the first such linkage by the U.S. side.
   The Soviets have consistently linked a long-range, or strategic
arms, agreement to limits on Star Wars, which Washington has said
it will not accept. The two sides are negotiating in Geneva with
the stated common goal of reducing their strategic arsenals by 50
percent.
   Both sides appeared to take a conciliatory attitude as the
meeting approached. The U.S. statement said, ``The United States
delegation looks forward to a constructive and successful review.''
   Viktor Karpov, chief of the Soviet delegation, said in an
arrival statement Saturday: ``The upcoming discussions should not
be confrontational.''
   The U.S. team is led by the director of the Arms Control and
Disarmament Agency, Maj. Gen. William Burns.
</TEXT>
