<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Afghan-Soviets     08-23 0646</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Afghan-Soviets,0674</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Believe Soviets Suffered Worst Losses In Explosion At Ammo Dump</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAN BIERS</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>ISLAMABAD, Pakistan (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Afghan guerrillas and Western
diplomats believe Soviet forces suffered their worst losses in 8{
years of fighting in Afghanistan when an ammunition depot blew up
earlier this month.
   But in Mosow a Soviet spokesman said Tuesday there were no
casualties in the explosions at the depot at the military base at
Kalagay, 100 morth of the Afghan capital of Kabul.
   The dump reportedly blew up Aug. 10 or Aug. 11 when it was hit
by rebel-fired rockets.
   Western diplomatic sources in Islamabad on Tuesday repeated
their earlier report that the rebels claimed at least 109 Soviets
were killed and eight helicopters were destroyed.
   Last week, guerrilla organizations said 500 Soviet soldiers
perished in the attack.
   London's Daily Telegraph, in its Tuesday editions, said up to
710 Soviet soldiers and civilians were killed. It said a report
received in Peshawar, Pakistan, from a guerrilla commander in the
Kalagay district claimed that 598 Soviet soldiers and 112 Soviet
civilians were killed and 284 Soviets were wounded.
   The Kalagay depot stored Soviet ammunition and weapons for
garrisons throughout the country.
   Soviet Foreign Ministry spokesman Gennady Gerasimov, addressing
a regular news briefing in Moscow, confirmed there had been an
explosion at the Kalagay base but he added:
   ``The explosion took place at the place where they give arms to
people from other detachments and there were no casualties.'' He
did not say when the blasts occured, what might have caused them or
give further details.
   It is believed that the greatest loss suffered previously by the
Soviets in a single action occurred two years ago when fighting
near a mountain tunnel triggered an avalance and more than 70
Soviet troopers were killed.
   Western reporters normally are barred from Afghanistan by the
Marxist government and there was no independent confirmation of the
conflicting accounts of casualties at Kalagay.
   Soviet troops entered Afghanistan in December 1979 to help
battle the guerrillas but they are now being withdrawn under an
agreement signed in April by Afghanistan and Pakistan.
   Western diplomatic and rebels sources said Tuesday the
guerrillas are trying to capture their first major city and are
attacking government forces aound three provincial capitals.
   They gave these reports:
   Rebels battled their way into Kunduz on Aug. 9, two days after
Soviet forces withdrew, but last week government troops regained
control and fighting continued.
   The Western sources said rebels shot down a Soviet plane flying
soldiers into Kunduz and up to 45 people aboard the craft perished.
   Kabul's official media said as many as 265 guerrillas have been
killed in the Kunduz fighting. It did not mention government
casualties.
   Guerrillas claimed they seized the provincial capital of Taloqan
on Aug. 12, but the claim was not verified and one Western source
said there was fighting around the city.
   On Monday, a rebel group said guerrillas had captured the
Arghandab district near Kandahar city.
   The Soviet Union had an estimated 115,000 military personnel in
Afghanistan and recently announced half of the force had been
removed as of Aug. 15.
   Under the April agreement, all of the Soviet troops are to be
out of Afghanistan by Feb. 15 and the Soviets have said they will
comply with the schedule.
   But there were reports that the withdrawal has slowed.
   ``We suspect this is a planned pause and that no further major
movements will occur until the onset of winter,'' one Western
diplomatic source said.
   He said the Soviets probably would ``make propaganda capital out
of the delay,''
   The Kremlin has accused Pakistan of violating the April
agreement by continuing to provide arms and bases for the
guerrillas and declared it would take unspecified measure if the
actions continued.
   The guerrillas did not participate in the peace negotiations and
have vowed to continue their fight.
</TEXT>
