<1ST_LINE>u p AM-Quayle-Parkinson 1stLd-Writethru a0693 08-23 0572</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Quayle-Parkinson, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0693,540</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Parkinson: Quayle `Flirted,' `Wanted to Make Love'</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: SUBS 3 grafs for grafs 14-16 pvs, bgng: ``The two ...'' to
UPDATE with Lewis comments today; Picks up 17th graf pvs, bgng:
``Washington attorney ...''</NOTE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Washington lobbyist Paula Parkinson says
GOP vice presidential candidate Dan Quayle ``flirted'' with her
during a 1980 golfing vacation in Florida and ``he wanted to make
love,'' Playboy magazine said Tuesday.
   Chicago-based Playboy is featuring a 1980 nude photograph of Ms.
Parkinson as part of a ``Women in Washington'' pictorial in its
November issue, scheduled to reach newsstands on Sept. 27.
   The magazine also interviewed Ms. Parkinson about her 1980 trip
to Florida with Quayle, an Indiana senator who was a congressman at
that time, and two other legislators, including then-Rep. Tom
Evans, R-Del., whom she was dating.
   Playboy released a statement Tuesday that included the text of
Ms. Parkinson's remarks in the upcoming issue.
   ``There has been much speculation about an item that will appear
in the November Playboy about Republican vice presidential
candidate Dan Quayle and former lobbyist Paula Parkinson,'' said
the magazine's statement, read by spokeswoman Elizabeth Norris.
   ``For clarification and to prevent exaggerated or excessive
further speculation, here is the exact quote from the November
Playboy:
   ``When DC lobbyist Paula Parkinson, star of a November 1980
Playboy pictorial, was asked about rumors of hanky-panky with
George Bush's VP choice Dan Quayle, she said she and Quayle hadn't
actually slept together during a 1980 vacation in Florida.
   ```He wanted to, but I was there as Tom Evans' date,' Ms.
Parkinson said. `We flirted a lot and danced extremely close and
suggestively. He said he wanted to make love.'''
   Ms. Parkinson's remarks to Playboy were similar to comments
released earlier Tuesday by two of her former attorneys, who
contended Quayle propositioned the lobbyist during the 1980
vacation.
   The Daily News of Los Angeles quoted the lawyers as saying that
Ms. Parkinson had told the FBI that Quayle propositioned her when
she shared a cottage with the three legislators.
   Quayle, who has been married since 1972, denounced the report.
   ``That is just an absolute, flat-out falsehood,'' he told
reporters. ``I had nothing to do with her down there. I had nothing
to do with her before, and I had nothing to do with her afterwards.
   ``I think y'all are going to have to be a little bit careful
about this, because it's totally untrue. I've got a wife and three
small children, and I hope there's some respect and dignity for
things I did not do before we go rushing off with all these
so-called rumors,'' he said.
   Washington attorney Glenn Lewis, who was one of the lawyers who
represented Ms. Parkinson when she was questioned by the FBI in
1981, said later the Playboy account was consistent with what Ms.
Parkinson told the FBI.
   She was interviewed by the agency as part of an investigation
into whether sexual favors were traded for votes on Capitol Hill.
   ``Quayle made a pass at her, said he would like to sleep with
her. She said, `No, I'm with Tom.''' Lewis said, referring to notes
from the FBI interview.
   Washington attorney Roy Kinsey, who also was present during the
interview, said his paraphrased notes show that she told the FBI,
``Quayle made a pass, and said he would like to sleep with'' her.
   Evans lost his re-election bid in 1982.
</TEXT>
