<1ST_LINE>r a AM-Monroe-Clemency     08-23 0378</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Monroe-Clemency,0389</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Louisiana Court Stops Execution; Roemer Defers Commutation
Decision</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By ALAN SAYRE</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>BATON ROUGE, La. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The scheduled execution of a convicted
killer who has maintained his innocence for more than a decade was
stayed Tuesday by the Louisiana Supreme Court pending a review of
the sentence.
   After the ruling, Gov. Buddy Roemer said he would wait for the
court's review before deciding whether to commute the death
sentence of Ronald Monroe to life imprisonment without parole, as
the state's Pardon Board has recommended.
   It was not known immediately how long the court's review would
take.
   Monroe, 33, had been scheduled to die early Thursday for the
Sept. 9, 1977, stabbing death of Lenora Collins of New Orleans. The
victim's daughter, then 11, also was stabbed and testified that
Monroe was the assailant.
   ``I agree with the Louisiana Supreme Court's decision to stay
the execution of Ronald Monroe,'' Roemer said in a statement. ``In
capital punishment cases, it is the responsibility of all those
involved in the review process to be certain about administering
justice.''
   Earlier Tuesday, the governor said he was leaning against
commutation but probably would stay the execution for up to 100
days to allow courts to review the case again.
   The Pardon Board issued its recommendation Monday after a
hearing lasting more than five hours. Board chairman Yvonne
Campbell said the panel found that Monroe had been deprived of due
process of law. She would not elaborate or disclose how board
members voted.
   During the hearing, Monroe pleaded for clemency, maintaining
that he had not committed the slaying.
   ``I am innocent and will be innocent until the day I die,'' he
said.
   Prosecutors contend that Collins, 33, was killed after she told
Monroe he was being evicted from an apartment in her family's
duplex.
   Defense attorney Douglas Morris of New York said a reputed
confession to Collins' slaying by another man raised enough
questions to justify commutation.
   Courts have rejected the claim that George Stinson, convicted in
the 1980 stabbing death of his common-law wife in Pontiac, Mich.,
told a cellmate he killed Collins. According to court testimony,
the cellmate told police that Stinson merely said Collins had been
killed in the same way as the Michigan woman.
</TEXT>
