<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Angola-Rebels     08-23 0283</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Angola-Rebels,0292</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Rebels Claim 59 Angolan Troops Killed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LISBON, Portugal (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Angolan rebels claimed Tuesday that they
killed 59 Angolan troops last week, releasing their statement in
Lisbon on the eve of the sixth round of peace talks involving South
Africa, Cuba and Angola.
   The National Union for the Total Independence of Angola said the
troops were killed from Aug. 17-20 in separate actions in five
Angolan provinces, against the loss of six rebel fighters.
   No independent confirmation of the report emerged.
   The rebels, who are backed by the United States and South
Africa, are not a party to the U.S.-brokered talks. The discussions
so far have produced a cease-fire, signed Monday, which formally
ended hostilites in southern Angola.
   The rebel organization has been fighting Angola's Marxist
government since Portugal granted independence to its former
southern African colony in 1975.
   Cuba keeps an estimated 50,000 troops in Angola. The talks due
to begin Wednesday in Brazzaville, Congo, are expected to include
discussion of a timetable for their withdrawal.
   Other topics said to be on the agenda are:
   _Formation of a joint military commission to monitor the
cease-fire in southern Angola and withdrawal of 2,000-plus South
African troops from Angola.
   _Issues involving implementation of U.N. Resolution 435
regarding independence for South African-controlled South-West
Africa, known as Namibia.
   Chester Crocker, a U.S. assistant secretary of state and the
main architect of the southern African accord, has said a lasting
peace cannot be achieved without an internal political agreement in
Angola.
   But on Friday, President Jose Eduardo dos Santos of Angola
reiterated his government's refusal to negotiate with the rebel
group, which he said had wrecked efforts to establish a just
society in Angola.
</TEXT>
