<2ND_LINE>AM-Israel, 2nd Ld - Writethru,a0714,0880</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Palestinian Underground Presses PLO for Political Program</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: LEADS with six grafs to UPDATE with three Arabs wounded;
picks up 4th graf pvs: Factions in...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By NICOLAS B. TATRO</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>JERUSALEM (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Palestinian underground leaders who oversee the
uprising in the occupied lands expressed frustration over the sharp
divisions in the PLO and urged Tuesday that the organization adopt
a clear political strategy.
   Also Tuesday, Israeli troops shot and wounded three Palestinians
during a clash in the Jabaliya refugee camp in the the Gaza Strip,
Arab reporters said, quoting officials at the Ahli Arab hospital in
Gaza City.
   An Israeli army spokesman said he had no reports of violence in
the Gaza Strip. The camp has been under a curfew since Monday.
   The call from Palestinian underground leaders to the PLO on
Tuesday came in a leaflet, the 24th issued since the rebellion
began Dec. 8 among the 1.5 million Palestinians in the
Israeli-occupied West Bank and Gaza Strip.
   At least 252 Palestinian have been killed since the uprising
began and four Israelis have been slain.
   Factions in the Palestine Liberation Organization have been
feuding over proposals to create a government-in-exile and declare
an independent Palestinian state in the West Bank and Gaza, which
Israel captured from Jordan and Egypt in the 1967 Middle East war.
   Most of the frustration occurs among mainstream elements who
support efforts to start peace negotiations with Israel. Those on
the other side feel such a move would aggravate divisions among
Palestinians.
   Daoud Kutta, a leading Palestinian journalist, said the main
division is over ``how to deal with the question of recognizing
Israel's right to exist.''
   ``People are saying the ambiguuity has to be cleared up,'' he
said.
   Supporters of PLO chief Yasser Arafat have called for a clear
statement recognizing the Jewish state as a means of spurring
negotiations. Opposing that view are the radicals, including the
Popular Front for the Liberation of Palestine led by George Habash,
who oppose any concessions before peace talks.
   Tuesday's appeal was directed to the Palestinian National
Council, the 447-member body the PLO calls its parliament in exile.
It is expected to meet next month.
   It said the underground is ``certain the council will adopt a
comprehensive and clear political program which will gain
widespread international support for the national rights of our
people.''
   Although the leaflet stressed that the clandestine leaders were
not trying to take over, they clearly were prodding the PLO for a
decision.
   Salah Khalaf, deputy commander of Arafat's Fatah guerrillas,
said Monday on Austrian radio he expects a Palestinian government
and state to be formed by year's end.
   ``We are realists. Israel is there. It exists as far as the
political reality is concerned,'' he said.
   Khalaf, also known as Abu Iyad, has called for a provisional
government with a new charter to replace the PLO covenant calling
for the destruction of Israel and establishment of a democratic
secular state.
   The Khalaf proposal is opposed by pro-Syrian Palestinian
factions on the left and Moslem fundamentalist groups on the right.
   Hamas, a fundamentalist umbrella group whose name is Arabic for
zeal, says an international peace conference is an American plot to
create circumstances ``so some Palestinians can sign over Palestine
to the Jews.''
   Saleh Hussein, a Moslem preacher in Bethlehem, said in an
interview the fundamentalists want to create a pan-Islamic state.
   ``The PLO wants to live with Jews as partners either with two
different states or in one state, and we completely reject this
idea and refuse to be partners with the Jews in any plan,'' he
declared.
   A document circulated in the West Bank this month by the
pro-Syrian followers of Abu Musa attacked moderate calls for a
Palestinian-Israeli dialogue and rejected a Palestinian state
limited to the West Bank and Gaza.
   Such a state ``means part of Palestine is not a home for its
citizens but a home of the Canadian, American and Russian Jews and
whoever is thinking of immigrating,'' the statement said.
   Jerome M. Segal, a University of Maryland professor whose
writings influenced Palestinians who drafted a proposed declaration
of independence, said a ``turning point'' had been reached in
Palestinian-Israeli relations.
   Segal, speaking to a Hebrew University audience, said
Palestinians should act on their own to declare a state and seek
international recognition.
   About five minutes into his speech, 12 supporters of the
right-wing Tehiya Party stood up and began chanting ``PLO, no!''
The hecklers sat down after a few minutes and left the hall shortly
afterward.
   In another development, Michel Sabah, the first Arab appointed
Roman Catholic patriarch of Jerusalem, rejected an invitation to
meet with Yitzhak Rabin, the defense minister. Rabin has held
private meetings with several other Palestinian notables.
   A church official said Sabah's refusal was in line with Vatican
policy of not meeting with Israeli authorities in Jerusalem.
   The Vatican does not recognize Israeli control over Jerusalem,
which was given international status by the United Nations under a
1947 partition plan. Israel captured the Arab section of Jerusalem
in the 1967 war, annexed it and declared the entire city the
Israeli capital.
</TEXT>
