<1ST_LINE>r a AM-VanFires     08-23 0291</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Van Fires,0299</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Transit Authority Pulls Vans off Streets after Fires</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Metropolitan Transit Authority has grounded
its fleet of 86 wheelchair-lift-equipped vans until officials can
determine what caused fires in two of them on the same day.
   The manufacturers, Ford Motor Co. and Collins Bus Corp. of
Hutchinson, Kan., planned to help in the investigation, officials
said.
   One van was engulfed in flames Sunday while the driver was
waiting for a passenger. No passengers were on board and the driver
was not injured. A second, less-serious fire was reported earlier
Sunday.
   Each van uses a Ford Econoline E-350 chassis fitted with a
wheelchair lift and other equipment by Collins. Metro put the $2.3
million fleet of vans into service in April.
   Until the problem can be studied further, Metro officials said,
they will rely on taxicab companies to transport MetroLift elderly
and handicapped patrons. Patrons will be asked to use the service
only for work and medical trips.
   On Aug. 4, Ford announced a voluntary recall of about 15,000
ambulances based on 1983-87 Econoline E-250 and E-350 chassis and
vans to replace engine compartment heater hoses. The automaker said
failure of the heater hose could result in a fire under the hood.
   Last September, Ford recalled 200,000 heavy-duty Econoline E-250
and E-350 vehicles to install underbody heat shields, special fuel
filler caps and, in some cases, high-flow fuel vapor venting
systems. Ford announced that recall to minimize any fuel expulsion
and to protect underbody components from high exhaust temperatures.
   Transit system spokeswoman Carol Boudreaux said officials were
unsure whether the problems cited in the recall orders would apply
to the system's new fleet. That was one of the things that the
investigation would cover, she said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
