<DOCNO> AP880823-0182 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2124EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r a AM-RuralTransportation     08-23 0598</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Rural Transportation,0616</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Lack of Transportation Plagues Rural America, Lawmakers Testify</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By J.L. SCHMIDT</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>OMAHA, Neb. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   ``You can't get there from here'' used to be
the punch line of jokes about rural America, but it's become a fact
of life for too many people, a congresswoman told a conference on
rural transportation Tuesday.
   The farm crisis, deregulation of the transportation industry and
too high a priority on urban transit has caused a major upheaval in
rural areas, Rep. Virginia Smith, R-Neb., said.
   ``The revitalization of rural America cannot and will not occur
unless we guarantee mobility,'' she said.
   Intercity bus service has declined over the past 20 years, she
noted.
   ``Since 1982, more than 3,000 towns have lost their bus service,
and 92 percent of those towns have populations less than 10,000
people,'' Mrs. Smith told the two-day conference sponsored by the
U.S. Department of Agriculture.
   She urged people in rural America to fight for their share of
transportation dollars.
   ``We make up 39 percent of the nation's population, but we get
less than 3 percent of the funds,'' she said. ``It's time we got
our fair share.''
   ``The nation's rural people need education and transportation,
but their population is decreasing, their affluence is dwindling
and they can least afford the services they need the most,'' said
New York State Sen. Charles Cook of Delaware County, in central New
York about 65 miles southwest of Albany.
   ``More than half of the nation's farm families rely on non-farm
income, as well. They are reliant on transportation. They don't
just go to town once a week to get staples anymore,'' he said.
   Mrs. Smith recounted results of a study made of the Black Hills
Stage Line, which makes a 564-mile daily trip from Omaha to Rapid
City, S.D., west across Nebraska on U.S. Highway 20.
   When the owners threatened to discontinue the line, Mrs. Smith
went to then-Transportation Secretary Elizabeth Dole to plead the
case. She came up with $225,000 for a demonstration project to keep
the bus route alive for one year.
   She got more money in Washington and the Nebraska Legislature
came up with $50,000 during the recent session to match it for
another year.
   Results of the demonstration study revealed that half of the
people riding the bus had no other means of transportation.
Two-thirds said they couldn't have made the trip without the bus,
Mrs. Smith said.
   Half said they had a yearly income of less than $10,000 and
``one in every five said they were using the bus to go to work,
school or a job pool,'' she said.
   ``The towns are small, the distances are great, but the people
need the bus,'' she said.
   Mrs. Smith said she had been told that ``doctors rely on the bus
for medicine, hospitals for blood supplies, farmers for machinery
parts and the florist for flowers.''
   ``It's the only option for overnight deliveries. Many of the
state's elderly use it to get to the doctor and to visit friends
and family.''
   A ray of hope was offered by Michael Redisch, chief of research
and analysis for the Interstate Commerce Commission's Office of
Transportation Analysis.
   ``There's a lot of capital out there, a lot of old buses and old
terminals that need to be disposed of,'' he said. ``Secondly,
there's a whole new breed of managers coming to the deregulated
companies, and they're trying to break with past habits and
practices.''
   That transition spells promise for the future, he said, adding,
``New ideas and innovations will help change the face of rural
America.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
