<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Safrica-DraftRally     08-23 0270</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Safrica-Draft Rally,0278</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>South Africans Protest Ban of Anti-Draft Group</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CAPE TOWN, South Africa (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   About 2,000 students marched
around the University of Cape Town campus Tuesday to protest the
government's banning of a group opposed to the military draft.
   About 20 young men who addressed the demonstrators said they
would refuse to serve in the military, echoing the stand announced
by 143 other men this month.
   Military service is mandatory for white men and voluntary for
other races.
   Numerous anti-apartheid groups and individual activists have
condemned the ban imposed by police Monday on the End Conscription
Campaign, an organization founded five years ago which advocated
alternative, non-military service for young men with moral or
political objections to joining the armed forces.
   The Rev. Allan Hendrickse, leader of the mixed-race chamber of
Parliament, was among those denouncing the ban. The black majority
is excluded from Parliament, which also has chambers for whites and
Asians.
   Hendrickse said there should be no conscription until all South
Africans have equal political rights.
   Defense Minister Magnus Malan called Hendrickse's remarks a
``slap in the face'' to soldiers and accused him of playing into
the hands of terrorists.
   The Congress of South African Trade Unions, the country's
largest black labor federation, said the ban was a sign of weakness
by the government.
   ``A government is in a serious crisis when it feels gravely
threatened by a smallish campaign questioning an aspect of its
policy,'' the federation said.
   ``Despite the powerful propaganda instruments at its disposal,
it is not able to stem the growing disquiet among whites about the
role of the defense force.''
</TEXT>
