<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2214EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Aquino     08-23 0463</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Aquino,0474</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>President Says She Is Confident She Will Stay In Power</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MANILA, Philippines (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Corazon Aquino said Tuesday
she was confident her government will stay in power and said she
will personally guarantee the safety of Ferdinand Marcos if the
courts let him come home.
   At a news conference with Filipino reporters, the 55-year-old
president brushed aside charges of incompetence leveled by Vice
President Salvador Laurel and said she had ``more important tasks
to attend to'' than respond to his charges publicly.
   Mrs. Aquino was asked to comment on a statement made Monday by
her chief aide, Executive Secretary Catalino Macaraig, that the
government could not afford to have Marcos return from Hawaii
because foes of the ousted president might try to kill him and
blame the slaying on the administration.
   ``In the event that Mr. Marcos is allowed by our courts to
return ... we will expect adequate security,'' she said. ``It (an
assassination attempt) will not happen because if it is necessary
(for) the chief of staff himself to go there and escort him, then I
will do that,'' Mrs. Aquino said.
   Mrs. Aquino's husband, Sen. Benigno Aquino Jr., was killed in
1983 while under military escort at Manila airport moments after
returning from three years in the United States.
   The shooting helped inflame popular unrest which toppled Marcos
and propelled Mrs. Aquino to the presidency in February 1986.
   Mrs. Aquino refused to allow Marcos to return from Hawaiian
exile.
   Last week, however, an anti-corruption court said Marcos had the
right to cross-examine a former Cabinet minister, who is due to
give a deposition next November, if the statement was to be used as
evidence in any future criminal trial.
   Marcos, who is a lawyer, said he would demand the right to
conduct his own defense at the deposition hearing. Mrs. Aquino has
said she would abide by the decision of the court if it rules that
Marcos can return.
   Mrs. Aquino said Tuesday she was confident no new coup attempt
would be made during her three-day visit to Brunei, which begins
Monday.
   Rumors of a new attempt surfaced after Laurel this month called
on Mrs. Aquino to resign and order new presidential elections.
   She said Tuesday, ``I think ... there are enough people ... in
the nation, who support us and who are concerned about the
preservation of democracy in our country. So, I feel confident,
rumors notwithstanding, this government will continue.''
   Mrs. Aquino said of Laurel's charges: ``I would just like to
remind the vice president I know what my duties are as president of
the Philippines. I think ... that he knows what his duties are as
vice president. I don't want to engage in name-calling. I have more
important tasks to attend do.''
</TEXT>
