<1ST_LINE>r a AM-HueyNewton 1stLd-Writethru a0691 08-23 0580</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Huey Newton, 1st Ld-Writethru, a0691,0590</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Ex-Black Panther Refuses Prison Release
^Eds: SUBS 6th-7th grafs, `Prison officers ...,' with 7 grafs to
explain more about consequences of Newton's action, background
about Streleski's refusal to leave prison.</HEAD>
<DATELINE>SAN QUENTIN, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Former Black Panther leader Huey
Newton refused to leave prison on his scheduled release date
Tuesday, demanding that officials also free fellow inmate and
ex-Panther Elmer ``Geronimo'' Pratt.
   Newton has been in prison for 60 days for parole violations.
Pratt, a convicted murderer, has been serving a life term since his
conviction in 1972. Two weeks ago he lost his eighth bid for parole
after a state panel called him a ``danger to the public.''
   Sue Gegner, an acquaintance of Newton's, said that Newton did
not expect Pratt to be freed. ``It's more of a statement that he's
trying to make,'' she said.
   ``Geronimo Pratt has been unjustly imprisoned for over 18 years
and he (Newton) feels very strongly about this,'' Gegner said.
   San Quentin spokeswoman Jeanne Ballatore said that when officers
went to Newton's cell Tuesday morning to begin release proceedings,
he refused to leave.
   Prison officers filed a disciplinary action against Newton for
refusing to obey a direct order. A state parole board panel met at
the prison later in the day and recommended that Newton's sentence
be lengthened by 30 days for violating the order, but Newton
instead requested a formal hearing by the full state parole board,
Ballatore said.
   He will remain in custody at least until the full hearing, set
for Aug. 30, and the board's decision about what action is in
order, she said.
   If Newton continues to refuse to leave, he can receive
additional discliplinary citations that require him to remain
behind bars up to the time his parole expires on Feb. 8, 1989.
   ``If at that point in time if he continues to refuse ... a
decision would have to be made. He'd be trespassing at that
point,'' she said.
   Authorities recall just one other inmate who declined to be
released from prison at the scheduled time, said Corrections
Department spokeswoman Christine May.
   Theodore Streleski killed popular Stanford University math
professor Karel DeLeeuw in 1978, smashing his head with a two-pound
hammer. He later called the killing a protest over treatment of
graduate students at the school.
   He refused to express remorse for the crime and turned down
parole three times from March 1984 to September 1985 because the
terms of his parole said he couldn't live in the San Francisco Bay
area. When he was finally released, his term for parole had expired
and he had no restrictions on where he could live.
   Newton served nine months of a 16-month state prison term for
possessing firearms as an ex-felon. He was released on parole Dec.
8.
   He was returned to custody in June for parole violations that
included failure to submit to drug testing and failure to advise
his parole officer that he had been arrested for investigation of
driving under the influence of alcohol or drugs.
   Supporters of Pratt, a former Panther deputy defense minister,
contend he's a political prisoner and the victim of police efforts
to jail Panther leaders and dismantle the Oakland-based radical
movement of the late 1960s and early '70s.
   Pratt was found guilty of slaying a Santa Monica woman during a
$30 robbery in 1968. Her husband also was shot, but survived. Pratt
maintained he was at party headquarters in Oakland at the time.
</TEXT>
