<DOCNO> AP880823-0191 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2337EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r i AM-Peru-Violence     08-23 0263</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Peru-Violence,0271</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Guerrillas Attack Jungle Bridge</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TINGO MARIA, Peru (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Police said Tuesday that guerillas
using explosives heavily damaged a jungle bridge on a main highway
near Tingo Maria.
   They said the Monday night attack, 220 miles northeast of Lima,
came during a three-day ``armed strike'' against a U.S. proposal to
kill coca plants with a herbicide.
   Cesar Acosta, chief of anti-drug police in the region, said
guerrillas of the Maoist Shining Path movement called the attacks
and used fallen trees, rocks and boulders to block roads leading to
Tingo Maria.
   The rebels are urging peasants to protest a U.S. proposal to
spray coca, the raw material of cocaine, with the herbicide Spike.
The government says rebels protect drug traffickers in exchange for
funds to buy arms.
   The Huallaga Valley north of Tingo Maria is known as the cocaine
cradle because about 60 percent of the world's coca is harvested
illegally there.
   Coca leaves are refined into semi-processed cocaine and then
smuggled into Colombia, where it is refined into cocaine for sale
abroad.
   Environmentalists have criticized the hebicide plan, saying that
Spike will denude all plants and ruin the zone for food crops for
years to come.
   Peru demanded more testing before Spike is used and the U.S.
government agreed.
   Acosta said police recovered pamphlets signed by the Shining
Path protesting the Spike plan and the presence of agents of the
U.S. Drug Enforcement Administration in the area.
   About a dozen U.S. agents have been in the area for more than a
year advising Peruvian anti-drug units, the government has said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
