<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1312EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>a a AM-ReligionToday ADV26   08-23 0830</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Religion Today, ADV 26,0858</2ND_LINE>
<NOTE>$Adv26</NOTE>
<NOTE>For Release Fri AMs, Aug. 26, and Thereafter</NOTE>
<HEAD>Big Shuffle Of Bishops Set By United Methodists</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By GEORGE W. CORNELL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Religion Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   As in some nationwide game of musical chairs,
United Methodists have ordered their big reshuffling of bishops. By
Sept. 1, they're to be in their new places.
   It's a quadrennial change-about of area leadership in which some
bishops, new and old, are deployed to different posts. This time,
21 bishops were involved, 40 percent of the church's total of 50
active U.S. bishops.
   In the process, five regional conferences July 12-16 elected a
total of 15 new bishops. They were consecrated and assigned to
areas other than where they came from. Six incumbent bishops were
transferred to new areas.
   The moving-about of clergy, bishops and pastors, reflects the
denomination's ``itinerant ministry,'' which stems historically
from early American ``circuit riding'' ministers, always on the go.
   ``The purpose is to infuse new blood and fresh ideas, so people
don't get into a rut,'' says Thomas McAnally of Nashville, Tenn.,
director of the denomination's news service.
   ``However, pastors used to be moved much more often that they
are now,'' he added, noting that some church-growth studies
indicate that longer pastorates are more effective.
   Pastors now generally serve congregations several years, some
indefinitely, but are subject to annual appointment by their
bishops. Bishops, in office for life, are limited to serving two
four-year terms in each place, except in special circumstances.
   The current re-posting of bishops and choosing of new ones in
the 9.6-million-member denomination occurred at five jurisdictional
conferences, involving a total of about 2,000 delegates, half
clergy and half laity.
   Two women were elected as bishops, each in their early 40's,
among the youngest bishops ever named in U.S. Methodism's history.
Under church law, they won't have to retire until 2012.
   They are:
   Bishop Sharon Brown Christopher, 43, of Waukesha, Wis., elected
at the North Central meeting in Buckhannon, West Va., assigned as
bishop in Minneapolis, replacing retired Bishop Emerson S. Colaw.
   Bishop Susan Burch Morrison, 45, of Baltimore, elected at the
Northeastern meeting in De Kalab, Ill., assigned as bishop in
Philadelphia, replacing Bishop F. Herbert Skeete, who was
transferred to Boston.
   The denomination has one other active woman bishop, Judith Craig
of Detroit, and two previous women bishops, Leontine Kelly of San
Francisco, retired, and the late Marjorie Mathews of Detroit who
died in 1986.
   Other transfers besides Skeete included Bishops George W.
Bashore from Boston to Pittsburgh; Edwin C. Boulton from Fargo,
N.D., to West Canton, Ohio, replacing retired James S. Thomas;
Calvin D. McConnell from Portland, Ore., to Seattle, Wash., and
Melvin G. Talbert from Seattle to San Francisco, replacing the
retired Kelly.
   Also, Bishop John W. Russell of Dallas was transferred to to the
newly created Fort Worth area, formerly combined with Dallas, while
newly elected Bishop Bruce P. Blake, formerly a Winfield, Kan.,
college president, was assigned to Dallas.
   Blake was elected at the South Central meeting in New Orleans,
which also elected Bishops William B. Oden, an Enid, Okla., pastor,
assigned to Baton Rouge, La., replacing the late Walter L.
Underwood, and Dan E. Solomon of Corpus Christi, Texas, assigned to
Oklahoma City, replacing retired John W. Hart.
   Blake, Oden and Solomon were all consecrated in ceremonies at
New Orleans' Roman Catholic Cathedral.
   ``It was a great ecumenical gesture,'' said the city's Catholic
Archbishop Philip Hannan.
   The Western jurisdiction, meeting in San Diego, elected only one
bishop, but it took 38 ballots over about three days to do it. He
is William W. Dew Jr., an Alamo, Calif., pastor and former theology
professor, assigned to Portland, Ore., replacing transferred
McConnell.
   The North Central meeting in De Kalb, besides electing
Christopher, also elected two male bishops.
   They are R. Sheldon Duecker of Muncie, Ill., assigned to
Chicago, replacing retired Jesse DeWitt, and William B. Lewis of
Belleville, ill., assigned to Fargo, N.D., replacing transferred
Boulton.
   Not for about 50 years had one jurisdiction elected so many
bishops in one year as the seven elected in the Southeastern
meeting at Lake Junaluska, N.C.
   One was black, Bishop Joseph B. Bethea, district superintendent
in Raleigh, N.C., assigned as bishop at Columbia, S.C., replacing
retired Roy C. Clark. He becomes the denomination's 13th black
bishop.
   Other Southeastern elections were:
   Bishops Thomas B. Stockton of High Point, N.C., assigned to
Richmond, Va., replacing retired Robert M. Blackburn; H. Hasbrouck
Hughes Jr. of Richmond, assigned to Lakeland, Fla., replacing
retired Earl G. Hunt.
   Also moved were Bishops Richard C. Looney of Knoxville, Tenn.,
assigned a new area of Macon, Ga.; Robert H. Spain of Nashville,
Tenn., assigned to Louisville, Ky., replacing retired Paul A.
Duffey.
   Bishop C. W. Hancock of Macon City, Ga., was assigned to a new
area of Montgomery, Ala., and Bishop Clay F. Lee of Jackson, Miss.,
was moved to Knoxville, Tenn., replacing retired R. Kern Eutsler.
</TEXT>
<NOTE>End Adv for Fri AMs, Aug. 26</NOTE>
