<1ST_LINE>r f PM-BusinessHighlights 2takes   08-23 0535</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 2 takes,0559</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Several big Wall Street firms still are heavily
engaged in program trading while small investors are avoiding the
stock market, according to statistics released by the New York
Stock Exchange.
   The NYSE's first monthly report on program trading provided some
of the most detailed figures yet available on the short-term and
highly profitable trading technique, blamed by some studies for
playing a role in the stock market crash and subsequent volatility
that has frightened away investors.
   The report released Monday showed program trading in July
accounted for 10.1 percent of the exchange's average daily trading
volume.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA MONICA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A management group's offer to take
Wickes Cos. Inc. private in a $598 million leveraged buyout has
brought numerous inquiries from other potential buyers.
   The $12-a-share tender offer, made late Sunday by a management
group led by Wickes Chairman Sanford Sigoloff, included a 60-day
wait before the group would begin buying Wickes stock, to give
other bidders a chance to emerge.
   Numerous potential buyers called Monday, according to Bear
Stearns & Co. Inc., which was retained to advise Wickes management
on the offer.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The management of Lear Siegler Seating Corp.
says it has agreed to purchase the company from Forstmann Little &
Co. in a buyout valued at $500 million.
   Management is being financed in part by the investment firm
Kidder, Peabody Group Inc., which will take an undisclosed equity
stake in the company, according to Monday's announcement.
   Forstmann, a leveraged buyout firm, acquired Lear Siegler in
1986 for $2.1 billion.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   If farmers boost plantings and the drought
eases, this year's massive drain on the U.S. wheat stockpile could
be brought under control in 1989, the Agriculture Department says.
   Total wheat supplies in the 1988-89 marketing year that began on
June 1 are estimated at about 3.1 billion bushels, down more than
20 percent from last season and the lowest in almost a decade, the
department's Economic Research Service said in an outlook report
Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>NEWARK, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Chubb Corp. wants to make sure this
summer's drought doesn't claim another victim along with parched
crops: its good name.
   Stung by criticism it backed away from drought insurance and
left thousands of farmers high and doubly dry, Chubb has set up a
crisis center, mobilized phone-answering troops for toll-free
numbers and taken out newspaper ads.
   Chubb has said applications for the insurance far exceeded the
original $30 million in coverage it had authorized. The company
later increased the authorized amount to $40 million.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farmers hit hard by this year's drought should
think about enrolling highly erodible cropland in the long-term
Conservation Reserve Program, the Agriculture Department says.
   The current signup period for the CRP will end on Aug. 31. More
than 25.5 million acres have been enrolled in previous signups, and
the goal is to have 40 million to 45 million acres in the program
by the end of 1990.
   Under the program, farmers offer bids to take land from crop
production and plant it to grass or trees for 10 years as a guard
against erosion.
</TEXT>
