<2ND_LINE>PM-Business Highlights, 1st add,0541</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Federal Deposit Insurance Corp will try a new
approach, a public auction, to sell more than $75 million in shaky
loans it acquired in its 1984 bailout of the Continental Illinois
National Bank & Trust Co.
   The loans, which include commercial, real estate, energy and
personal loans, are among $5.2 billion in Continental Bank loans
the FDIC purchased for $3.5 billion as part of its $4.5 billion
plan to save the bank from failure.
   The auction will be held Oct. 20, officials said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Department of Housing and Urban
Development says the demands of a homeless assistance group to stop
the sales of foreclosed single-family dwellings would bankrupt a
Federal Housing Administration mortgage insurance fund.
   The fund has helped millions of first-time, low- and
moderate-income homebuyers since its creation in the 1930s, HUD
said Monday.
   HUD called off a sales campaign for foreclosed properties
because of the threat of a lawsuit by the National Housing Law
Project. The group claims HUD is violating a homeless-assistance
law passed last year that requires government agencies to consider
the needs of the homeless before selling foreclosed properties.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SAN FRANCISCO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The new chief of Chevron Corp. says he is
basing his plans for the nation's fourth-largest energy company on
oil prices of less than $20 a barrel.
   Kenneth T. Derr, elected chief executive officer last Friday by
the company's board of directors, told a news conference Monday he
expects oil prices to continue moving in a volatile pattern.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Early indications are that Audi of America Inc.
is regaining some U.S. business lost in recent years, with a new,
renamed line of sedans and station wagons and a warranty covering
routine maintenance, an Audi executive says.
   Sales in the first two weeks after the Aug. 1 introduction of
the 100 and 200 Series cars and warranty were up 59 percent from
the first half of July, Richard Mugg, vice president in charge of
Audi of America, said Monday.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>SANTA BARBARA, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   President Reagan signed legislation
significantly increasing the liability of nuclear power companies
for compensation of the public in the event of an accident.
   The bill signed Monday extends for 15 years a law passed in the
1970s designed to provide such protection.
   The new law, like the old one, requires private insurance of
$150 million per reactor. It increases from $5 million to $63
million per reactor the second-tier insurance, provided by the
federal government.
</TEXT>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Interest-rate worries drove the stock market broadly lower on
Monday. The Dow Jones industrial average, down 21.52 points last
week, fell another 25.78 to close at 1,990.22.
   The dollar finished mostly higher in domestic trading after
rising sharply overseas.
   Bond prices fell in quiet trading.
   Soybean, corn and oat futures prices plummeted their permitted
daily limits on the Chicago Board of Trade; wheat futures also
declined; livestock and meat futures fell; platinum posted sharp
gains to lead precious metals futures higher; energy futures were
mixed; and stock-index futures retreated.
</TEXT>
