<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OilPrices     08-23 0169</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oil Prices,0177</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oil Futures Prices Mostly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oil futures prices are mostly higher in what
analysts called a relatively directionless market.
   On the New York Mercantile Exchange, contracts for September
delivery of West Texas Intermediate, the benchmark grade of U.S.
crude oil, edged up 3 cents a barrel Monday to close at $15.76.
   Monday was the final day of trading in the September contract,
and analysts said the expiration was the key factor in the advance.
   Contracts for September delivery of wholesale unleaded gasoline
slipped 0.07 cent to finish at 47.52 cents a gallon, but other
contract months gained. Wholesale heating oil for September rose
0.25 cent a gallon to 44.73 cents a gallon.
   Analysts said the market was awaiting fresh developments
affecting supply and demand or the 13-nation Organization of
Petroleum Exporting Countries.
   ``The market is trading in two- and three-day trends,'' said
Richard Redoglio, a vice president of Merrill Lynch Energy Futures.
``There's not much news out there to go on.''
</TEXT>
</DOC>
