<DOCNO> AP880823-0202 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0029EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-SpencerGifts Bjt   08-23 0611</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Spencer Gifts, Bjt,0632</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Spencer Gifts Going Yuppie, Moving Away From Inexpensive
Mail-Order Items</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By JOYCE A. VENEZIA</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>EGG HARBOR TOWNSHIP, N.J. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A $400 picture telephone and
other expensive gadgets are taking their places alongside the Santa
Claus toilet paper, windshield ice protectors and other household
items that for years have characterized the Spencer Gifts catalog.
   Changing demands in the mail-order business mean a newer,
increasingly upscale product lineup for Spencer, greater
concentration on retail outlets and a new, computerized telephone
ordering system, company president John Hacala said in a recent
interview.
   For years, Spencer Gifts Inc. could get by with its offerings of
elastic bra extenders, personalized calendar towels and other
inexpensive, unusual household items and gadgets.
   ``It's nothing you need and everything you'd like to have,''
says Laurin LeTort, the company's vice president of human resources.
   But competition and a changing consumer profile have forced some
changes.
   ``The mail-order industry has become a booming business,
especially with more expensive merchandise, such as what L.L. Bean
and J. Crew offers,'' LeTort said of the clothing retailers. ``For
years, Spencer Gifts and several other companies stuck with
lower-price products.
   ``But with postage increases and higher wages, it's become
difficult to operate at that level.''
   In recent years, Spencer has concentrated most of its energy on
retail stores, usually located in shopping malls. The company has
more than 600 stores in 46 states, LeTort said.
   Spencer also plans to change the focus of its catalog
merchandise, in an effort to keep up with its changing customers.
   A first step has been the introduction of several ``A2Z'' stores
and catalogs, featuring more expensive products and gadgets, such
the $400 picture phone, a $30 baseball cap with a solar-powered
fan, a $70 inflatable raft complete with built-in toy machine guns
and a $200 neon telephone.
   Spencer Gifts stores are geared to attract younger consumers,
while catalogs from Spencer Gifts Inc. traditionally have attracted
women over 45 years old in rural America, Hacala said.
   ``But now 50 percent of American women are in the workforce, and
time is not available to hit the stores as much, so they like to
shop out of a catalog for the things they really need,'' he said.
   Spencer Gifts eventually will change its catalog offerings to
reflect the shopping trend, Hacala says. He says the company also
must select more expensive products for financial reasons.
   ``We can't continue concentrating on 88-cent products,'' Hacala
says. ``You can't pack and ship that merchandise cost-effectively.''
   The final figures are not in but Spencer Gifts, a wholly-owned
subsidiary of MCA Inc. in Los Angeles, projects sales of $300
million for 1987.
   In the catalog business, LeTort says, the company is ``about the
last of the few survivors at the lower end of the market. We need
to reposition ourselves to go after a higher profit margin.''
   By switching its focus, Spencer Gifts will transfer its
mail-order facility in Atlantic City to Williamsburg, Va., where
labor is more readily available at lower wages than in the
Northeast. More than 200 full-time jobs will be affected, although
another 800 or so people traditionally have been hired as temporary
packers during the busy holiday season, Hacala says.
   He says the company's national headquarters will remain in Egg
Harbor Township.
   Spencer also must modernize its mail-order system, one of the
originals in the business.
   Since 1947, a paper order form in each catalog has been the only
way to order, Hacala said. Now, the company is investing in an
elaborate computer system that will allow customers to order via a
toll-free telephone number, he said.
   ``People want instant gratification,'' he said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
