<DOCNO> AP880823-0204 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0033EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-RevivingAudi     08-23 0483</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Reviving Audi,0500</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Renamed Car May Be Reviving Sales For Audi</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By WILLIAM S. BERGSTROM</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DETROIT (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Audi of America Inc. is showing signs of
rebounding from a dramatic sales decline that followed complaints
and lawsuits over accidents caused by unintended acceleration of
some Audis, according to one company executive.
   Richard Mugg, vice president in charge of Audi of America, said
Monday that if the company maintained its early August sales pace
it would top the month's sales goal of 2,600 cars.
   ``In the past, for Audi, that would have been no big deal. But
when you are in a recovery process it's very encouraging,'' he said.
   Mugg credited Audi's revision and renaming of one line of U.S.
cars, plus a new warranty aimed at high-cost maintenance, for
aiding the early sales rebound.
   Sales in the first two weeks after the Aug. 1 introduction of
Audi's new warranty and new 100 and 200 Series cars were up 59
percent from the first half of July, Mugg said.
   He acknowledged that July was a slow month to compare with, that
late summer sales usually are not brisk and that July also marked
the closeout of the discontinued Audi 5000 line.
   Audi of America's sales reached about 74,000 in 1985 but dropped
to 41,000 last year _ and Mugg has projected 27,000 in sales for
this year _ after a wave of complaints of sudden, unintended
acceleration incidents leading to accidents and lawsuits.
   The complaints also have involved other brands of automobiles,
but not as often as Audis. Audi engineers and other investigators
have failed to find a mechanical fault.
   Audi began installing interlock devices designed to prevent the
car from being put accidentially into gear with a foot on the
accelerator, and 275,000 automatic transmission cars were recalled
in October 1987 for installation of the devices.
   Mugg said Audi since then had counted only 14 sudden
acceleration complaints, and he said those were on cars with
improperly installed interlocks.
   The National Highway Traffic Safety Board is investigating 433
complaints involving the interlock-equipped Audis, but NHTSB
spokesman Ron DeFore said the complaints, which still must be
confirmed, involve engine surge rather than the full acceleration
described in earlier complaints.
   ``We have felt that an interlock was sufficient,'' DeFore said.
   Audi's former three-year, 50,000-mile warranty was expanded to
cover scheduled maintenance, all dealer visits and even routine oil
changes and parts such as wiper blades, brake pads and light bulbs.
   ``We're the only one covering maintenance and wear and tear for
50,000 miles,'' Mugg said.
   Audi's marketing also is emphasizing technological advances such
as anti-lock braking systems and all-wheel drive available on 100
and 200 series Audis, Mugg said.
   While the new models show only minor exterior changes from the
Audi 5000 body shell, the cars are more extensively changed beneath
the skin, with more than 1,400 new parts, Mugg said.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0205 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0727EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f PM-Dollar-Gold     08-23 0407</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Dollar-Gold,0425</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Dollar Lower But Rebounding, Gold Slightly Higher</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A round of coordinated central bank intervention
pushed the dollar lower in early European trading today but dealers
said the U.S. currency was rebounding as the market shrugged off
the attempt to check its advance.
   Gold prices were higher in quiet trading.
   The central banks of West Germany, Switzerland and Austria said
they sold dollars in the open market in Frankfurt this morning and
the Deutsche Bundesbank, West Germany's central bank, said it had
intervened earlier in the day in Asian trading.
   None of the banks would say how many dollars they sold but
dealers in Frankfurt and Rome said the size of the intervention was
such that the market easily absorbed it.
   One Rome trader estimated the total size of the intervention at
``maybe several hundred million dollars.''
   Dealers said the dollar continues to be well bid despite the
show of unity by central banks to keep the currency under control.
   ``The market is still bullish'' toward the dollar, one trader
said.
   Traders said two U.S. economic indicators being released later
today could give the market some new momentum.
   The market expects July consumer prices to rise 0.4 percent
following a 0.3 percent rise in June and durable goods orders to
drop 5.4 percent in July following a 9.4 percent rise in June,
dealers said.
   In Tokyo, where the business day ends before Europe's begins,
the dollar closed at 133.93 yen, up fractionally from 133.88 yen
late Monday. Later, in London, it was quoted at 133.90 yen.
   Other dollar rates at midmorning, compared with late Monday's
rates, included: 1.9056 West German marks, down from 1.9190; 1.6035
Swiss francs, down from 1.6105; 6.4660 French francs, down from
6.5050; 2.1498 Dutch guilders, down from 2.1605; 1,411.60 Italian
lire, down from 1,417.00; and 1.23 Canadian dollars, up from 1.2291.
   In London, the British pound rose to $1.6815, compared with
$1.6767 late Monday.
   Gold opened in London at a bid price of $433.10 a troy ounce and
at midmorning, the city's five major bullion dealers fixed a
recommended price of $432.70, both up from Monday's late bid of
$432.
   In Zurich, the bid price was $432.90, up from $431 bid late
Monday.
   Earlier, in Hong Kong, gold rose $2.58 to close at a bid $434.59.
   Silver also rose in London where it was quoted at a bid price of
$6.74 a troy ounce, compared with Monday's $6.64.
</TEXT>
