<2ND_LINE>PM-Japan-Markets,0270</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stocks Fall, Dollar Rises Slightly</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Tokyo Stock Exchange suffered a decline for the
second day in a row today amid fears of higher interest rates and
lack of direction in the market, while the dollar held firm,
closing at 133.93 yen.
   The Nikkei Stock Average of 225 selected issues plunged 159.23
points, following a 130.24-point loss Monday, to end the day's
trading at 27,919.95. It was the first time for the Nikkei average
to close below the 28,000-point level since Aug. 16.
   Volume on the first section was thin, an estimated 500 million
shares, down from the previous day's 600 million.
   Declining share prices and modest trading in Tokyo were because
of investors' wait-and-see mood due to spreading fear of higher
interest rates world-wide, stock dealers said.
   ``The overnight plunge on Wall Street directly affected us
today,'' said Yoshio Shimoyama of Nikko Securities Co. in Tokyo.
Influence on share prices and volume in Tokyo came mainly from the
United States, he said.
   Investors are ``cautious'' waiting for the release of the U.S.
consumer price index today, and the revised gross national product
figure for April-June on Thursday,'' Shimoyama said. Tokyo trading
``is up to what happens in New York.''
   On the foreign exchange market, the U.S. currency opened at
133.75 and moved in a narrow range of 133.75-134.00 yen before
finishing at 133.93, up 0.05 yen from Monday's close.
   Notable movement in the currency market is also unlikely ahead
of the scheduled release of the two U.S. reports this week,
exchange dealers said.
</TEXT>
