<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0733EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f PM-FarmScene     08-23 0908</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Farm Scene,0934</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Drain on Wheat Stockpile Could Ease Next Year</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DON KENDALL</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Farm Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Next year could bring a leveling off of the
massive drain on the U.S. wheat stockpile if the drought eases and
farmers expand plantings as expected, says the Agriculture
Department.
   The department's Economic Research Service says the total wheat
supply for the 1988-89 marketing year that began June 1 is about
3.1 billion bushels, down more than 20 percent from last season and
the lowest in almost a decade.
   More than 22 million acres of wheat land were idled under the
USDA's acreage program this year when farmers were required to set
aside 27.5 percent of their base acres. For 1989, they have to idle
only 10 percent.
   ``With increased area and average yields in 1989-90, the United
States would be able to produce 2.5 billion bushels of wheat,
enough to cover likely use without a further stock decline,'' the
report said Monday.
   Although the supply _ this year's harvest plus excess left over
from previous crops _ will be more than enough to meet expected
use, the wheat inventory by next June 1 is expected to be around
597 million bushels, down from 1.266 billion bushels this June 1.
   Based on the current rate of wheat use for domestic consumption
and exports, the U.S. wheat supply next June 1 would represent an
87-day supply, compared with reserves for 185 days this June 1. It
also would be the smallest since 1973-74.
   This year's wheat harvest of 1.82 billion bushels is far short
of the more than 2.5 billion bushels needed to cover expected
domestic and export demands in 1988-89. The shortfall of 684
million bushels has to come out of reserves.
   Thus, according to the report, the beginning inventory of 1.266
billion bushels is drawn down by the shortfall to 582 million
bushels. When imports of 15 million bushels are added, the
projected U.S. wheat stockpile next June 1 becomes 597 million
bushels.
   ``Largely due to drought, hard red spring (HRS) wheat production
is forecast to decline 56 percent in 1988 to 188 million bushels,''
the report said. ``However, indications are that HRS and durum crop
quality is higher than expected, and protein content is rated
high.''
   Drought struck HRS and durum wheat areas in the northern plains,
including the Dakotas, severely this year.
   ``Hard red winter (HRW) production in 1988 is an estimated 894
million bushels, down 12 percent from a year earlier, as area and
yields are forecast lower,'' the report said. ``In contrast, soft
red winter (SRW) production is up 33 percent in 1988, as area and
yield increased.''
   The report said some farmers in the SRW areas do not participate
in the government's wheat program and had stopped planting when
prices dropped in the mid-1980s. However, last fall prices began to
rise, and growers expanded plantings.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Agriculture Department officials are advising
farmers who suffered drought damage to consider enrolling highly
erodible cropland in the long-term Conservation Reserve Program.
   The current signup period for the CRP will end Aug. 31. More
than 25.5 million acres have been enrolled in previous signups, and
the goal is to have 40 million to 45 million acres in the program
by the end of 1990.
   Under the program, farmers offer bids to take land from crop
production and plant it to grass or trees for 10 years as a guard
against erosion. In return, they get federal assistance to pay for
up to half of the cost of establishing the protective cover, plus
annual rental payments for the CRP land.
   Vern Neppl, acting executive vice president of the department's
Commodity Credit Corp., said Monday that farmers may bid to enroll
eligible land that has not been harvested in 1988 due to drought.
   ``If their bids are accepted, the producers will receive their
first CRP rental payments in 1988,'' Neppl said. ``Also, they will
be guaranteed payments for nine more years, an additional source of
income regardless of weather condition during those years.''
   Cropland that has been hayed in counties approved for drought
relief is eligible for the CRP if it meets program requirements,
but there may be a reduction in the 1988 payment, Neppl said.
Producers also have the option of enrolling land for 1989.
   Enrollment of erodible land in the CRP will help farmers meet
the conservation provisions of the 1985 farm law, Neppl said. Those
require producers to have an approved conservation plan for
erodible land in place by Jan. 1, 1990, to remain eligible for USDA
program benefits.
</TEXT>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The Agriculture Department will hold a public
hearing next month in Georgia to explore the possibility of setting
up a grower-financed program for researching and promoting Vidalia
onions.
   Officials said Monday that a Vidalia onion producer group
representing 19 southeast Georgia counties believes the program is
needed ``to distinguish the Vidalia onion in the marketplace, and
by finding more efficient ways to produce, distribute and store
their onions.''
   Enthusiasts say the Vidalia onion has no peer when it comes to
sweetness and munchiness, but growers in some other parts of the
nation contend their onions are just as sweet and munchy.
   The USDA said the hearing will be Sept. 20 in Lyons, Ga. Further
information can be obtained from John R. Toth, Southeast Marketing
Field Office, USDA, 500 3rd St. N.W., Winter Haven, Fla. 33881.
Phone 813 299-4770.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
