<1ST_LINE>r f PM-OregonMagazine     08-23 0224</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Oregon Magazine,0234</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Oregon Magazine Sold to Publisher of Pacific Northwest Magazine</HEAD>
<DATELINE>PORTLAND, Ore. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Oregon Magazine has been sold to the
publisher of Seattle-based Pacific Northwest, a monthly magazine,
and the two publications will be merged immediately, company
officials announced.
   Terms of the sale were not disclosed with the announcement
Monday.
   Portland-based New Oregon Publishers Inc., publisher of Oregon
Magazine, said in a news release that the bi-monthly magazine's
July-August issue was its last.
   New Oregon Publishers is owned by Win McCormack, who created
Oregon Magazine from Oregon Times, a newsprint monthly, after he
bought that publication in 1975.
   Pacific Northwest Media Inc., publisher of Pacific Northwest,
said it would not continue Oregon Magazine as a separate
publication.
   Subscribers to Oregon Magazine will receive Pacific Northwest
instead or can request a refund of their remaining subscription,
said Peter Potterfield, editor and publisher of Pacific Northwest.
   McCormack said one of the primary reasons for the sale was to
raise money to finance and expand his company's special
publications division, which publishes special-event programs,
guides and catalogs.
   ``We believe that special, highly focused publications of this
nature are a more sensible and lucrative way to publish in this
particular marketplace, and that periodical magazine publishing is
better done over a wider geographic area than the state of Oregon
encompasses by itself,'' McCormack said.
</TEXT>
