<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0944EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Japan-InsiderTrading     08-23 0320</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Japan-Insider Trading,0330</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Law On Suspicious Trading Takes Effect In Japan</HEAD>
<DATELINE>TOKYO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   An article of Japan's recently revised Securities
and Exchange Law broadening the Ministry of Finance's powers to
investigate suspicious trading took effect Tuesday.
   Article 154 of the new law empowers the ministry to directly
query companies listed on Japan's stock exchanges in its
investigations of suspicious trading. Until now, the ministry has
only been able to gather information from the exchanges.
   Along with Article 154, changes in securities law permitting
trading of cash-settled index futures and options were put into
effect Tuesday.
   Reports in the Japanese press speculated that Article 154 was
put into effect ahead of schedule in response to the public outcry
over the shady dealings, and possibly insider trading, which came
to light in two recent stock trading scandals.
   ``There have been reports all over that enforcement of this part
of the law was moved foward, but these are all mistakes,'' said a
spokesman at the ministry's securities division.
   Both the ministry and the Tokyo Stock Exchange are investigating
unusual trading in shares of Sankyo Seiki Manufacturing Co. ahead
of the official announcement of a deal between Sankyo Seikei and
Nippon Steel Corp., which sent Sankyo Seikei shares sharply higher.
   The ministry enjoys wide discretion in the timing of enforcement
of new securities law. Reports surfaced in recent weeks that the
ministry might speed enforcement of some portions of the new
securities law.
   Article 154 does not extend the ministry's reach in its
investigations to companies whose shares are listed for
over-the-counter trading, as those of Recruit Cosmos, the center of
attention in the other of the two recent scandals.
   Aides to a number of prominent politicians, and public figures
including journalists, were found to have been allowed to buy
shares of Recruit Cosmos before the shares were listed to trade
over the counter. The shares surged in value after the registration.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0212 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 0946EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Britain-Economy     08-23 0205</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Economy,0215</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Britain's Output Grew 1.3 Percent in Second Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Britain's economy grew at a faster-than-expected
1.3 percent in the second quarter, the government said Tuesday.
   The country's inflation-adjusted gross domestic product,
measured by total output of goods and services, rose 5.1 percent
from the second quarter of 1987, the Central Statistics Office said.
   The GDP index, which uses a 1980 base of 100, rose to a
seasonally-adjusted 124.3 in the second quarter from a revised
122.7 in the first quarter and 118.2 in the second quarter of 1987,
the office said said.
   The first-quarter index was previously reported as 122.5.
   The markets had expected a 1 percent rise in the second quarter.
   Output in the manufacturing sector grew 1.6 percent in the
latest period, while service sector output grew 1.7 percent, the
office said.
   The index is considered the most reliable guide to short-term
movements in the economy.
   Britain also calculates GDP based on expenditure as well as on
income data and publishes an average estimate of the three GDP
measures, which is considered the best guide to long-term movements
in the economy.
   The office is due to report the average estimate of GDP for the
second quarter in September.
</TEXT>
