<2ND_LINE>PM-Economy Rdp, 1st Ld-Writethru,0498</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Consumer Price Rise, Durable Goods Orders Fall in July</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: Tops with 8 new grafs with reports on consumer prices and
durable goods. Picks up 2nd graf pvs, The Dow ...</NOTE>
<BYLINE>By The Associated Press</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Consumer prices rose 0.4 percent in July while durable goods
orders plunged 7 percent, the biggest drop in four years, the
government said today in reports that cooled fears of inflation.
   In the credit markets, bond prices moved higher after the
reports were released, sending their yields lower. Traders bought
bonds out of confidence that their value would not be eroded by
surging inflation.
   The rise in consumer prices was fueled by a 1.4 percent rise in
prices at grocery stores, the steepest one-month rise in that
category in 4{ years, according to the Labor Department report.
   July's overall gain, if it persisted for 12 months, would amount
to a yearly inflation rate of 5.2 percent.
   The Commerce Department, meanwhile, said total orders for
durable goods fell to a seasonally adjusted $116.6 billion last
month, primarily because of a huge decline in orders for cars,
aircraft and ships and tanks.
   It was the biggest decline in orders for durable goods since a
7.2 percent drop in April 1984. In June, orders had risen at the
fastest pace in more than six years, climbing by 8.7 percent.
   Prices of the widely followed 30-year Treasury bond were up
about $6 for every $1,000 in face value while their yields slipped
to 9.38 percent from 9.45 percent late Monday.
   Speculation about higher interest rates had weighed on the
financial markets on Monday, pushing stock prices lower and bond
prices lower.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrial stocks fell 25.78 to
1,990.22 on Monday, its first close below 2,000 in nearly three
months.
   Bond prices fell, with the yield on the benchmark 30-year
Treasury bond rising to 9.45 percent from 9.39 percent late in
Friday's session.
   ``This is very nervous trading,'' Jack Baker, head of block
trading at Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc., said of Monday's action.
``This isn't the kind of market that's going to bring people off
the sidelines.''
   The Dow Jones close Monday was its lowest since it finished at
1,956.44 on May 27, the day before the three-day Memorial Day
holiday. When traders returned May 31, the Dow climbed 74.68 points.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of nearly 3 to 1
among issues listed on the New York Stock Exchange.
   The economy has been growing at such a strong pace that the
Federal Reserve boosted its rate on loans to member banks by a half
percentage point to 6.5 percent earlier this month in a bid to curb
inflation.
   Monday's trading was characterized by indecision, analysts said.
Traders searching for clues to the economy's direction looked ahead
to today's report on consumer prices and Thursday's revised
estimate of second-quarter economic growth.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
