<1ST_LINE>r f PM-StockPrivileges     08-23 0196</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Stock Privileges,0203</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Court Rules Exec Entitled to Damages After Being Denied Stock
Privileges</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal judge has ruled a former Duff & Phelps
Inc. executive is entitled to nearly $1 million in damages because
he was denied stock privileges enjoyed by a fellow executive.
   U.S. District Judge Prentice Marshall said Monday that Paul Much
``was not dealt with honestly or fairly'' because he was forced by
the company to sell back his Duff & Phelps stock in 1983 when he
quit for another job.
   Much had charged in his lawsuit that at the same time he was
leaving the company, the Duff & Phelps board permitted another
employee, Carol Franchik, to keep her stock after she was fired for
having an affair with the firm's chairman Claire Hansen.
   On Nov. 29, 1983, Much sold back his 485 shares of stock in the
privately held firm for $59,910.
   Ms. Franchik, however, kept her stock until the company was
sold, then divested her 300 shares for a $600,000 profit.
   Marshall said Hansen allowed Ms. Franchik to keep her stock
because she had threatened to bring a ``potentially valuable gender
discrimination case against them.''
</TEXT>
