<1ST_LINE>u f PM-BoardofTrade Open   08-23 0314</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>PM-Board of Trade, Open,0326</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Crop Futures Open Mixed</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Grain and soybean futures opened mixed today on
the Chicago Board of Trade with fresh export business supporting
the corn and wheat markets while wetter, cooler weather pressured
soybean prices.
   Morocco, South Korea, Taiwan and Tunisia all had tender offers
pending for U.S. corn this morning, and Indonesia and Tunisia were
awaiting responses to their wheat bids, analysts said.
   But foreign demand for U.S. soybean products remained flat.
   ``The soybean market is still trying to find some sort of demand
out there,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``The U.S. soybean
oil market is overpriced and there's still a lot of soybean meal
supply in the Southern Hemisphere.''
   The arrival of cooler, wetter weather in the Midwest was seen as
helping the soybean crop. But cool temperatures were considered
deterimental to the corn crop, which is rapidly maturing.
   In early trading, wheat was 1 cent to 3{ cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.84 a bushel; corn was {
cent to 2{ cents higher with September at $2.79 a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 4\ cents higher with September at $2.49 a bushel;
soybeans were 3 cents lower to 3 cents higher with September at
$8.38 a bushel.
   Cattle futures were mostly lower while pork futures were higher
in early trading on the Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .35 cent lower to .15 cent higher with October
at 70.40 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .15 cent to .45 cent
lower with August at 81.40 cents a pound; hogs were .05 cent to .70
cent higher with October at 40.47 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were unchanged to 1.33 cents higher with August at 37.10
cents a pound.
   Livestock and meat futures settled lower on Monday.
</TEXT>
