<1ST_LINE>r f BC-Earns-Deere     08-23 0265</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Earns-Deere,0275</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Deere More Than Triples Earnings in Third Quarter</HEAD>
<DATELINE>MOLINE, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Farm machinery-maker Deere & Co. more than
tripled its earnings and increased sales 16 percent in the third
quarter of 1988, despite the drought gripping much of the Farm
Belt, the company reported today.
   Deere, based in Moline, reported net earnings of $81 million, or
$1.14 per share, up from $25.5 million, or 38 cents per share, for
the three-month period ending July 31.
   Sales for the quarter were $1.39 billion vs. year-earlier sales
of $1.19 billion for the period.
   ``Our increased profitability is due primarily to higher sales
and production volumes, some improvement in price realization and
greater efficiencies in our worldwide operations,'' Deere Chairman
Robert A. Hanson said in a news release.
   ``However, higher prices for some raw materials are partially
offsetting these improvements.''
   Hanson said it was hard to predict the impact of the drought on
Deere's earnings performance. Although crop yields are down, the
prices for farm products has risen and commodity reserves are
dropping.
   ``Retail sales of our agricultural and lawn-and-grounds-care
equipment were lower in the latter part of the quarter,'' he said.
``We believe continuing dry weather could affect retail demand in
some areas during the remainder of the year.
   Deere's earnings for the first nine months of its fiscal year
totaled $234.9 million or $3.25 a share, vs. a net loss of $131.7
million during the same period of 1987, a strike-marred year. Sales
for the first three quarters were $3.88 billion, a 38 percent jump
over last year's sales of $2.8 billion.
</TEXT>
