<2ND_LINE>PM-Wall Street 3pm,0354</2ND_LINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market turned mostly lower this
afternoon, as blue-chip issues gave up some earlier gains and the
broader market retreated.
   Trading slowed from Monday's sluggish pace.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 25.78 points
on Monday to its lowest level since late May, was down another 4.27
at 1,985.95 with one hour left in the session.
   Declining issues outpaced gainers by a margin of 8 to 5 on the
New York Stock Exchange, with 539 up, 825 down and 553 unchanged.
   Big Board volume amounted to 99.08 million shares at 3 p.m. on
Wall Street, compared with 104.34 million shares at the same point
on Monday.
   Market analysts said a pair of new economic reports showing a
rise in consumer prices in July and a decline in durable goods
orders had been largely anticipated, and failed to provide traders
with much direction.
   Before the market opened, the Labor Department reported consumer
prices rose 0.4 percent in July and the Commerce Department said
orders for durable goods fell 7 percent in the same month.
   The reports sparked a mild rally in the bond market, where
traders have been wary for the past few weeks of signs of
accelerating inflation combined with economic strength.
   By midafternoon, the prices of the closely-watched 30-year
Treasury bond was up about $6.25 for every $1,000 in face value, as
its yield fell to 9.38 percent from 9.45 percent late Monday.
   But stock prices failed to follow bonds higher.
   Among actively-traded issues on the NYSE, Knight Ridder was down
{ at 38[, Coca Cola was up ] at 38~, Clorox was up 1\ at 30} and
International Business Machines was down [ at 110|.
   Wickes was off [ at 13[. Its management has proposed buying the
company in a leverage buyout for $12 a share in cash and stock.
   The NYSE composite index was off 0.20 at 145.74. On the American
Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 0.92 to 292.09.
</TEXT>
