<HEAD>Soybeans, Corn Close Lower; Wheat Rises</HEAD>
<DATELINE>CHICAGO (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices closed sharply lower
Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to rain in the
Farm Belt. Corn also closed lower while wheat advanced on fresh
export demand.
   The Agriculture Department said soybeans suffered immense stress
in last week's heat wave, and private analysts predicted the USDA
would again lower its soybean production estimate in its Sept. 12
crop production report.
   But the market ignored those bullish factors and focused on
recent rain and cooler temperatures in the Midwest.
   ``It's looking pretty good for the beans,'' said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York. ``With the moisture that has come in, you're
getting some pretty good recovery yield reports.''
   Stronger export demand surfaced for both wheat and corn, but
corn futures retreated in sympathy with the soybeans, Loewy said.
   At the close, wheat was 2 cents to 5 cents higher with the
contract for delivery in September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was
unchanged to 4\ cents lower with September at $2.73 a bushel; oats
were 1{ cents lower to 1 cent higher with September at $2.47{ a
bushel; soybeans were 5 cents to 35{ cents lower with September at
$8.08 a bushel.
</TEXT>
