<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1851EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-CEOs-Bush     08-23 0277</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-CEOs-Bush,0288</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Most CEOs Believe Bush Would Raise Taxes, Survey Says</HEAD>
<NOTE>Eds: For release at 6 p.m. EDT.</NOTE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A majority of the chief executive officers of
the nation's largest corporations believe George Bush would raise
taxes if elected president, according to a survey released Tuesday
by Fortune magazine.
   The survey, which will appear in Fortune's Sept. 12 issue, was
taken just before the Republican Party convention began last week.
It polled 215 chief executive officers from the biggest U.S.
industrial and service companies.
   Bush has made his pledge not to raise taxes a central element of
the campaign.
   In the survey, however, 65 percent of the CEOs canvassed said
they believe Bush would raise taxes, while only 31 percent believe
he would not.
   Ninety-eight percent of the chief executives polled believe
Democratic presidential candidate Michael Dukakis would raise taxes
if elected.
   Many of the CEOs believe Bush would be less likely than Dukakis
to raise taxes on companies and affluent individuals, and they
suggest the Republican candidate could opt for consumption taxes
instead.
   Eighty-six percent of the CEOs said they will vote for Bush in
the November election, compared with 7 percent who plan to vote for
Dukakis.
   But the respondents said they weren't as confident as they were
in January that the Republicans would retain the White House. Fifty
percent now expect Bush to win, compared with 90 percent in
January, while 33 percent anticipate a Dukakis victory.
   Dukakis's alliances with Jesse Jackson to his left and Sen.
Lloyd Bentsen to his right are among the main reasons the
executives believe a Republican victory is now less certain, the
survey showed.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> AP880823-0239 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1857EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>r f AM-SuperconductingAgreement     08-23 0462</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Superconducting Agreement,0475</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Du Pont And University Of Houston Sign Agreement On
Superconductivity</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By MICHAEL L. GRACZYK</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The University of Houston and Du Pont Co. on
Tuesday signed what officials said was a first-of-its-kind
agreement under which the company will license and commercialize
superconducting products and processes based on discoveries of
school researcher Paul Chu.
   The university receives an initial payment of $1.5 million under
the agreement. In addition, Du Pont will pay the school $1.5
million upon issuance to the university of a U.S. patent covering
the superconducting material developed by Chu, considered a world
leader in the field, and another $1.5 million two years after that
patent is issued.
   Richard L. Van Horn, university president, said the agreement
could be worth millions more to the school because of royalties
amounting to 50 percent on products of commercial interest to Du
Pont and 75 percent on products not of commercial interest.
   ``It's very hard to estimate,'' Van Horn said. ``It could be in
the area of $4 million or it could be the sky's the limit. It could
be $10 million or $20 million or more. It certainly will be in the
millions of dollars.''
   The money will go for further research at the university, he
said.
   Superconductors are materials that conduct electricity without
resistance and repel magnetic fields. Their use had been limited by
the need to cool them with liquid helium to minus 450 degrees
Fahrenheit, but Chu and his research team, who he referred to as
``unknown heroes,'' found a new superconductor that works at higher
temperatures.
   The temperature of the new material is high enough to allow the
use of cheap, readily available liquid nitrogen as a coolant. Until
that discovery, superconductivity could be achieved only with the
much scarcer liquid helium.
   A superconducting material that works at room temperature holds
the promise of major advances in the production and use of
electricity, more powerful magnets and motors, more sensitive
medical equipment and more powerful beams for smashing atoms.
   Constantine S. Nicandros, executive vice president of Du Pont
and president of Conoco Inc., a Du Pont subsidiary, said the
30-page agreement was better than a solid prospect on an oil well.
   ``We regard Paul Chu and the University of Houston as much more
of a blue chip investment than a gamble,'' Nicandros said.
   Chu, who under the standard university agreement stands to
personally gain half of the profits the school receives from
patents, said Du Pont's presence would enable the benefits of
discoveries in his laboratory to get more quickly into commercial
development.
   Officials of Du Pont and the University of Houston said it was
difficult to estimate when products may become commercially
available or what those products might be.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
