<1ST_LINE>r f AM-USX-Plant     08-23 0186</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-USX-Plant,0195</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Texas Plant Sought by Iraq Also Wanted by Birmingham Steel</HEAD>
<DATELINE>HOUSTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Officials with the Birmingham Steel Corp. say
they are interested in buying the local USX Corp. steel plant that
has been idle for two years, if a deal to sell the mill to Iraq
doesn't go through.
   Birmingham Steel, based in Birmingham, Ala., and another
unidentified group offered to buy the plant for $115 million in a
deal for the building, property and equipment.
   Company officials said Iraq's offer of $100 million was for
plant and equipment. The Iraqis are interested in dismantling the
plant to be shipped home in pieces and reassembled.
   Rep. Jack Fields, R-Texas, is opposing the Iraq deal, saying the
sale would reduce this country's steelmaking capabilities and
increase domestic steel prices.
   Fields said Iraq's ambassador to the United States, Abdul-Amir
al-Anbari, had told him a $1 million downpayment already had been
made to USX.
   The steel plant, which once employed 2,000, was shut down two
years ago.
   United Steelworkers union officials also expressed anger Monday
that USX is negotiating to sell the equipment to Iraq.
</TEXT>
