<1ST_LINE>u f AM-CommodityRdp     08-23 0824</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Commodity Rdp,0856</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Weather Change Sends Soybean Futures To 12-Week Low</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By DAVID DISHNEAU</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<TEXT>
   Soybean futures prices tumbled to a 12-week low of $8.07 a
bushel Tuesday on the Chicago Board of Trade in reaction to rain
and cooler weather in the drought-stricken Farm Belt.
   Corn and oat futures also moved lower while wheat advanced.
   On other markets, cotton, coffee and energy futures fell
sharply; precious metals were mixed; livestock and meat futures
were mixed; and stock-index futures advanced.
   The Agriculture Department said soybeans suffered immense stress
in last week's heat wave, and private analysts predicted the USDA
would again lower its soybean production estimate in its Sept. 12
crop production report.
   But the market ignored those bullish factors and focused on
recent rain and cooler temperatures in the Midwest.
   ``It's looking pretty good for the beans,'' said Richard Loewy,
senior grain and oilseed analyst with Prudential-Bache Securities
Inc. in New York. ``With the moisture that has come in, you're
getting some pretty good recovery yield reports.''
   Stronger export demand surfaced for both wheat and corn, but
most corn futures retreated in sympathy with the soybeans, Loewy
said.
   Demand for U.S. soybean products remained flat.
   ``The soybean market is still trying to find some sort of demand
out there,'' said Cathy Leow, an assistant vice president with
Thomson McKinnon Securities Inc. in New York. ``The U.S. soybean
oil market is overpriced and there's still a lot of soybean meal
supply in the Southern Hemisphere.''
   Wheat settled unchanged to 5 cents higher with the contract for
delivery in September at $3.86 a bushel; corn was 3{ cents lower to
\ cent higher with September at $2.73} a bushel; oats were
unchanged to 1{ cents lower with September at $2.47{ a bushel;
soybeans were 5 cents to 34 cents lower with September at $8.07 a
bushel.
   Cotton futures fell sharply on the New York Cotton Exchange
following the USDA's decision late Monday to revise the cotton
program to make U.S. cotton more competitive on the world market,
said Ernest Simon, cotton specialist with Prudential-Bache
Securities Inc. in New York.
   The price support program has kept the price of U.S. cotton
significantly higher than that produced by other nations despite
abundant U.S. supplies.
   Cotton for October delivery traded down the 2-cents-a-pound
daily limit during the session but closed 1.80 cents lower at 50.50
cents a pound.
   Coffee futures prices plummeted near the close on mostly
technical factors in the absence of fresh supply-and-demand news,
analysts said.
   The coffee market has been volatile lately and likely will
remain so through Sept. 20, when the contract for September
delivery expires, said Kim Badenhop, an analyst in New York with
Merrill Lynch Capital Markets Inc.
   ``Traders are having trouble trying to justify major moves in
either direction,'' he said. ``You get a run up and then everybody
sells and it just gets knocked on its rear end again.''
   The September contract settled 4.04 cents lower at $1.2122 a
pound.
   Oil futures prices declined in light trading on the New York
Mercantile Exchange amid investor anticipation of higher oil
product inventories, analysts said.
   In a report issued after the close, the American Petroleum
Institute said that while stocks of gasoline and distillates rose
last week, crude oil inventories declined by nearly 4.3 million
barrels.
   Analysts had expected a buildup of 2 million to 4 million
barrels of crude, said John Azarow of Shearson Lehman Hutton Inc.
   The API reported gasoline stocks were up 349,000 barrels and
distallate stocks rose 2.1 million barrels.
   Analysts also said the oil market declined on a report that
Saudi Arabia had exceeded its OPEC crude oil production quota
during the first three weeks of August.
   West Texas Intermediate crude oil settled 21 cents to 31 cents
lower with October at $15.70 a barrel; heating oil was .47 cent to
.79 cent lower with September at 44.03 cents a gallon; unleaded
gasoline was .18 cent to .34 cent lower with September at 47.18
cents a gallon.
   Gold futures fell slightly on New York's Commodity Exchange in
response to the drop in oil prices while silver was nearly
unchanged.
   Gold settled $1.40 to $1.50 lower with October at $436 a troy
ounce; silver was unchanged to 0.4 cent lower with September
unchanged at $6.74 a troy ounce.
   Livestock and meat futures finished narrowly mixed on the
Chicago Mercantile Exchange.
   Live cattle were .07 cent to .25 cents lower with October at
70.87 cents a pound; feeder cattle were .13 cent lower to .25 cent
higher with August at 81.42 cents a pound; hogs were .10 cent lower
to .57 cent higher with October at 40.37 cents a pound; frozen pork
bellies were .57 cent lower to .70 cent higher with August at 36.95
cents a pound.
   Stock index futures advanced slightly on the Chicago Merc, where
the contract for September delivery of the Standard & Poor's 500
index settled .70 point higher at 257.30.
</TEXT>
