<1ST_LINE>u f AM-WallStreet     08-23 0655</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Wall Street,0679</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Stock Market Barely Budges in Sluggish Trading</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By SKIP WOLLENBERG</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>AP Business Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The stock market finished about where it started
Tuesday after a listless session distinguished chiefly by one of
the lowest trading volumes of the year.
   The first of some widely-anticipated economic reports due for
release this week failed to inspire either buying or selling
pressure.
   The Dow Jones average of 30 industrials, which fell 25.78 points
on Monday to reach it lowest level in nearly three months, gave up
another 0.89 to close at 1,989.33. That is its lowest close since
it ended at 1,956.44 on May 27.
   Declining issues outnumbered gainers by about 8 to 5 in
nationwide trading of New York Stock Exchange-listed stocks, with
552 issues up, 811 down and 580 unchanged. The NYSE index finished
unchanged at 145.94.
   Volume on the floor of the NYSE came to 119.54 million shares,
down from 122.25 million in the previous session and the lowest
since 113.4 million shares were traded on Aug. 5. There have only
been two other days this year when trading volume was lower than it
was Tuesday _ May 23, when it was 102.64 million shares, and June
20, when it was 116.75 million.
   ``Everyone is at the beach,'' said Tom Fogarty, director of
institutional equity sales at Nomura Securities International Inc.
``There is no momentum on the upside or on the downside.''
   Nationwide, consolidated volume in NYSE-listed issues, including
trading at regional exchanges and on the over-the-counter market,
totaled 141.58 million shares on Tuesday.
   Market analysts said new economic reports showing a 0.4 percent
rise in consumer prices in July and a 7 percent decline in durable
goods orders had been largely anticipated, and failed to provide
traders with much direction.
   The reports sparked a mild rally in the bond market, where
traders have been vigilant for signs of accelerating inflation
coupled with economic vigor.
   The price of the closely-watched 30-year Treasury bond was up
about $6 for every $1,000 in face value, as its yield fell to 9.38
percent from 9.45 percent late Monday.
   Blue-chip stock prices drifted higher for much of the morning,
while the rest of the market was mixed. But by mid-afternoon, even
the blue-chips gave up their gains.
   Thomas Czech, chairman of the investment committee at the
brokerage Blunt Ellis & Loewi in Milwaukee, said in failing to
follow the bond market higher, the stock market demonstrated it
``is nervous over too much growth and has been surprised for
several months now as to how strong things are.''
   Dean A. Gulis, director of reserach for the brokerage Roney &
Co. in Detroit, said the low volume indicates ``there is apathy and
fear on the part of investors generally.''
   Wickes was the second most actively-traded issue on the NYSE,
slipping [ to 13[. A management group has proposed buying the
company for $12 a share.
   Among other actively-traded issues on the NYSE, Coca Cola rose |
to 39[, General Electric was unchanged at 39[ and International
Business Machines rose [ to 110~.
   Clorox rose 2[ to 31| on speculation that a West German company
that already owns a stake in Clorox may be buying more.
   Deere rose 1[ to 42| after the farm-equipment maker reported its
earnings tripled in the quarter ended July 31 despite the drought.
   In over-the-counter trading, Farmers Group climbed 2{ to 69} on
speculation that it may drop its resistance to B.A.T. Industries,
which has proposed a buyout at $72 a share.
   The Wilshire Associates Equity Index, the market value of NYSE,
American and OTC issues, fell $2.236 billion, or 0.09 percent, to
$2.574 trillion.
   Standard & Poor's industrial index rose 0.10 to 294.59, and
S&P's 500-stock composite index edged up 0.11 to 257.09.
   At the American Stock Exchange, the market value index fell 1.01
to 292.00. The NASDAQ composite index for the over-the-counter
market closed at 373.53, down 0.20.
</TEXT>
