<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Jaguar     08-23 0266</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Jaguar,0277</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Luxury Automaker Eliminating 1,200 Jobs</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Jaguar PLC, the British luxury car maker, plans to
eliminate about 1,200 jobs over the next three years in a bid to
increase efficiency, the company said Tuesday.
   The move is part of Jaguar's efforts to match the efficiency
levels of West German competitors, Bayerische Motorenwerke AG,
maker of BMW cars, and Daimler-Benz AG, maker of Mercedes cars, a
company official said.
   Jaguar said the reduction in its manual-labor workforce from
12,500 workers to around 11,300 will be achieved by attrition,
rather than layoffs.
   ``Through natural wastage we lose around 400 workers a year,''
said the official, who spoke on condition of anonymity. ``To reach
our workforce target we simply won't replace those who leave.''
   The official said Jaguar's West German competitors produce about
six cars for each worker annually, compared with just over four
cars a worker at Jaguar.
   ``By slimming our workforce and by continuing to invest in
advanced manufacturing processes we intend to catch up,'' he said.
   A spokesman for the Transport and General Workers Union, which
represents most Jaguar workers, said unions had been involved in
negotiations over the manpower reduction proposals and were ``glad
that there wouldn't be redundancies.''
   As part of a two-year pay package negotiated last year with
hourly workers, Jaguar intends to speed up production at its plants.
   Workers at its big Coventry assembly plant in the English
midlands first resisted the new productivity levels as unrealistic
but later accepted the targets.
   Jaguar's new production target is 54,000 cars in 1988, compared
with 48,020 cars in 1987.
</TEXT>
