<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Britain-Unemployment     08-23 0173</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Britain-Unemployment,0180</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Long-term Jobless Falls Under One Million</HEAD>
<DATELINE>LONDON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Long-term unemployment has fallen below the 1
million mark for the first time in more than five years, the
government said Tuesday.
   The number of people out of work for longer than 12 months
dropped to 948,000 in the second quarter of 1988, the Department of
Employment said.
   That was a drop of 81,000 from the first three months of the
year and 290,000 from the same period of 1987, the department said.
   Employment Secretary Norman Fowler said there were particularly
sharp drops in long-term unemployment among the young, which fell
by 36 percent from a year ago and by 47 percent over the past two
years.
   He said the long-term jobless benefited from a sustained fall in
unemployment since the summer of 1986, and from a new employment
training program which was designed to equip people with the skills
necessary to fill Britain's 700,000 vacant jobs.
   Britain had an unemployment rate of 8.2 percent in July, or 2.31
million people.
</TEXT>
