<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Interco     08-23 0268</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Interco,0279</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Interco Files Suits Against Companies In Takeover Bid</HEAD>
<DATELINE>ST. LOUIS (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Interco Inc. filed suit in federal court
Tuesday accusing groups led by the Rales brothers with violating
securities laws in their $2.7 billion bid for the retailing concern.
   The suit, filed against Cardinal Acquisition Corp. and City
Capital Associates L.P., claims their outstanding $70-a-share
tender offer involves so much debt and so little equity that it
would, if consummated, violate SEC margin regulations.
   The suit also alleges that the defendants failed to disclose
that the takeover bid was being made on behalf of, among others,
Drexel Burnham Lambert Inc. and Chase Manhattan Bank, both of which
have equity stakes in Cardinal Acquisition.
   Because the defendants ``have concealed critical facts about
their unlawful conduct, the roles of Drexel Burnham and Chase
Manhattan, and their proposed takeover of Interco,'' the suit
contends, ``Interco's stockholders and the investing public are
being deprived of material information.''
   The suit said shareholders are being forced to make decisions in
a market ``distorted by defendants' illegal conduct and false and
misleading statements.''
   St. Louis-based Interco has rejected the Rales' overtures since
they first offered to acquire the company for $64 a share last
month. The group is led by Steven and Mitchell Rales of Washington,
D.C.
   Earlier Tuesday, Harvey Saligman, Interco's chairman and chief
executive officer, urged shareholders not to tender their shares to
an offer he called financially inadequate.
   Interco manufactures men's and women's apparel, footwear,
furniture and home furnishings. Some of its brand names include
London Fog clothing, Florsheim and Converse shoes and Broyhill and
Ethan Allen furniture.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
