<HEAD>Stock Jumps in Heavy Trading; German Company's Interest Cited</HEAD>
<DATELINE>OAKLAND, Calif. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Clorox Co.'s stock rose in heavy trading
Tuesday amid speculation a West German company and large
shareholder had increased their holdings in the diversified
consumer products giant.
   The company's stock jumped $2.125 to close at $31.625 a share on
an extraordinarily high volume of 1.1 million shares on the New
York Stock Exchange.
   A Clorox spokesman said the company was unaware of any potential
takeover attempt.
   ``We're not aware of the reason behind today's heavy trading,''
said Fred Reicker, director of corporate communications. ``Some of
the people we have talked to have speculated that the Henkel
organization has been buying more shares.''
   Henkel Corp. of West Germany, which has had a cooperative
agreement with Clorox since 1974, announced in March 1987 that it
intended to increase it Clorox holdings to 30 percent, the maximum
allowed under a pact between the two.
   Henkel bought more stock last week and currently owns 26.6
percent of Clorox's shares, according to Reicker.
   Industry observers said stock speculators may also have bought
Clorox shares Tuesday following initial purchases by Henkel, trying
to stage a market rally to drive the stock price higher.
   On Aug. 9, Clorox reported a 26 percent increase in its annual
earnings, attributing the strong performance primarily to a lower
corporate tax rate.
   Clorox is a large, diversified company whose major product is
bleach.
