<HEAD>Southern Travel Magazine To Be Sold to Time Inc. Unit</HEAD>
<DATELINE>NEW YORK (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Southern Progress Corp., an Alabama-based
subsidiary of Time Inc., has agreed in principle to buy Southern
Travel magazine from the New York Times Co. Magazine Group, the
companies announced Tuesday.
   Terms weren't disclosed.
   The New York Times Co. Magazine Group said it acquired the
magazine, then known as Travel South, in 1986 and renamed it
Southern Travel.
   It was published twice in 1987 and four times this year. Its
circulation has grown to 210,000 from 165,000, the Times said in a
statement.
   William Kerr, president of the Times magazine group, said his
company was pleased with the magazine's progress but that the
group's managers wanted to focus on their sports-leisure and
women's service publications that include Family Circle, Golf
Digest, Tennis and Decorating Remodeling.
   Don Logan, chief executive of Southern Progress, said Southern
Travel will complement another of the company's magazines, Southern
Living, in tapping the growing travel market.
   Southern Progress, based in Birmingham, Ala., also publishes
Southern Accents, Progressive Farmer and Cooking Light magazines.
