<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Revco     08-23 0239</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Revco,0247</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Bankruptcy Judge Approves Revco Credit Arrangement</HEAD>
<DATELINE>AKRON, Ohio (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A federal bankruptcy judge Tuesday approved a
$145 million credit plan for Revco D.S. Inc., a drugstore chain
that sought protection from its creditors in court last month.
   ``We interpret this new credit facility as a strong vote of
confidence from our senior bank lenders and the court,'' said Revco
Chairman Boake A. Sells. ``Our stores are open. We have been
saying, `Revco is in business to stay.' We believe our banks are
saying the same thing.''
   Under the agreement approved by U.S. Bankruptcy Judge Harold F.
White, Wells Fargo Bank and Marine Midland Bank will be the lead
lenders extending the credit to Revco through Feb. 1, 1990.
   The new arrangement is expected to be finalized Sept. 8, Revco
said, and will replace a $50 million interim financing agreement by
Wells Fargo and Marine Midland since Aug. 3.
   Revco filed for Chapter 11 bankruptcy protection on July 28,
about a month after it failed to make an interest payment on about
$700 million in outstanding high-risk junk bonds used to finance
its 1986 $1.5 billion leveraged buyout.
   In a leveraged buyout a company is acquired largely through
borrowed funds repaid from a target company's profits or asset
sales.
   The Twinsburg, Ohio-based company sought protection from
creditors after talks with bondholders broke down, becoming the
largest company involved in a leveraged buyout to take such action.
</TEXT>
