<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 1929EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>u f AM-IMF-Brazil     08-23 0367</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-IMF-Brazil,0378</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>IMF Approves $1.4 Billion Loan for Brazil</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By CARL HARTMAN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>WASHINGTON (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   The International Monetary Fund approved a
$1.4 billion loan to Brazil on Tuesday, to go along with proposed
new lending of $5.2 billion from commercial banks, an IMF spokesman
said.
   The fund will disburse the new loan by installments through Feb.
28, 1990, so that the money can be cut off in case the fund decides
that Brazil's economy has not performed as promised.
   Brazil reportedly has promised to cut government spending by 22
percent, as an economic austerity condition such as those often
required by the IMF.
   The new loans will amount to less than the interest payments on
Brazil's existing debt of $121 billion, the largest in the Third
World. Last year, Brazil suspended interest payments on what it
owed to banks, but has begun them again this year.
   Finance Minister Mailson da Nobrega said in July that the
suspension has not been formally revoked, but might be once the
nation's 700 creditor banks joined in the new bank loan agreement.
He announced last week in New York that 95 percent of the total had
been committed.
   In addition to its mounting debts, the government of President
Jose Sarney has been struggling with inflation, which reached a
record 24.04 percent in July. One report has suggested that the
rate will reach 927 percent for the year, well above the level of
600 percent said to be the basis for the agreement between the
government, the IMF and the banks.
   The IMF spokesman, who insisted on anonymity, did not say how
soon the new loan would have to be repaid. Brazil will have 20
years to pay back the $5.2 billion from the banks, including an
eight-year grace period during which only interest will be due.
   On July 30, Brazil agreed in Paris with 13 creditor governments
to delay repayment of $5 billion of its $15 billion debt to them.
The rescheduled debts, which fall due between Jan. 1, 1987 and
March 31, 1990 were delayed for 10 years, with a five-year grace
period.
   Brazil has not been making payments on principal of its bank
debt, either.
</TEXT>
