<1ST_LINE>r f AM-Hildreth     08-23 0366</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>AM-Hildreth,0381</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Fallen Computer Whiz Indicted on 11 Counts of Felony Larceny</HEAD>
<BYLINE>By KEVIN GALVIN</BYLINE>
<BYLINE>Associated Press Writer</BYLINE>
<DATELINE>DEDHAM, Mass. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   A state grand jury indicted fallen computer
whiz Tex Zachary Hildreth on 11 counts of felony larceny Tuesday,
for allegedly bilking six investors out of more than $500,000 to
keep his failing company in operation.
   Hildreth, 24, fled the state and apparently tried to commit
suicide with his mother in a New Hampshire hotel after creditors
and authorities seized his Massdata Corp. in May.
   Mike McGorty, spokesman for Norfolk County District Attorney
William Delahunt, said Hildreth apparently solicited the money to
pay off other investors and some bank notes.
   Hildreth orchestrated ``various financial deals where he
promised investors substantial returns,'' McGorty said. ``The money
is still outstanding.''
   Hildreth also was charged with using falsified documents to
obtain bank loans, McGorty said.
   Each of the 11 counts in the indictment carries a maximum
penalty of five years in prison or a $25,000 fine and two years in
prison, McGorty said.
   During a two-month period, the grand jury heard testimony from
more than 50 witnesses, McGorty said, and an investigation was
continuing.
   Hildreth is scheduled to be arraigned Wednesday in Norfolk
Superior Court. His attorney did not return telephone calls made by
The Associated Press after business hours Tuesday.
   Hildrethbought his first computer at age 16 and, with the help
of a mentor, rented office space to start his own software firm at
age 20. He quickly surrounded himself with symbols of success,
including a $220,000 Weymouth condominium, a $32,000 BMW, and a
50-inch, $4,000 color TV.
   Massdata was closed in May when Rockland Trust Co., which was
owed more than $400,000, tried to seize its assets.
   Hildreth and his mother, Rose, 50, fled Massachusetts after the
Braintree-based company was closed. They were captured shortly
afterward when an employee at a Manchester, N.H., motel called
police to report a bloodied man wandering in the lobby.
   Police found Hildreth, who apparently had slashed his wrists, in
the lobby. They found his mother lying in their hotel room and also
found a bottle of non-prescription pills in the room along with
what appeared to be suicide notes.
</TEXT>
