<DOCNO> AP880823-0260 </DOCNO>
<FILEID>AP-NR-08-23-88 2357EDT</FILEID>
<1ST_LINE>d f BC-Obit-Duffy     08-23 0157</1ST_LINE>
<2ND_LINE>BC-Obit-Duffy,0165</2ND_LINE>
<HEAD>Former USG Corp. Chief Dies At 68</HEAD>
<DATELINE>EVANSTON, Ill. (AP) </DATELINE>
<TEXT>
   Edward W. Duffy, who spent 40 years with
the USG Corp. and rose up the ranks to become its chairman, died
Monday at Evanston Hospital. He was 68.
   Duffy served as president of USG from 1971 to 1981, before he
was chosen as vice chairman of the company's board of directors. He
became chairman and chief executive officer in 1983 and retired in
1985.
   Duffy was born in Ottawa, Ill. in 1919 and joined USG, a
building materials and industrial processing company, in the 1940s
when it was known as U.S. Gypsum.
   Duffy began his career in the research department and in 1969
was elected to the board of directors and named executive vice
president of USG's building materials business.
   He is survived by his wife and daughter.
   Funeral services were scheduled for Friday in suburban Glenview,
with burial in nearby Des Plaines.
</TEXT>
</DOC>
